deck_description:
üß¨ Regenesis Centur-Ion Snake-Eye Deck Profile

 

üî• Deck Type: Combo / Control Hybrid

 

üéØ Format: Advanced (2025, TCG)

 

üåê Main Focus:

 

Use Centur-Ion’s Synchro recursion and boss monster setup

 

Enable strong extenders and disruption from Snake-Eye

 

Splash Regenesis and Unchained engines for mid-game recovery, board-breaking, and utility

 

Adapt to meta-heavy environments (Ryzeal, Kashtira, Malefic, Blue-Eyes) with a versatile Extra Deck toolbox

 

 

 

---

 

üß© Core Engines and Game Plan

 

üèõÔ∏è 1. Centur-Ion Engine (Main Strategy)

 

Centur-Ion is your Synchro control core. It focuses on summoning high-impact monsters like Legatia and Primera, while constantly resetting your board.

 

Key Cards:

 

üîπ Centur-Ion Primera – Your playstarter; summons and recurs other Centur-Ions.

 

üîπ Centur-Ion Trudea – Non-target, non-destruction removal.

 

üîπ Centur-Ion Emeth VI – Searches field spells and resets the grind.

 

üîπ Centur-Ion Legatia – Level 12 Synchro boss, recursion & protection.

 

 

Field Spells:

 

üîπ World Legacy Whispers – Negates monster effects.

 

üîπ World Legacy Secrets – Negates monster effects (used with Emeth VI).

 

üîπ Centur-Ion World – Buffs and stabilizes Centur-Ions.

 

 

 

---

 

üêç 2. Snake-Eye Package (Extenders & Control Options)

 

Snake-Eye provides board presence and field manipulation while enabling quick Synchro/Link setups.

 

Key Cards:

 

üî∏ Snake-Eye Ash – Searches and facilitates additional summons.

 

üî∏ Snake-Eye Oak / Poplar – Help with continuous board presence.

 

üî∏ Original Diabellstar (optional splash) – Great synergy with Snake-Eye to get into Regenerations and field control.

 

 

 

---

 

‚ôªÔ∏è 3. Regenesis Engine (Toolbox & Recursion)

 

Not Fire Kings! These are the utility cards like Regenesis Genesis Field (if running it), or similar "regeneration" or recursion-based tools. This engine powers resource loops and allows you to recycle lost pieces.

 

Function:

 

Reuse discarded Synchro materials or Snake-Eye monsters.

 

Create loop setups with Centur-Ion for second-turn grind.

 

Boost mid-late game tempo after trading resources.

 

 

 

---

 

üî• 4. Unchained Mini-Engine (Optional)

 

This helps against boards you can't out easily or to bait out negates. Also fuels Link Climb.

 

Example Cards:

 

üî∏ Unchained Soul of Disaster

 

üî∏ Abominable Unchained Soul

 

üî∏ Escape of the Unchained (board pop synergy)

---

 

üí• Disruption & Utility (Hand Traps & Side Options)

 

Droll & Lock Bird / Ash Blossom / Ghost Belle – Meta-stoppers.

 

Effect Veiler – Synchro synergy + monster negation.

 

Nibiru / Gamma – Against swarming decks.

 

Evenly Matched / Dimensional Barrier – Blowout board wipes or floodgates.

 

Trap Trick – Access your backrow tech reliably.

 

 

 

---

 

üß† Playstyle Summary:

 

Turn Goal

 

1st Set up Centur-Ion Legatia + World Legacy + I:P Masquerena. Backed by traps and Snake-Eye.

2nd Break board with Unchained/Snake-Eye. Climb into Accesscode/Unicorn. Synchro climb if needed.

Grind Regenesis and Emeth VI provide longevity. Keep generating advantage through loops.

 

 

 

---

 

‚úÖ Why This Deck Works Now

 

Synchro toolbox adapts to any game state.

 

Centur-Ion is one of the most consistent Synchro lines in modern formats.

 

Snake-Eye gives strong early-game and recovery.

 

Regenesis and World Legacy spells/traps give you a midgame edge.

 

Hard to out boss monsters + multiple win paths (Synchro, Link, grind).

 

 

 

---

deck_excerpt: Using Resonators to build a great board with Red Dragon Archfiend and potentially into Red Supernova Dragon
deck_description: Using Resonators to build a great board with Red Dragon Archfiend and potentially into Red Supernova Dragon
Una historia de dos hermanas llena de maldiciones, tragedia, serpientes y venganza
Without Ulcanix this deck is like 80 bucks

The set The Perpetual Maze is a Selection Pack, released on June 4th, 2025. MASTER DUEL - HOW TO PLAY! COMBO RYU-GE SWORDSOUL DECK - NEW SELECTION PACK: THE PERPETUAL MAZE. Hopefully this video will help everyone build and play decks more easily. Below is the deck profile for everyone to refer to.

This deck needs no introductions. For the past few formats, it has been a highly consistent deck to compete against the meta. From being the reason Hot Red Dragon Archfiend King Calamity got sent to the shadow realm, to being able to play under the Mulcharmy Cards AND Droll & Lock Bird , Centur-ions find themselves an very niche this format as well. While on the surface, it might seem like a strategy that fails to compete against the likes of Ryzeal, Mitsurugi and even Maliss, well timed applications of the card and the engines in this deck can put up a fight that would give any of the archtypes I mentioned a reason to fail. 

 

Main Combos

  1. Opening: Centur-Ion Trudea - this is one of the main starters in terms of the openers for the deck, not the most optimal, but it can get you where you need to be. She forces the player to open with a normal summon, then using her effect to place herself and any other another Centur-Ion monster from the Hand or MD to the S/T Zone as a Continuious Trap, normally we would choose to place Centur-Ion Primera , then you use Centur-Ion Primera to SS herself from the S/T Zone to your side of the field, which would trigger her on-summon effect, to grab any Centur-Ion card from deck to the hand. If you don't already have a copy of Wake Up Centur-Ion! in your hand, this will be the optimal time to add the card, even thought you may be tempted to add the field spell, do not. Activate Wake Up Centur-Ion! , since you have a Centur-Ion monster in the S/T Zone, you get to SS a token with either LV 4 or LV 8. Optimally, for recursion, SS as a Level 4. Once this is done, Synchro Summon the monster and token for the LV 8 Synchro Centur-Ion Primera Primus , which will add you an Emblema card from Deck or GY to your hand, here you will grab Emblema Oath , then activate it and (if you do not have Centur-Ion Atrii in hannd already) choose to place a Centur-Ion monster face-up in the S/T Zone and place Centur-Ion Atrii (NOTE: Once a Centur-Ion Atrii remains face-up on field during the turn you activate this, you will be locked into only SS Centur-Ion monsters from the ED). Activate Centur-Ion Atrii and SS her from the S/T Zone, then use her on summon effect to Draw a card and then you CAN destroy 2 cards on field, one you control and one the opponent controls. After this, Synchro Summon using Centur-Ion Atrii and Centur-Ion Primera Primus for Centur-Ion Auxila (if you are going 1st or need to search a specific engine piece) or Centur-Ion Legatia (if you are going 2nd or just want additional non-engine resources). Use Wake Up Centur-Ion! in GY, banishing itself to send a Centur-Ion card from deck to GY, you would normally send Centur-Ion Phalanx to recur a Synchro Centruion monster (useful if you get hit with a nibiru). if you have more bodies and can continue to play, do so in a manner that gives you an edge. DO NOT FORGET THE EFFECT OF THE LEVEL 12 CENTUR-ION SUNCHROS AT THE EP TO PLACE ANY CENTUR-ION MONSTER FROM GY OR BANISH ZONE, FACE UP IN THE S/T ZONE.
  2. Opening: Stand Up Centur-Ion! - this is the ideal opener for the deck. Start by activating Stand Up Centur-Ion! , use it's effect the turn it was activated to send a card from hand and then place any Centur-Ion monster from deck, face up in the S/T Zone, normally you would choose to grab Centur-Ion Trudea , from here, the combo remains the same as Combo 1. 
  3. Opening: Emblema Oath - this is similar to opening Stand Up Centur-Ion! , you normally choose to set a Centur-Ion Spell facedown which would be Stand Up Centur-Ion! , although if you already have the field spell in hand, you are free to choose. If you choose to place the field spell, the combo follows the line of combo 1 and 2, until you have to SS the token, since choosing to Synchro Lv 8, you WILL get to add the Emblema Card from deck or GY to hand, but since Emblema Oath is once per turn, it woul be ideal to SS the token as a LV 8, and Synchro into a Level 12 directly, specifically Centur-Ion Auxila (searching either Centur-Ion Bonds (to place a body in the S/T Zone from the hand or GY) or Centur-Ion Atrii to Normal summon and get an additional draw, this all depends on your preference or hand) or Centur-Ion Legatia (if goinf 2nd and need to move a card that is giving you difficulty).
  4. Opening: Centur-Ion Primera - this is normally a card you don't really object to opening with as the only starter, but in formats where Droll & Lock Bird is going around, and opening this as the only starter means you will definitely need to be adding cards to build or break a board, it is not the most optimal. Although, if this is the had you are given, make the most of it. Since this will be you NS, use the effect on Summon to add Stand Up Centur-Ion! to hand (if you get drolled, pray there is no more HT to follow). Then activate Stand Up Centur-Ion! and use the effect to place Centur-Ion Trudea in the S/T Zone from deck. SS Centur-Ion Trudea from S/T Zone as a Lv4. Attempt to place Centur-Ion Trudea back into the S/T zone and place another Centur-Ion monster in the S/T zone with it. Normally the choice is based on what you want your endboard to be, Centur-Ion Gargoyle II is the best option here as it can also modulate it's level and recur itself back into the hand from the GY once used as a synchro material. Remember, in this comboline, you already have a non-tuner Centur-Ion in the S/T Faceup, so you will need to be able to add a tuner Centur-Ion that can SS itself during the opponent's MP. If you opted to Place Centur-Ion Gargoyle II , then SS it as a Lv8 and Synchro Summon using it and Centur-Ion Primera for Centur-Ion Auxila , which will protect all S/T face up on the field. In the EP, place Centur-Ion Primera in the S/P Zone and use them to make either a Crimson Dragon or Centur-Ion Auxila based on the situation. Crimson Dragon is normally a better choice as it can bring and other Synchro 12 from your ED.

Notes/Rulings

  1. This deck can be played in a minimal combo way, to avoid Nibiru, the Primal Being and set up to play in the opponent's turn.
  2. The Bystials help to give the Centur-Ions an extra push to do some unorthodox plays that can catch opponents off guard.
  3. Any Centurion MD Monster + Lv6 Bystial gives you Chaos Angel or Bystial Dis Pater.
  4. Any Hand Trap + Level 8 (except Centur-Ion Primera Primus ) give you access to Psychic End Punisher 
  5. All Level 12 Centur-Ion Synchros places a Centur-Ion monster from the GY or Banish Zone in the S/T Zone during EITHER player's EP.
  6. Crimson Dragon's effect to add a S/T from deck to hand is an on summon effect, the effect to tag out into another synchro monster is a Quick Effect.
  7. Stand Up Centur-Ion!'s effect to Synchro Summon does not only trigger when you SS a monster, but also if your Opponent SS a monster. And it does not need to use only Centurion Monster or the Monster that SS to trigger the effect. 
  8. Red Supernova Dragon does not banish itself for cost. If it is moved from the field before it can  resolve, the other card on the opponent's field will get banished, but it will not return during your next EP. Also, if you use this effect in your turn and it leave the field by it's own effect, it WILL SS itself back to the field during that same EP. This is not an activated effect, but unlike SP, and can trigger some effects.
  9. Blue-Eyes Ultimate Spirit Dragon can SS from the GY, Centur-Ion Auxila or Crimson Dragon from the GY if either of them were Synchro Summoned and then sent to the GY.
  10. Monsters summoned with the effect of Crimson Dragon are considered Synchro Summoned and can return to the field from GY/Banish if sent there from field.
  11. Powersink Stone counts each time monster effects are activated by BOTH players in the turn and will affect both players once the first 2 monster effects resolves (anywhere). If there is a chain 5 with all of the links being monsters, when the chain is resolving, chain 5 will give a counter to Powersink Stone and chain 4 wil give the second counter to Powersink Stone , after that, if the other monster in the remaining chain links are on the field, their effect become negated. While Powersink Stone is in effect, neither player can attempt to activate monster effects on the field, example; Powersink Stone is live and the opponent has Haggard Lizardose on field, the would not be able to banish for cost using Haggard Lizardose effect, then have it resolve negated.
  12. If during the EP, after Powersink Stone has removed its counters, 2 monster effects are activated, on resoloution, new counters will be placed on Powersink Stone and they will not be removed after, since removing the counters can only happen ONCE PER TURN. The counters will remain on Powersink Stone until the EP of the next turn, or if the card leaves the field.
  13. Centur-Ion Phalanx is a trap card, hence, it's effect in the GY can be activated during the opponent's turn.

deck_description:
Dino Control 2025 GOAT

The best Dinosaur build of all the variants I'm trying out

Stay tuned for Dino deck #3 some time in the future

Yu-Gi-Oh Tabletop Format - Merlantean Abyss

Yu-Gi-Oh Tabletop Format (YGOT) is a format that infuses the combos and strategies of the modern YGO meta with the pace of play of earlier YGO by adapting the TCG to a 9 x 9 grid-based game board format where the player pilots an "avacard" (a designated link monster listed in the side deck) across the game board to eliminate the opponent's life points or capture the opposing players' avacard, summoning monsters and setting spells and traps along the way. This format is compatible for 2-4 players.

This deck built from the Atlantean and Mermail archetypes is a starting point to understand the format and should not be considered competitive-focused. It primarily focuses on bringing out your XYZ monsters and swarming the field with monsters while also recycling them to your deck and hand, often with high risk, high reward tactics. Worldsea Dragon Zealantis is the avacard.

More information, including a link to the rulebook for the format, is forthcoming.

deck_excerpt: Domain Format: Budget Structure Deck Amplified
deck_description:
Endless Bodies, Strategic Destruction.
This is a beginner-friendly Domain Format list built upon a $9.99 MSRP purchase of the Structure Deck: Sacred Beasts. It consists of a $20 upgrade of cards purchased from sites like TCGplayer.
(I blame Unchained Soul Lord of Yama for eating 1/4 OF THE BUDGET)

Deckmaster: Dark Beckoning Beast 
Domain Restrictions: DARK // FIEND
Made for Domain Format: Join the Community Discord!

To create this upgrade, please remove these 11 cards and any duplicate cards from the SD: Sacred Beasts (reference the sidedeck): 
Note: Please also remove the 2 included Phantom Tokens

  • ydke://LsnvAZdzKgR0L7UBZ6u7BK2pWwDMN+MFaIi1AdJz1gUlXHgCg4I9BRVY9wDHvMUAqYfOAaSXOANje9QEsLKiASWfRAPheMkE+TLFAIf4ygDUGgQAKfJQBZAGIwCQf44FPw0aAll7YwRGSGQE7ydRALsKYQSLajMDok+KAAZs4QHU+vgA!gOWVAoapsAU=!KlHOAGfCLQLYxvAES6rhAieO2QHaJW0AbkpvBNlSlAD2hZgAee6IA6BSfQU=!
  • View on YGOprodeck
  • Structure Deck Full Contents (YGOprodeck)

Next, you will want to buy and add these 39 cards to the deck: 

  • ydke://U+xIAODxaQVB2qsEZgEeAA70lAKfm2kFJ/o2BLjEKgMHJHQCxDtHBcExnwNWzx4DkFaQAQ//8QU6upoCcYFxAZLptgOCS7kF/byFBVXO4wMN9QwBPkiiATijNwXP79AE3xYvA2hesQJeHkoC+5oxAw==!hjiVAxhvrQEK9sYC6Py9BP7j7AFh0cEBiVRyAQC5CAR77PgCt95HBKKjRAS/DkkC!!
  • View on YGOprodeck
  • View on TCGplayer Cart

Additional Resources can be found here:
https://docs.google.com/spreadsheets/d/1c8_W7TLHoExz9Iq2yNBKG4kniKN3fjamfMVRehPRitQ/edit?usp=sharing

Domain Format General Rules:

  • Singleton Format: Every card restricted to 1 copy per deck.
  • 60-card Format: Each Main Deck must contain exactly 60 cards.
  • 4-player Pods: Each player competes individually in an all-out battle against three opponents.
  • Deckmaster Restrictions: Each player chooses a "Deckmaster" which dictates the allowed types and attributes for their deck.
  • Deckmaster Contract: A Deckmaster can be summoned from a designated "Deckmaster Zone" using normal summoning rules. After switching zones, Deckmasters may return to the "Deckmaster Zone," where they start the game.

Refer here for additional rules and exceptions:

https://www.domainformat.com/rules 

Broad Categories

This simple strategy has cards that fall into three simple categories:

  • Self-Destruction
  • Big Attack 
  • Field Swarming

Primary Packages: Sacred Beasts, Yubel, Unchained

Reccommend Sacred Beasts Guides (from Jesse Kotton and Revz Cards):

  • https://youtu.be/Ul_4K--3dv8?si=CoqURxyJtD_C1YHw
  • https://youtu.be/t99kE2M5lvU 

Reccommened Yubel Guides (from Gnurrgard and PhantomsYGO):

  • https://youtu.be/_jt5LLTfN9Q 
  • https://youtu.be/CvJGhAEMxaw?si=W0px_fdC1WsbmfH5 

What do we want our Deckmaster to do? Dark Beckoning Beast 
- Combo Starter
- Find Sacred Beast Spell/Traps
- Additional Normal Summon 

A fantastic Normal Summon for the strategy, Dark Beckoning Beast allows the deck to easily put monsters on the field for out Link-Summoning plays through its search ability and additional normal summon. The most important card to search is Opening of the Spirit Gates, which not only provides another search, and revive a fiend, but also gives us the ability to recur a continous spell from our GY. 
From only the Normal Summon of Dark Beckoning Beast and 2 discards, we will be able to set up a full field of a Negate, a Negate , a Disruption , and lastly a Destruction. 

You may also choose to access the Sacred Beast combo lines with Dark Beckoning Beast, which will be able to set up 1-2 Sacred Beasts on the field. The important card to search using Dark Beckoning Beast for this combo would be the Dark Summoning Beast to summon a Sacred Beast straight from deck. 
If you wish to summon out the Fusion Armityle the Chaos Phantasm - Phantom of Fury instead, it can be done by sending all the Sacred Beasts to GY using Chaos Core (use Unchained Soul of Sharvara to target it, searched by Unchained Soul Lord of Yama) and then fuse the Armityle the Chaos Phantasm - Phantom of Fury by using Fiendsmith's Sequence to shuffle back all the Sacred Beasts to deck.  

Dark Beckoning Beast can add: 

  • Opening of the Spirit Gates 
  • Awakening of the Sacred Beasts 
  • Phantasmal Martyrs
  • Dimension Fusion Destruction  
  • Fallen Paradise 
  • Chaos Summoning Beast / Phantasmal Summoning Beast / Dark Summoning Beast 
  • Cerulean Skyfire / Hyper Blaze 

Please remember that the additional normal summon provided by Dark Beckoning Beast can be used on any Fiend monster with 0 Atk /0 Def, regardless of its Level. 

Self-Destruction 
- Destroy Spirit of Yubel over and over and over...
- Destroy Unchained cards to summon monsters! 
- Trigger Unchained Soul Lord of Yama

Spirit of Yubel has no once-per-turn on its ability to summon out a Yubel  if it is destroyed. This lack of once-per-turn can be leveraged by destroying it using Nightmare Pain and our various Unchained cards, all while generating monster advantage. You always want to be destroying Spirit of Yubel if there is any card that requires a card of ours to be destroyed. If you happen to not have Spirit of Yubel on the field, please check the GY to see if you can use Gruesome Grave Squirmer GY effect to revive Spirit of Yubel. These Yubel cards - Spirit of Yubel , Yubel , Yubel - Terror Incarnate , Yubel - The Ultimate Nightmare - all allow us to easily generate monsters on the field so long as are destroying them. 

The primary entry point to accessing Spirit of Yubel is Samsara D Lotus. Samsara D Lotus can be revived from GY by Opening of the Spirit Gates or Muckraker From the Underworld once it is sent to GY using Aerial Eater. 

Spirit of Yubel can add:

  • Nightmare Pain 
  • Eternal Favorite 
  • Mature Chronicle 

The ability to benefit off destruction of our cards also allows this deck to play better into disruptions that destroy our cards, because we will then be able to profit off that destruction. (However this only applies to monster destruction and not Spell/Trap Destruction)

Field Swarming
- Make sure you can summon your Moon of the Closed Heaven and Unchained Soul Lord of Yama 
- Use Spirit of Yubel and Opening of the Spirit Gates to get many monsters
- Link Summon using your swarm of monsters

The Fiend Extra Deck is extremely generic, which allows us to easily pivot any monster we obtain into advantage. Our Deckmaster Dark Beckoning Beast is fantastic in its ability to put 2 dark fiends on the field with only one Normal Summon. Opening of the Spirit Gates is also fantastic for its ability to revive a fiend monster from GY. 

In particuar, we want to summon out Moon of the Closed Heaven in order to gain access to Fiendsmith's Sequence. This is because the easiest way to find Samsara D Lotus, and by extention the Yubel archetype, is by using Fiendsmith's Sequence to summon Aerial Eater to send Samsara D Lotus to GY. 
Because Moon of the Closed Heaven can use any effect monster as material, we play Danger! monsters as additional extension.

When we have Fiend monsters, we are able to easily create an Unchained Soul Lord of Yama. This is the primary point of access for the Unchained engine. The most important endpiece of the Unchained engine is Unchained Soul of Rage , which can be easily made if we add Unchained Soul of Sharvara using Unchained Soul Lord of Yama.  

In the cases of Grind Games, please remember that Opening of the Spirit Gates can add back a Continous Spell from GY, and that Awakening of the Sacred Beasts can add back a Continous Trap from GY.

Big Attack 
- Use the Big 4000 ATK of Raviel, Lord of Phantasms and Hamon, Lord of Striking Thunder!
- Reflect battle damage through Nightmare Pain!  

While all of the monsters in the Yubel archetype have 0 ATK / 0 DEF , the battle damage redirection ability of Nightmare Pain allows the deck to easily OTK given our opponents have highly statted monsters. Additionally, because our opponents are forced by Nightmare Pain to attack into Yubel monsters, they sometimes will have no choice but to die by their hubris! 

Attack Power is where the Sacred Beasts shine the most. In addition to  Raviel, Lord of Phantasms and Hamon, Lord of Striking Thunder each holding a respectable 4000 ATK, their fusion monster Armityle the Chaos Phantasm gains 10000 ATK (during our turn only)! The "dificulty" lies in summoning these monsters, however we are fortunate in that we never have to summon them using their own ridiculous conditions. Due to Phantasmal Summoning Beast and Dark Summoning Beast, we can directly IGNORE their summoning conditions AND summon them from Deck! Both of the Summoning Beast can be searched using our deckmaster Dark Beckoning Beast. 

Summoning out the 10000 ATK Armityle the Chaos Phantasm is similarly easy. By using Chaos Core (searchable through our deckmaster Dark Beckoning Beast), we can send all the required Sacred Beast Fusion Materials to GY, and summon out Armityle the Chaos Phantasm through the fusion effect of Fiendsmith's Sequence by shuffling the Materials back into Deck! 

If the Sacred Beasts high attack power does not end the game, use of their continous trap Awakening of the Sacred Beasts most definetly will bring victory closer. This powerful trap has effects that scale based on the number of Sacred Beasts controled, and is the primary endboard piece for the Sacred Beast strategy. 

Other Considerations: 

Monsters: Tour Guide From the Underworld , Borrelsword Dragon , Santa Claws , Diabellstar the Black Witch , Lady Labrynth of the Silver Castle , The Winged Dragon of Ra - Sphere Mode , D/D/D Vice King Requiem ( + Dark Contract with the Gate ),  Danger! Mothman! 

Extra Deck: Goblin Bikers Gone Bonkers , Super Starslayer TY-PHON - Sky Crisis ,  Goblin's Crazy Beast , D/D/D Stone King Darius , Promethean Princess, Bestower of Flames + Knightmare Phoenix , Knightmare Mermaid , Relinquished Anima , Unchained Soul of Anguish , Predaplant Verte Anaconda , Topologic Bomber Dragon / Topologic Trisbaena / Topologic Zeroboros 

Spell/Trap: Soul Demolition , Farewelcome Labrynth , Fiendsmith's Sanct , Foolish Burial , Titanocider , Monster Reborn , Change of Heart / Snatch Steal , Torrential Tribute , Heavy Storm / Twin Twisters , Gigantic Thundercross 

Removed from Deck: 
Monsters: Lady Labrynth of the Silver Castle , Tour Guide From the Underworld , Danger! Mothman! 
Extra Deck: Super Starslayer TY-PHON - Sky Crisis , Predaplant Verte Anaconda , Borrelsword Dragon , Goblin Bikers Gone Bonkers , Unchained Soul of Anguish
Spell/Traps: Torrential Tribute , Fiendsmith's Sanct , Soul Demolition ,  Farewelcome Labrynth , Gigantic Thundercross 

To Recap

Important Cards: Opening of the Spirit Gates , Unchained Soul of Rage , Spirit of Yubel , Awakening of the Sacred Beasts 
Strategy Elevator Pitch: Endless Destruction and Rebirth. 

Best Non-Budget Upgrades: Phantom of Yubel , Nightmare Throne , Fiendsmith's Requiem , Super Polymerization + Yubel - The Loving Defender Forever, Varudras, the Final Bringer of the End Times , A Bao A Qu, the Lightless Shadow 

Unleash the Cycle: Destroy. Float. Link. Dominate.

deck_excerpt: Remember when Halqifibrax was the face of synchro and the degen decks it brought into existence? Now imagine that guy as an entire deck!
deck_description:
Remember when Halqifibrax was the face of synchro and the degenerate decks it brought into existence? Now imagine that guy as an entire archetype!
 
The busted Crystron support from the latest Masterduel Selection Pack "Perpetual Maze" renders the strategy worthy of competitive ladder! These water attribute robots get a consistency powerboost in the form of 5 cards - Inclusion, Cluster, Suldafor, Tristaros and Eleskeletus Crystron surprisingly goes toe to toe with top decks like Blue-Eyes, Branded and Fiendsmith variants and can grind them out in an extended duel. The deck is now consistent enough to jam in about 20 staples, it has a ton of inherent gas, and by nature of how Crystrons combo many common handtraps don't effect them much. They can weave and make plays through powerful lingering handtraps like Shifter, Mulcharmies Droll and Nibiru - and of course, minor handtraps like Veiler, Ash Blossom and Imperm get shrugged off. 
 
The Horus engine also grants Crystron extra plays, protection and beatsticks as well, giving them a significant buff!
 
Crystron is a difficult deck to play because of all the combo lines for each sort of gamestate, so it rewards a highly skilled pilot. If you're looking for a powerful midrange deck that catches duelists off-guard on ladder with weird combo lines, I highly recommend playing Crystron!

ARCHETYPES AND DECKBUILDING
 
The CRYSTRON cards form the foundation of this deck, and it is a strategy that turbos out tuners that enable it to make quick-synchro plays during your opponent's turn. The Crystron deck core is fairly compact, consisting of 17 cards. 
 
The 3-ofs in the deck are Inclusion (searches any Crystron card) and Smiger (searches spell/trap, basically Inclusion) since they are both 1-card combos that get you your full board and GY set-up. Sulfefnir is a 3-of as well since it is a important combo piece that replaces itself (just like Kashtira Fenrir)! 
 
2-of Tristaros are used since it is the key piece of the deck which allows synchro summoning during your opponent's turn, and can summon 2 Crystrons at once from your deck. It is this deck's best normal summon, since if your opponent does something, it can react to it to immediately and synchro summon. This number can be bumped up to 3 if you like extra consistency. Sulfador is used at 2 as well since it's a double foolish burial! It's a highly searchable combo piece, but two is needed for an extended grind game. 
 
1-of of Prasiortle (extender that summons from hand) and Thystvern (searches monster) are used since they are highly searchable combo pieces, each with a certain specific use in different situations. 1 Cluster is used as this deck's ace trap card interruption, able to destroy an opponent's card by shuffling back Crystron cards from the GY or Banishment - giving the strategy potentially infinite grindgame!  
 
A tiny HORUS package of 5 cards. It makes the deck more powerful because it boosts consistency (The Zombie Vampire), provides protection (Galaxy-Eyes Photon Lord). The Horus monsters are fairly powerful themselves, bulldozing most threats off the board during the battlephase, especially with King Sarcophagus' removal. 
 
This Crystron decklist has 17 STAPLE cards! The standard "Maxx C" package is included as well as Crossout and it's targets. 1 Foolish Burial is added for consistency. 
 
COMBOS AND GAMEPLAN
 
In terms of interruption, the board that Crystron sets up is relatively straightforward. It ends on 1 targeted pop with Cluster, 1-2 spell/trap negates with F.A. Dawn Dragster and potentially triple monster banish from field/GY with Quariongandrax. Some hands can pivot into Cyber Dragon Infinity's omni-negate. 
 
Regarding execution of the Crystron strategy, it's fairly difficult to sequence interruption properly, especially if your opponent doesn't play into it. Crystron's gimmick is all about quick-synchroing during your opponent's turn, and those actions are only available during your opponent's Main Phase or Battle Phase. If you don't have proper synchro materials on-board or in GY, the quick synchros won't work, especially Quariongandrax which specifically requires two tuners. 
 
That being said, if you get handtrapped, you can generally still end on Cluster's targeted destruction and sit on your handtraps. Next turn, you can attempt to combo again with your set-up GY/Banishment. 
 
Here a regular 1 card opening for Crystron: 
 
Inclusion = Double F.A Dawn Dragster (x2 S/T negate), Crystron Quariongandrax (triple monster banish in-field/GY), Crystron Cluster (targeted pop), + follow-up for next turn. 
  1. Activate Inclusion to search for Sulfador. 
  2. Activate Sulfador targeting Inclusion to destroy it.
  3. On-summon, Sulfador sends to the GY Cluster and Thystvern. 
  4. Banish Thystvern in the GY to search for Tristallos. 
  5. Normal Summon Tristaros. 
  6. Synchro summon Eleskeletus using Tristaros + Sulfador.
  7. On-summon, Eleskeletus recovers Cluster from the GY. 
  8. Banish Tristaros from the GY to destroy Eleskeletus and summon Sulfefnir and Rosenix. 
  9. Activate Eleskeletus' trigger effect when destroyed to summon Tristaros from Banishment. 
  10. Activate Rosenix's effect to targeting Sulfefnir to destroy it and summon Citree from deck. 
  11. Activate Sulfefnir's effect to summon another Sulfefnir from deck. 
  12. Synchro summon F.A Dawn Dragster using Citree + Sulfefnir. 
  13. Banish Inclusion from the GY to summon Citree from the GY. 
  14. During your opponent's Main/Battle Phase, activate Citree to summon Sulfefnir from the GY to synchro summon a second F.A Dawn Dragster using Citree + Sulfefnir. 
  15. During your opponent's Main/Battle Phase, activate Cluster to target destroy 1 card your opponent controls by shuffling back Citree from Banishment. 
  16. During your opponent Main/Battle Phase, activate Tristaros summoning Citree from deck to synchro summon Quariongandrax using Tristaros + Citree + level 5 F.A. Dawn Dragster (level 5 since it negated earlier).

For your follow-up next turn, your GY, Hand and Banishment have enough starters and extenders to continue grinding the game out and possibly finish the game! 
 
Going first, you make decent board from 1 card while you have handtraps in hand while generating plenty of follow-up for next turn.
 
Going second, you weaken your opponent with the 16 handtraps/staples you have. Then Crystron cards can weave their way through interruption and handtraps when played properly!

This is only a basic combo for the deck, there are tons of 1-2 card combos Crystron can do. If you want more combos, feel free to check out Yacine656's or SuperNix's combo videos in Youtube!

GENERAL TIPS
  • Personally, I found that the hardest part of playing this deck is figuring out when to pull the trigger for your interruptions. Learning to properly sequence your interruptions, especially in the heat of the moment is difficult, so practice a lot! Otherwise, the deck is simple and straightforward to learn. 
  • The interruptions from Crystron is relatively minor compared to decks with bigger boards like Ryzeal and Maliss. The strength of Crystron comes from resilience through interruption and a robust grindgame. If you can force out a grindgame from your opponent with full Crystron set-up you have a high chance of winning. 
Want to see the deck in action? Scroll to the very bottom for the Youtube video!

GLHF Duelists!

deck_name: Meu Bom Campeao YCS Promissao - Epic Level
deck_excerpt: Meu Bom Campeao YCS Promissao - Epic Level
deck_description: Meu Bom Campeao YCS Promissao - Epic Level

deck_excerpt: "I summon blue eyes abyss dragon and have-"
We can finally do more than just Shenshen pass!
deck_description:
Strengths

The deck can very effectively kill a lot of Extra Deck-based strategies going first, including Ryzeal and Maliss (assuming you don't get hand trapped). Usually you can also kill Fusion and Synchro-based decks if you can properly resolve Ursarctic Polar Star (which happens more often than you'd think).

Unlike other Ursarctic builds, if you are stopped mid-combo, you might be able to pivot towards your Mitsurugi engine which does quite well in the grind game, through Futsu no Mitama no Mitsurugi's constant Special Summons from the Graveyard, a board wipe in Ame no Murakumo no Mitsurugi, and even an omni-negate through Mitsurugi Great Purification.

The Mitsurugi engine also provides some more benefits: the deck is slightly less vulnerable to the threat of Droll since Prayers is a Quick-Play Spell that you can activate during the Draw Phase, your Tributes actually do something now, Nibiru isn't as much of a threat as it used to be, and on top of that, it only needs one card to get started: any way to access Habakiri. 

Additionally, due to the Levels of the Mitsurugi monsters, we have access to Crimson Dragon and Ultimaya Tzolkin, additional extenders that you can utilize to access negates in Crystal Wing Synchro Dragon or Hot Red Dragon Archfiend Abyss. 

There's also some synergy in Ursarctic Grand Chariot and the Mitsurugi monsters - although resolving Grand Chariot's negation effect is unlikely. 

Weaknesses

The deck is still highly susceptible to Droll and will almost certainly just stop working. At most you might be able to get to Futsu and just go for a grind game.

The Mulcharmy cards are also absolutely devastating. Purulia and Fuwalos are serious threats to the Deck and there's barely a good way to play around it if you only draw into your Ursarctic cards.

It's also quite hard to get some of your resources back if they're banished. Dimension Shifter will technically not stop Kusanagi or any of the other Mitsurugi monsters' effects, sure, but it still hurts a lot as you can't get back those resources once they're banished.

The two engines also don't really "feed into each other" and often times you can actually just use one engine and leave the other out of the picture until you can actually use it later. Ursarctic technically has a way to maybe get to your Mitsurugi stuff through Ursarctic Radiation, but the chances are usually quite low. 

Also... you're still playing Ursarctic. All of the other threats that the deck suffers from are still present in some way. The deck is still quite susceptible to interruptions like Ash, Imperm, Veiler, Belle, Impulse, Purge, the list goes on. That's why our non-engine cards are meant to help break boards (Super Poly & Fenrir) OR stop those hand traps. You might think that we could just run 12 hand traps/staples, but Ursarctic's inconsistency and neediness for other cards (there's no 1 card combos) makes this kind of weird non-engine, in my opinion, kind of necessary.

Tips

  • Use your Ursarctic cards first if you have any of the necessary pieces to start the basic Mitsurugi combo. The Mitsurugi engine is much stronger, and baiting out common hand traps with the Ursarctic engine can allow you to give you some sort of board to work with.
  • Activate Mitsurugi Prayers during your Draw Phase in order to play around Droll - just a little, anyway. 
  • If you have a Habakiri, Mitsurugi Ritual, and an Ursarctic in hand, you can Tribute the Habakiri to add Murakumo - this can allow you to access Futsu.
  • Use Habakiri's effect to Special Summon (ideally Saji or Aramasa) BEFORE you Tribute it with an Ursarctic monster.
  • If you have nothing good to add to your hand off of your Mitsurugi cards, add Habakiri. It's a great tribute and can be used as discard fodder for some of your other cards if need be.
  • If you have a Level 4 Mitsurugi monster, a Level 7 Ursarctic, and also a Level 8 Ursarctic Tuner, Synchro Summon Crimson Dragon first, add Synchro Rumble, then revive your Ursarctic Tuner. If you control Crimson Dragon, avoid going into your Ursarctic Synchros unless absolutely necessary. Opt for a Synchro 9 so you can Special Summon Hot Red Dragon Archfiend Abyss. 
  • Shenshen is TERRIBLE unless you're playing against Mitsurugi or pretty much almost any other deck. Don't risk a bad Maliss matchup and opt for Wolfrayet (if you know what they're playing and it isn't Maliss then just opt for Shenshen)
  • Special Summon Fenrir before you do anything else. He's the best bait and utility card we have in the deck.
  • Avoid using Droll while your Mitsurugi cards are still live. If you don't want them to access certain cards, you have tools to stop that. 

Tech Options

  • Azamina Engine - A 6-card engine I heavily considered and tried out. Consisting of just 2 WANTED: Seeker of Sinful Spoils, 2 Diabellstar the Black Witch, 1 Deception of the Sinful Spoils, and 1 The Hallowed Azamina, it synergizes with the deck a little more than you'd think it would. Diabellstar can be used as material for Ursarctic plays, and Deception can Tribute a Mitsurugi monster to give you access to Hallowed. Another omni-negate doesn't hurt, after all. Downsides are losing some needed hand advantage due to Diabellstar, and also losing some quite valuable non-engine space. 
  • Diviner of the Herald - A great way to get to Polari with any other Level 7 monster AND search out Habakiri or Mitsurugi Ritual. While for a time I tried using the card, it is unfortunately really susceptible to Imperm and Veiler. I took it out after some testing with it, since I figured Diviner could have better been used as another Level 7 or higher Tribute that's guaranteed instead of just accessible.
  • Sakitama & Aratama - I'll be honest, I've never tried running these, but they could prove useful to help you go into King of the Feral Imps in order to begin your Mitsurugi plays (or just go into Bagooska if you get Drolled...). Downsides are that they can't be Tributed, and also the fact that the engine isn't exactly 
  • Vermillion Dragon Mech and Navy Dragon Mech - These are amazing going second cards, but I feel like the existing Extra Deck is fine as is - the Synchro 9s we have are relatively strong and should do the trick. 
  • Kuibelt the Blade Dragon - It's a pop that can be used on your opponent's turn with Crimson Dragon - I feel like the negate off of Hot Red Dragon Archfiend Abyss is a little better though.

That's all! If you have any ideas that'll help me improve the deck, let me know.

Nadir Servant is back to three, and more importantly, Branded Fusion is back up to semi-limited! This means that it's slightly more spashable as an engine in other decks, and I thought about testing it out in Voiceless Voice!

If Branded Fusion is accessed, Albaz and friends significantly strengthen the endboard of Voiceless Voice with Mirrorjade's banish and Sanctifire's GY disruption. You don't even have to hard draw Branded Fusion to get Mirrorjade out, Voiceless Voice also sometimes has extra link material on field to make Verte Anaconda! From there you can make Sanctifire, then during your opponent's turn you can make Mirrorjade! Branded Fusion also can send to the GY important light combo pieces like Saffira or Trias Hierachia so you can get your Voiceless Voice gameplan going. 

Otherwise, this strategy functions like the usual Voiceless Voice deck. 

GLHF Duelists! 

Want to see the deck in action? Scroll to the very bottom for the Youtube video!

Hello! In this deck, we will OTK the opponent by converting healing into damage. Let's see how...

 

 

Gameplan

1) Draw until you found Chronograph + Director + Smile + Simochi. When you have two monsters on the field, Link Summon Azalea with these two as materials and pop anything but Azalea. If you have more, use materials and pop in a way that Taotie would point to empty spaces.

2) When you have destroyed something with Azalea, you can trigger Chronograph, which lets you bring forth itself and Director. There, you can Synchro Summon Z-ARC with Chronograph + Director.

3) Replace Z-ARC with Arcray and Link Summon Taotie with Azalea + Arcray.

4) With Chronograph + Z-ARC + Arcray remaining steady at Extra Deck, set Smile + Simochi and end your turn. When it's your opponent's turn, activate Smile and chain into Simochi. By Special Summoning Chronograph + Z-ARC + Arcray with Smile, your opponent would gain LP. However, Simochi converts it into 2000 + 4000 + 4000 = 10000 damage and kills the opponent on the spot.

 

If you wonder how to save up some SR and UR points, I can show you:

- "Magicians' Souls" can be collected by purchasing "Vortex of Magic" deck. 30 UR saved and you can try a new deck!

- "Wonder Wand" can be collected by purchasing "Spellbook of Prophecy" deck. 90 SR saved and you can try a new deck!

- "Trade-In" can be collected by purchasing "Origin of the Galaxy" deck. 90 UR saved and you can try a new deck!

- "Upstart Goblin" can be found within "Bonkers Bikers' Wild Wheels" Secret Pack to save 60 UR!

- "Pseudo Space" can be found within "Cyber City Guardians" Secret Pack to save 60 SR!

- "Into The Void" + "Allure of Darkness" can be found within "The Infinite Void" Secret Pack to save 180 SR!

- "Performapal Monkeyboard" can be found within "The Bizarre Playing Board" Secret Pack to save 30 UR!

- "Pot of Acquisitiveness" + "Taotie Dragon" can be found within "Legacy Pack" to save 60 SR!

- "Sky Striker Ace - Azalea" can be found within "Sky Striker Awakening" Secret Pack to save 30 UR!

- "Chronograph Sorcerer" + "Supreme King Z-ARC - Synchro Universe" + "Odd-Eyes Arcray Dragon" can be found within "Counterswing Mages" Secret Pack to save 60 SR and 30 UR!

 

So, in total, you can save up to 540 SR and 360 UR, if you are willing to spend some gems. Other SR and UR cards I didn't mention are essential.

deck_excerpt: These wacky flip monsters are finally in Master Duel!
deck_description:
For the 1st stage of the WCS Qualifiers 2025, I decided to try out the newly released Mimighoul archetype. This is a control deck where the main gimmick is to gift your opponent flip monsters with negative effects, and then forcing them to be flipped face-up. I don't see it being meta, but it's really wacky and fun to play, plus it's not too expensive.

Your best starters are Mimighoul Maker and Mimighoul Dragon (and in turn, Mimighoul Dungeon, which can search Dragon or any other Mimighoul monster), but the deck really excels when you have access to 2-card combos. To play the deck optimally, you need 3 copies of Mimighoul Maker, however, I only managed to pull 2, and can't afford to spend more UR points for a fun deck at the moment. Many times, what you want to do is either lock your opponent from normal summoning with Mimighoul Dungeon, and use Mimighoul Room to summon Mimighoul Dragon or Mimighoul Archfiend to their side of the field and then flip them up with Mimighoul Maker's GY effect or Mimighoul Master.

Both the Kashtira cards and Triple Tactics have insane synergy with this archetype, since you can make the Mimighouls activate on your opponent field (even if you don't, they are still very good standalone cards). Bystial Magnamhut is non-engine that can also get you into engine (it can search Mimighoul Dragon). Silhouhatte Rabbit is a nice way to turn 2 random monsters into a disruption (without having to play a Fiendsmith package), same for I:P Masquerena (to make S:P Little Knight or Underworld Goddess of the Closed World on the opponent's turn). Number 13: Embodiment of Crime can, in theory, flip up the Mimighouls you give your opponent during your own turn (as well as your opponent's), but in practice I haven't used it yet.

I really enjoyed my time with this deck, but if there's one thing I didn't like is that Mimighoul Master feels like such an awkward card. If it either was a Level 1 monster, or it was a searcher for Mimighoul Spell/Trap cards as well, it would be an amazing card for the archetype, but the fact that it is neither of those makes it harder to use, hence why everyone runs it at 1 copy (imagine a monster that searches on summon being a soft garnet lol). I even wonder if there is a world where you could play Mimighoul without Master. Also, be aware that Dominus Impulse completely shuts down the Mimighoul effects for the entire duel, I got lucky and didn't have to deal with it though.

I hope you enjoy the deck. I also attached a video where you can see some nice duels I had, even though it doesn't really showcase the standard Mimighoul combos (you can probably find other videos that explain those though). Happy dueling!

deck_excerpt: A mix of Ryu-Ge, Dino, and a couple extra Wyrm monsters for spice
deck_description:
This deck is incredibly flexible both in its endboard and in its decklist. You can put in handtraps, sub out Kaitoptera for Giant Rex if Polymerization is too much of a brick, and throw in a lot of different extra deck options.

Mistva pops itself for cost which sets up for Xeno Meteorus, and War Zone can search for any Dino you need. Those are your main segues from Ryu-Ge into Dino, but the deck does suffer from not going the other way around, so if you can't get Mistva or War Zone, then Sea Spires and Wyrm Winds become bricks without the respective monsters and you're stuck with Dino combos, which are nerfed due to limited options

deck_excerpt: I think Yummy is a going second Archetype, change my mind.
deck_description:
I think Yummy can go second.

I don't want this deck to work but I'm curious that it might.

Relying on cards like Dark ruler and forbidden droplet to negate a field. Basically every card in this deck is there to mess up whatever your opponent has created.

Even if the Yummy cards haven't been summoned by a synchro monsters effect, they are still decent coming onto the field themselves.

A lot of the spells work when you have no cards, Alpha and Yummy Surprise bounce cards you control to help you activate them.

Alpha + any of the Yummy synchros can make an easy Baron (you often have too many yummy synchros to know what to do with anyway).

Nimble Beaver can help get to Herald and Number 64 Raccoon. If Nimble Beaver is summoned with obedience schooled Alpha can jump him back to hand to reactivate his normal summon effect.

Forbidden Droplet, the Sky Striker quick plays and Yummy Surprise can all be retrieved with Ukanomeitsune-no-onari.

It wont be used often but Number 64 Raccoon summons a token that can be used to make link spider to help Yummy's special summon themselves. Raccoon also cant be destroyed by battle or card effects when you control another beast monster (which is obviously quite easy to achieve).

Soul drain doesn't effect this deck at all. Rivalry of warlords is really easy to play under as its almost an all beast deck.

Triple tactics thrust to grab: Obedience School or Sky Striker Engage for summoning; or Dark Ruler, Feather Duster, Evenly Matched etc. for board breaking.

Lava Golem + Rivalry of Warlords could lock opponent into feind monsters only but will rarely come up.

Finally, it's easy to get the Sky Striker Engage "draw one card" effect as you're playing so many spells.

deck_excerpt: Independent Nightingale FTK ft. Venom Bros + Royal Magical Library
deck_description:
Greetings! Here, you will copycat Nightingale three times to shoot your opponent and kill for good. Let's get into action!

 

 

Gameplan

1) With Trismagistus and Double/Pendulum Summon, have 3 x Level 4 monsters at your side and XYZ Summon Strix with two of them as materials.

3) Play "Fusion Tag" and target on remaining Level 4 monster. Choose Supreme in order to change the name of said monster as "Starving Venom".

4) Play "Fusion Gate" and activate it twice in order to Fusion Summon the following monsters:

  • Starving Venemy Dragon = Dissolver + Cosmo/Monk/Souls
  • Odd-Eyes Venom Dragon = Dissolver + Level 4 monster (Starving Venom)

5) Copycat Nightingale with Odd-Eyes and Venemy to deal lots of damage. If this wasn't enough, bring forth Supreme by tributing Odd-Eyes and Venemy. Copycat Nightingale with Supreme to seal the game.

deck_excerpt: Gem-Knight con nuevo soporte (Battles of Legend)
deck_description:
Gem-Knight con nuevo soporte (Battles of Legend)

1. Estado del arquetipo con nuevo soporte:

  • El nuevo soporte de Gem-Knight es muy sólido, permitiendo combos consistentes y acceso a cartas clave.

  • A diferencia de versiones anteriores, no se usan tantas cartas viejas del arquetipo, ya que las nuevas son significativamente mejores.

2. Fortalezas del mazo:

  • Muchas cartas nuevas funcionan como one-card starters, con efectos como:

    • Búsqueda.

    • Invocación adicional.

    • Reciclaje desde el cementerio.

  • Brilliant Fusion está de vuelta, y no es una vez por turno, lo que potencia aún más el motor del mazo.

  • El nuevo Link Monster tributa para invocar hasta tres Gem-Knights desde el cementerio, facilitando fusiones, enlaces o jugadas XYZ.

3. Integración con otros motores:

  • Se pueden incluir motores como Mitsurugi o Fiendsmith, ya que el mazo accede fácilmente a King of the Feral Imps.

  • Esto abre la puerta a híbridos que mejoran su capacidad de generar interrupciones y extender jugadas.

4. Opciones defensivas:

  • El mazo tiene espacio para 12–15 hand traps sin perder consistencia.

  • Algunas cartas Gem-Knight permiten jugar durante el turno del oponente, aunque sus efectos no son negaciones, lo cual limita su impacto.

5. Problemas y limitaciones:

  • El mayor punto débil es el extra deck, especialmente las fusiones. Muchas no generan suficiente presión ni ofrecen interacciones relevantes.

  • Se destaca la necesidad de fusiones nuevas y más poderosas para que el mazo pueda ser realmente competitivo en formato actual.

  • El mazo no es resistente a Nibiru, aunque en ocasiones puede recuperarse usando los motores mencionados.

6. Jugabilidad en duelos:

  • El video muestra duelos donde el mazo juega a través de múltiples interrupciones y resuelve jugadas incluso bajo presión.

  • Hay comentarios sobre situaciones en las que Ash Blossom o Droll & Lock Bird detienen las jugadas clave.

  • A pesar de eso, el motor de Gem-Knight permite reconstruir campo o defenderse gracias a cartas como Prayers (omni-negación) o los nuevos fusiones.

üîö Conclusión:

 

El nuevo soporte de Gem-Knight lo convierte en un mazo con buen potencial gracias a sus starters y extensiones, pero sufre por un extra deck limitado. Si Konami lanza nuevas fusiones efectivas, podría convertirse en un contendiente real en el metajuego.

Solomon Muto aka Grandpa is the first one in the series with a deck focusing on Exodia. We basically using 11 continuous traps with 3 Magic Planters to have control (protection) on field and some +2 Draws. All the other cards just helps us to draw more cards or more pieces. While I've tried other approaches with Doom Shaman and many Hand Destruction cards to return the 4 pieces of Exodia from grave to hand, this takes so much time and it's not easy at all. THIS approach feels easier to execute even if we miss the tribute summon of a level 5-6 monster to remove Sangan or Emissary of the Afterlife ourselves from field to proc their effects.

deck_excerpt: Dark Magician and a few new friends.
deck_description:
With Dark Magician getting new cards, me and thousands of others I'm sure have been making all types of decks to see what they can do with it. I've tried a lot of different decks I've seen posted and a lot of them have been really fun, but this behemoth of a deck is the most fun I've had since I got back into Yu-Gi-Oh. 

This 60 card beast of a deck was partially inspired by KingMahde and RoyalGamesYT. KingMahde gave me the idea that maybe a 60 card DM deck isn't that bad and RoyalGamesYT gave me the idea of adding Fiendsmith.

Playing this deck is a little more advanced that just playing Primite Dark Magician, but honestly it's not super complicated at all. I'll list some key points I've noticed while playing this deck.

  • Not every hand will allow you to open with a floodgate/boss monster, but it is a lot more consistent now than it has ever been for Dark Magician decks.
  • Opening with ensuring you can get Dragoon out either Turn 1 or at the draw phase of Turn 2 with Gaze is going to be your main objective.
    • If you cannot open with Dragoon, try and just get either fiendsmith, primite, negates, or a strong link monster out.
  • Make sure you do not use Gaze of Timaeus during your turn unless you can dodge the banish effect at the end of the next turn.
    • For example: fusion summoning with Gaze, then immediately getting it off the board for something else (possibly bringing it back in the same turn). You could also use I:P Masquerena to link it during your opponents turn to dodge the banish.
  • Do not flood your spell & trap zones. It is really easy with this deck to set out multiple continuous/face down spells & traps. Be careful not to overdo it so you can still use something if needed.

While this deck may not be a meta killer, it can definitely put up a good fight against some good decks. There are better combinations (like Diabell and snake eyes) that are more competitive, but if that's not your thing I would recommend giving this deck a try and see what combos you can pull off. If you do try this deck, let me know what you think or if you would maybe swap a card in/out.

The Fiendsmith engine makes this deck more resistant to cards that prevent banishing, such as Artifact Lancea, Imperial Iron Wall, and Chaos Hunter. Any two effect monsters can summon Moon of the Closed Heaven, who can access the Fiendsmith engine through Fiendsmith's Requiem because she's a light fiend.

The Orcust-Fiendsmith Connection

Girsu, the Orcust Mekk-Knight can be a one-card starter for the Fiendsmith engine because he summons an Orcust token, which can be used as link material for the effect monster Galatea-i, the Orcust Automaton. Galatea-i can then discard a card to search World Legacy - "World Crown", which can special summon itself to a zone Galatea-i points to. World Crown + Galatea-i = Moon of the Closed Heaven. Also, Orcust Harp Horror, Orcust Cymbal Skeleton, Orcust Knightmare, and World Legacy - "World Wand" have graveyard effects that will lock you into only special summoning dark monsters for the rest of the turn, so make sure you use the Fiendsmith engine first before activating their effects.

deck_name: Legacy of Yami: My First Main Deck
deck_excerpt: You don't come back from infinity!
deck_description:
I used to play Yu-Gi-Oh! back in the early days, around 2002 to early 2004, and I recently lost all of my old cards, including the four decks I had kept for years. I’m posting them here mostly for memory’s sake, and maybe someday I’ll try rebuilding them.

This was my main deck back then. I built it when I was really young and just loaded it up with all of my strongest cards at the time. Me and the small group I played with weren’t exactly great at building decks. Most of mine were around 50 cards, and one of my friends had a deck that was literally just a giant stack of like a hundred. Totally ridiculous, but it was a fun time.

We’d hang out at the local card shop, and I was always trying to trade for the cool or hard-to-find cards, or save up to buy them directly from the store. I wasn’t chasing meta or anything. I just wanted what I heard was powerful or felt important.

Originally, I had Dark Magician in here like a lot of kids did back then, but eventually I received Cosmo Queen and instantly replaced him. She became my ace card. I don’t even know why I loved that card so much, but I did. There was just something about her art, the high ATK, and that mysterious vibe. I loved when I got her out, it felt like a big deal. 

This was the first of my four decks. It definitely wasn’t a good deck by competitive standards, but we didn’t care. It was really just an arms race between a few of us, throwing whatever strong monsters or flashy spells we had into a pile and seeing who came out on top.

For some reason, I always liked the older, kind of bad field spells too. Stuff like “Yami” really stuck with me. I think it just reminded me of the anime. Even if it wasn’t great, I liked the atmosphere it brought to the duel.

So yeah, this was my main deck. Not the best-built, but full of memories. RIP

deck_excerpt: Blue Eyes! Attack with all your might! White lightning!
deck_description:
The second of four decks lost recently that I built when I was younger. Most of my friends back then had a Blue-Eyes White Dragon deck, so naturally I built one too. It was my second favorite deck overall, but it mostly ended up with the leftover good cards from my collection. One of the few pros was that I actually had some duplicates in this deck. 

I probably should have made it more of a pure Dragon deck, but I lost a lot of the key pieces during trades. Cards I had duplicates of like Lord of D. and Flute of Summoning Dragon ended up getting traded away before I created this deck. Some of those even went to my friends early on, which is kind of funny looking back.

None of us actually owned a Blue-Eyes Ultimate Dragon, so one of my friends made a laminated picture of it, and we just used that whenever someone wanted to summon it. 

I also got fixated on including Sanga of the Thunder in one of my decks, and Mountain gave me just enough of a reason to throw him in here. I pulled Sanga randomly out of a pack my parents bought me at Walmart after I asked for it.

At one point I had Harpie Ladies and Harpie’s Pet Dragon in this deck too. I liked how the pet dragon looked, but it didn’t really work, so I took them out. I did keep a few Winged Beast monsters though.

Serpent Night Dragon was also in the deck for a while, but I eventually replaced it with Luster Dragon #2. Some of the cards I always wanted for this deck but never got included Tri-Horned Dragon, Tyrant Dragon, and the level 4 Luster Dragon.

Harpie’s Brother is called Sky Scout now. RIP

The third of four decks I recently lost. This is where my resources were really starting to run thin. I sort of built this one out of spite because I kept pulling a lot of water cards I didn't want, like Amphibian Beast. I loved opening that card the first time, but I ended up with six of them somehow.

I never got my hands on Catapult Turtle, but it probably would have fit right in. I think I really wanted Suijin for this deck too, but I couldn't get that either. There was some kind of strange stall and burn strategy going on here, though I rarely used this deck against my friends. I would sometimes duel myself with it on boring days in my room. Not sure if anyone else ever did that or if it was just me. I was probably pretending to beat Mako or something in my mind.

deck_excerpt: full utopia power for all of you
Angel of Mischief FTK ft. Materiactor Meltdown
deck_description:
Welcome! In this deck, Gigaboros will be well fed and evolved into a mischievous girl. Let's get into action!

 

 

Gameplan

1) Place ME-PSY-YA on Pendulum Zone and Special Summon Chaos Emperor Dragon with its ability to unlock "Primal Seed" loop. Then, revive as many Level 3 monsters as possible via "Monster Reborn" and XYZ Summon Gigaboros with them, to where Reprodocus would point to.

2) When you XYZ Summon, you can Special Summon Oni. Use Oni on Gigaboros to reduce its Rank from 3 to 2. By reviving another Level 4 monster, you can XYZ Summon Number 80 alongside Oni as materials.

3) Play Chalice on Number 80 and activate Meltdown. By triggering Number 80, Meltdown asks you to feed Gigaboros from top of your Main Deck. Keep going until Gigaboros has 9 materials but not before playing "Pot of Generosity" a few times.

4) In order to let Astral Force active, Number 80 has to go. Fortunately, you have two methods...

  • Link Summon Reprodocus by using Saryuja + Number 80 as materials.
  • Revive Ravenous with "Monster Reborn" and pop it.

5) No matter what you do for #4, you have to Link Summon Reprodocus. Activate Reprodocus to change the Type of Gigaboros into Fairy.

6) Play Astral Force to replace Gigaboros with Mischief. Congratulations, you win the duel!

 

If you wonder how to save up some SR and UR points, I can show you:

- "Monster Reborn" can be found by completing the tutorial to save 30 UR!

- "Pot of Avarice" can be collected by purchasing "Re-Contract Universe" deck. 90 SR saved and you can try a new deck!

- "Wonder Wand" and "Spellbook of Knowledge" can be collected by purchasing "Spellbook of Prophecy" deck. 120 SR saved and you can try a new deck!

- "Summoner Monk" + "Centur-Ion Legatia" can be found within "True Awakening of the Oathbound Knights" Secret Pack to save 90 SR and 30 UR!

- "Rank-Up-Magic Astral Force" can be found within "Number Recall" Secret Pack to save 30 SR!

- "Upstart Goblin" can be found within "Bonkers Bikers' Wild Wheels" Secret Pack to save 90 UR!

- "Into The Void" + "Allure of Darkness" can be found within "The Infinite Void" Secret Pack to save 180 SR!

- "Moray of Avarice" can be found within "Treasures of the Cosmic Ocean" Secret Pack to save 30 UR!

- "T.G. Hyper Librarian" can be found within "Futuristic Creatures" Secret Pack to save 30 UR!

- "Pot of Acquistiveness" + "Ravenous" + "Primal Seed" can be found within "Legacy Pack" to save 60 SR and 60 UR!

- "Formula Synchron" can be either found within "Evoked Dragon of Miracles" or "Stardust Ties" Secret Packs to save 60 SR!

- "Ghostrick Angel of Mischief" can be found within "Mischievous Specters" Secret Pack to save 30 UR!

- "Materiactor Meltdown" + "Materiactor Gigaboros" can be found within "The Perpetual Maze" Timed Pack to save 30 SR and 30 UR! Don't miss out before it's too late!

 

So, in total, you can save up to 660 SR and 330 UR, if you are willing to spend some gems. Other SR and UR cards I didn't mention are essential.

 

That's all for this one. If you have any questions, feel free to ask. Have fun in Master Duel!

the lore goes deep, my first deck was a pile of ice barrier cards and it had black rose dragon, it was a eay that a teacher taught me math, i saved and bought abc becuse i thought they looked cool (machine pile in 2016) then my little self found that i loved yubel asa concept, so played tried to make it good for a long time.

A slow-burning control deck built around Lilith, Lady of Lament because I like her and Lair of Darkness card art. By tributing monsters (my own and yours), Lilith sets traps directly from the deck, creating a rotating arsenal of interruptions, removals, and floodgates. With Back Jack stacking your deck and Darkest Diabolos looming as an unrelenting boss, this build thrives on resource denial, precision disruption, and board suffocation. It's annoying but thats half the fun.
The idea of this deck is to have as many easy to sommun level 4/8 to start the Centur-Ion combo and no matter the engin, you have ways to interact every turn with your oponents.

My first attempt to make a domain deck. The idea here is you have many 1 card comboes and all of them lead to a strong board where you can have interruptions over multiple turns. The Arrival Cyberse @Ignister  is your tower, Allied Code Talker @Ignister + Firewall Dragon Singularity makes for a continuous stream of bounces and negates, plus if you can add Firewall Dragon this makes for multiple bounces and a negate.

deck_excerpt: HERO's with no locks (and no Fiendsmith). May your wallet be spared.
deck_description:
This HERO deck was designed to minimize bricks and be able to play without locks. This was made for MD, but the concept can be ported to TCG. It is current ly a work in progress (lines, ratios and card choices arent as optimal as I'd prefer yet).

A Hero Lives goes from Stratos > Dead End > Necrom > Infernal Rider > Dark Fusion, while Vyon goes Vyon > Necrom > Dead End > Shadow Mist > Adusted > Adds Dark Fusion. Both these lines go into Backfire, adding Dark Calling. You would then use Cross Sheep to revive a card of your choice. With the right extenders, you can make Appo, Verte > DPE, Dragostapelia and potentially more. These are very basic combos, and there are some more risky lines that get you more (such as Toxic Bubble draw or Shadowmist searching Mask Change).;

Prepare to descend into a symphony of shadows and light with this Darklord Melodious Lightsworn Tearlaments deck, a truly unique and potent fusion! This isn't just a deck; it's a forbidden concerto where fallen angels serenade divine melodies, and the chaos of the Lightsworn fuels the abyssal depths of the Tearlaments. Unleash the Darklords to dominate the field with their immense ATK and LP-recovering effects, endlessly recycling powerful spell and trap cards. Then, witness the angelic might of the Melodious monsters, whose harmonious calls flood your board, setting the stage for devastating fusions and synchros. The unpredictable Lightsworn engine will mill your deck at blinding speeds, populating your graveyard with essential resources while occasionally summoning powerful monsters like Judgment Dragon to wipe your opponent's board clean. But the true secret weapon lies within the Tearlaments. They weave through your graveyard, fusing with your other archetypes to unleash terrifying boss monsters like Tearlaments Kaleido-Heart, disrupting your opponent's plays and ensuring your dominance. This deck thrives on synergy and surprise, constantly adapting to your opponent's strategy. Will you overwhelm them with a swarm of Darklords, lock them down with Melodious fusions, or unleash a sudden Lightsworn-Tearlaments combo that leaves them in disarray? Every duel is a new performance, a delicate balance between order and chaos, light and shadow.

deck_excerpt: Cyber Jar Mill ft. Wanghu + Wattfox
deck_description:
Greetings! In this deck, Cyber Jar will deplete your opponent's deck and they can't be able to do anything. Let's see...

 

 

Gameplan

1) When you have Granite present, Link Summon Saryuja and shuffle your deck in a way that it only consists of 1 x Cyber Jar as minion and rest as spells.

2) Place ME-PSY-YA on Pendulum Zone and Special Summon Chaos Emperor Dragon with its ability to unlock "Primal Seed" loop. To protect this interaction, use Dress on Chaos.

3) Use Granite to pull out Cyber Jar from your hand as face-down. Then, Special Summon Wanghu with Saryuja and give Wanghu to the opponent with "Shien's Spy".

4) Play Double Summon to bring forth Wattfox. After Wattfox has been destroyed by Wanghu, your opponent can't be able to do anything. Then, use Book on Cyber Jar.

5) With Cyber Jar being activated, all monsters but Chaos will be destroyed and you can search other Cyber Jar. Special Summon it as face-down. Meanwhile, your opponent can't do the followings even under Cyber Jar...

  • Special Summon due to Wattfox. They can only add monsters to their hand.
  • Activation of Monster/Spell/Trap cards and effects at anywhere. This completely shuts down any hand traps and their GY/BZ in hopes of disruption.

6) To repeat what was explained in #5, use Phoenix to place Cyber Jar on top of your Main Deck. Afterwards, you can play Book on Cyber Jar. Keep going until your opponent has no cards in their Main Deck and end your turn. When it's their turn, they will deck-out and you win the game.

 

If you wonder how to save up some SR and UR points, I can show you:

- "Pot of Avarice" can be collected by purchasing "Re-Contract Universe" deck. 90 SR saved and you can try a new deck!

- "Wonder Wand" and "Spellbook of Knowledge" can be collected by purchasing "Spellbook of Prophecy" deck. 120 SR saved and you can try a new deck!

- "Summoner Monk" can be found within "True Awakening of the Oathbound Knights" Secret Pack to save 90 SR!

- "Upstart Goblin" can be found within "Bonkers Bikers' Wild Wheels" Secret Pack to save 90 UR!

- "Into The Void" + "Allure of Darkness" can be found within "The Infinite Void" Secret Pack to save 180 SR!

- "Moray of Avarice" can be found within "Treasures of the Cosmic Ocean" Secret Pack to save 30 UR!

- "T.G. Hyper Librarian" can be found within "Futuristic Creatures" Secret Pack to save 30 UR!

- "Pot of Acquistiveness" + "Ravenous" + "Cyber Jar" + "King Tiger Wanghu" + "Primal Seed" can be found within "Legacy Pack" to save 90 SR and 120 UR!

- "Formula Synchron" + "Accel Synchro Stardust Dragon" can be found within "Evoked Dragon of Miracles" Secret Pack to save 90 SR and 30 UR!

 

So, in total, you can save up to 660 SR and 300 UR, if you are willing to spend some gems. Other SR and UR cards I didn't mention are essential.

 

That's all for this one. If you have any questions, feel free to ask. Have fun in Master Duel!

deck_description: The Divine Pantheon's Symphony Unleash a cacophony of Ritual Summons and Divine Beasts with this hybrid build that expertly weaves together the sacred Voiceless Voice and the mechanical precision of Drytron. Your opponents will face an unyielding barrage of high-level monsters, from the radiant Saffira, Dragon Queen of the Voiceless Voice to the imposing Drytron Meteonis Draconids. This deck doesn't just summon; it orchestrates a symphony of disruption, utilizing cards like Ash Blossom & Joyous Spring and Infinite Impermanence to silence your opponent's every move. Prepare to dominate the field with a divine presence and an iron fist! Ancient Rites, Modern Might Witness the fusion of ancient Ritual magic and cutting-edge technology in "Ancient Rites, Modern Might." This deck seamlessly integrates the powerful Voiceless Voice and Megalith archetypes with the speed and consistency of Drytron. Each turn is a masterclass in resource management, as you cycle through your deck to bring forth an array of unstoppable monsters. From the protective embrace of Skull Guardian to the explosive potential of Shinobaron Peacock, your opponents will struggle to keep pace with your evolving board. This isn't just a deck; it's a strategic dance between tradition and innovation, culminating in absolute victory. The Unseen Chorus Beneath the surface, an "Unseen Chorus" of Ritual Monsters awaits. This deck masterfully blends the celestial beauty of Voiceless Voice with the ritualistic power of Megalith and the reliable engine of Drytron. Each card serves a purpose, from preparing your ultimate Ritual Summons to disrupting your opponent's most critical plays. With a deep toolbox of Extra Deck options like Herald of the Arc Light and Chaos Angel, you're ready for any challenge. This deck is for the duelist who appreciates intricate combos, powerful boss monsters, and the satisfaction of outmaneuvering their opponent with an almost mystical synergy.

deck_excerpt: Fuse dragons, synchronize with spellcasters, and defeat Despia.
deck_description:
Fun Albaz deck that takes minimal influence from the evil forces of Despia!

Flexes pretty well. Fun to take to a local and mess around.

Handles Blue-Eyes, Red Dragon Archfiend, and even Branded mirror matches pretty well. Contact fusing into Alba-Lenatus is basically a win button if you can pressure your opponent out of their resources.

Use Lubellion & Light of the Branded to draw out the game and wear your opponent's resources out while keeping your fusions in circulation.

Garura & Mudragon do tons of heavy lifting, but you can side in other super-poly options depending on your opponent's build. Use Granguignol to drop Yubel into the GY to bring it back with Sanctifire to boardwipe via Fallen of Albaz.

Elemental Crescendo: A Symphony of Chaos This isn't just a deck; it's a maelstrom of unexpected synergies, where the raw, untamed might of the Dragon Rulers collides with the graceful melodies of the Melodious monsters and the swift, aerial assaults of the Harpies. You'll witness the legendary Dragon Rulers, like Blaster, Tidal, and Tempest, rise from the banished zone to dominate the field, while the angelic voices of Shopina and Soprano serenade your opponent into submission. But don't be fooled by the harmonious tunes! Hidden within are the disruptive forces of the Windwitches, ready to chime in with their devastating Synchro plays, leading into the likes of Crystal Wing Synchro Dragon and Cyber Slash Harpie Lady. And just when your opponent thinks they've weathered the storm, the chaotic mill of the Lightsworn engine will unleash a torrent of graveyard-based comebacks, setting up explosive plays with cards like Charge of the Light Brigade and Minerva, the Exalted Lightsworn. "Elemental Crescendo" thrives on calculated risk and explosive comebacks. It's a deck that demands a duelist who can adapt on the fly, weaving together disparate archetypes into a cohesive, and utterly devastating, strategy. Will you unleash the full fury of the elements and conduct your way to victory?

deck_excerpt: dare to be blow up me field
deck_description:
to those who wish to play rogue against mitsu/ryzeal in alin format i present unchained.

i got day 2 with the decklist and top 64 in UK nats 2025, it actually a personal best for me and i never feel i couldn't set a board or break a board

*disclaimer the maliss match up was properly the worst, and maybe need better side decking for.

I went into this nats with droll being the best handtrap in the format in the present of pure mitsu and ryzeal/mitsu being the best deck, and mulcharmy's in everyone deck.

both fiendsmith and unchained after one search could play under droll and always setting up caesar with intruption in graveyard, such as paradise and yama. under mulcharmy the plan was still to droll myself and play under droll, so in the build was potentially 7 outs for mulcharmy's.

44 cards actually supported with siding process as aruha, chambers and engraver were easy to take out. the mulcharmy's alter the deck building and siding process due to potential drawing, it is very OCG as max C exists. the single ogre and belle was only at 1 because of that reason, you just couldn't brick on one for. 

the big blue dog was needed to push through boards hated seeing it on hand but hater siding it out, the big blue forces response of potential sp and is non destructive removing.

i just wanted to share my success and i was so happy to do so well with a personal favourite deck.

peace

deck_description: "Azure Dominion: The Chronos Dragon's Roar" This isn't your grandfather's "Blue-Eyes" deck. Prepare for a paradigm shift as the legendary Blue-Eyes White Dragon ascends to new heights, not just through its inherent might, but through an unprecedented fusion with the stoic power of the Centur-Ion empire and the elegant adaptability of the Dragonmaids. Witness the chaotic beauty of Chaos MAX Dragon ritual summoned alongside the relentless Centur-Ion Legatia, backed by the strategic maneuvers of the Dragonmaids. This deck is a symphony of ancient power and cutting-edge tactics, designed to overwhelm your opponent with a diverse arsenal of boss monsters, unexpected synchro plays with Crimson Dragon, and the disruptive force of Horus's chosen. Can you withstand the combined might of three distinct dynasties, all vying for ultimate dominion?

deck_excerpt: Maiden and Sage semi-limited? That's no problem for Kaiba and Kisara!
deck_description:
Maiden and Sage semi-limited due to the June 2025 banlist? That's no problem for Kaiba and Kisara! Blue-Eyes is still one of the most powerful and consistent decks of the format! 

Already powerful with the structure deck support, Blue-Eyes White Dragon is propelled into even higher heights of power with the introduction of the Primite cards! Primite adds a whole new layer of interruption, advantage, starters and recursion to the Blue-Eyes strategy. Ether Beryl searches sets your Primite spells from deck while being a level 4 Dragon which can be linked into Spirit with Eyes of Blue. Lordly Lode searches for Primite cards, while being an extender for any normal monster, most notably Blue-Eyes White Dragon. Finally, Drillbeam's potent targeted negate banish is a powerful interruption that also resets itself every turn! 
 
Able to play low to the ground in simplified gamestates due to Maxx "C" or mass handtraps, Blue-Eyes Primite can still have a respectable board even when interrupted. On the other hand, Blue-Eyes Primite's best board is extremely hard to crack, especially with Drillbeam protecting your massive Dragons!
 
The immense advantage that this 7 card engine makes Blue-Eyes nearly unstoppable in Masterduel ladder when piloted properly! Now you get to dominant the duel arena just like Kaiba did in Battle City as the world's (second) strongest duelist!

GLHF duelists!

Want to see the deck in action? Scroll to the very bottom for the Youtube video!
