deck_excerpt: OTK Those Noobs! (Noob PWNing Guide included!)
deck_description:
Learn the P.U.N.K. combo starters and extenders for maximum PWNage!

Price: 600LP EACH!!!

Ukiyoe-P.U.N.K. Sharakusai gives you a fusion on the field if you have the materials in your hand (Ukiyoe-P.U.N.K. Rising Carp). 

 

Gagaku-P.U.N.K. Wa Gon gives you a spell search (Gagaku-P.U.N.K. Crash Beat, P.U.N.K. JAM Extreme Session, and Gagaku-P.U.N.K. Wild Picking).

 

Joruri-P.U.N.K. Madame Spider gives you a trap search (Joruri-P.U.N.K. Dangerous Gabu, Joruri-P.U.N.K. Nashiwari Surprise).

 

Noh-P.U.N.K. Ze Amin gives you a monster search (Ukiyoe-P.U.N.K. Sharakusai, Gagaku-P.U.N.K. Wa Gon, Joruri-P.U.N.K. Madame Spider).

 

Fiendsmith Engraver is a standard of the Fiendsmith engine run in so many modern decks. You will be able to grab your Fiendsmith in Paradise or Fiendsmith's Lacrima to summon Extra Deck monsters.

 

 

Learn the boss monsters? You got it, boss!

Dominate and destroy! All your Lvl. 8s can self-tribute for a lower-level "P.U.N.K." monster.

Noh-P.U.N.K. Rising Scale provides super awesome special summons at the standard 600LP cost and can self-summon by banishing a "P.U.N.K." card. She can also flip cards into face-down Defense Position. Get dunked on!

 

Noh-P.U.N.K. Ogre Dance gets free ATK points and can self-summon by tributing a "P.U.N.K." monster. u mad bro?

 

Noh-P.U.N.K. Foxy Tune provides LP gain if you get kills on her. She also self-summons herself by tributing a "P.U.N.K." monster. Someone call the Whambulance!

 

Noh-P.U.N.K. Deer Note plays from the hand, revealing 1 other "P.U.N.K." monster from your hand. You can send Deer Note to the GY with this effect, allowing you to get a free GY special summon of whatever you want, basically. Provided your GY isn't only Deer Note, you can get any of your Lvl. 3s or Lvl. 8s on the field. It might just be you and me, but that's okay, because do you really need ANYONE ELSE?!

 

 

Learn your Extra Deck! Let's OTK!

I only need one shot.

Ukiyoe-P.U.N.K. Amazing Dragon gives you a triple bounce off the rip and can special summon a "P.U.N.K." monster from the GY every turn, excluding itself. What are those?!

 

P.U.N.K. JAM Dragon Drive allows you to pocket a Lvl. 3 from your deck or send it to the GY. While in the GY, you can negate the activation of any chains to your "P.U.N.K." cards.

 

P.U.N.K. JAM FEVER! can be summoned using any Fusion or Synchro "P.U.N.K." monster, or using your boss monsters if you somehow don't have either. While on the field, you can detach a material to draw 1 card. Also, it gives you the ability to negate another monster's effect while you have any of your Lvl. 3s in your GY.

 

 

Counter the enemy!

Obligatory hand-trap section! Yay!

Mulcharmy Fuwalos is a standard hand-trap in the current meta which can be activated as long as you control no cards (e.g. Opponent goes first). While it doesn't prevent your enemy from setting up, for every enemy Special Summon from the Deck or Extra Deck, you can draw 1 card.

 

Ash Blossom & Joyous Spring is a notorious hand-trap which allows you to negate the activation of any card that involves searching the deck (there are so many cards that do this). This will sometimes brick entire setups if you're lucky and/or your opponent is unlucky enough.

 

PSY-Framegear Gamma and PSY-Frame Driver are part of a handtrap core that has been in the game for a long time. While it's been seen less and less lately, the Psychic attribute of these monsters are pretty good for "P.U.N.K." as a whole. While you control no monsters, Gamma is playable when an opponent's monster activates an effect. This will allow you to negate the activation, destroy the monster, and summon Gamma and Driver. During the End Phase, they are both banished.

 

Training complete!

Get out there and PWN some noobs!

Dive into a maelstrom where worlds collide and darkness reigns supreme! This isn't just a deck; it's a forbidden symphony of the Underworld's most formidable forces. Witness the elegant terror of the Labrynth as they lure opponents into a treacherous maze of traps, only for the Dark World's relentless discard engine to unleash a flood of monstrous power. But the abyss runs deeper still, as the primeval Tearlaments weave their aquatic fusion magic, reshaping the battlefield with every move. And just when your foes believe they've found a foothold, the unyielding might of the Horus ancient kings rises, alongside the insidious control of Lair of Darkness. This deck is a masterclass in controlled chaos, blending oppressive trap strategies with explosive Special Summons and devastating board-wipes. Prepare to drag your opponents into an inescapable nightmare, where every turn brings a new, terrifying revelation from the deepest, darkest corners of the game!

deck_excerpt: These new (and old) water machines are no joke!
deck_description:
Crystron recently got new support in Master Duel, and it is actually quite powerful. That, and the facts that Crystron doesn't care about Bystials, has solid grind game capabilities and has good in-engine answers to popular decks like Fiendsmith (Quariongandrax) and Blue-Eyes (Quariongandrax and Cluster) make it a very solid pick right now. You could play it completely pure, but the Speedroid package and the Millennium engine facilitate the Crystron gameplan and can provide extra disruption or going 2nd capabilities.

This is one of those decks where it can take a little time to click with, but once it does, it is very fun and competent. I was able to reach Master I this season using this list, so let's start breaking it down, starting with the Crystrons themselves.

Crystron is a Synchro archetype focused on Machine monsters. Their tuners have some quick effect to allow for Synchro Summoning during the opponent's turn. Then, each of the Crystron Synchro monsters has some effect when summoned, and float into some monster when destroyed. Most main deck Crystron monsters also have some kind of effect in the GY. Be mindful that many of the Crystron effects lock you into Machines or Machine Synchro monsters.

  • Crystron Quariongandrax is the Crystron boss monster. It requires 2+ tuners and 1 non-tuner, but when Synchro Summoned it lets you banish monsters from your opponent's field or GY, up to the number of synchro materials used (generally 3), making it very strong in the current meta. For example, summoning it during your opponent's turn destroys the Fiendsmith engine.
  • To allow summoning Quariongandrax during the opponent's turn (as well as other synchros), the strongest tuner is the newly added Crystron Tristaros. It lets you, in response to an opponent's card effect, Special Summon a Crystron monster from deck and immediately Synchro Summoning using that monster. To make Quariongandrax, you want to use Crystron Tristaros + Crystron Citree + a Level 5 (Sulfefnir, Sulfador, or Dawn Dragster after using the negate), so generally Tristaros will summon Citree from the deck. Since Tristaros effect works during either turn, you can use it as a normal summon before starting your other combos to play around your opponent's interactions.
  • For the deck to work, you need some Level 5's. Crystron Sulfefnir is the original one, which can summon itself from hand or GY by discarding a Crystron card, then it destroys a card on your field. You can destroy itself, since its second effect is to summon any Crystron from deck when destroyed. Crystron Sulfador on the other hand was added in the newest wave of support - it can summon itself from hand or GY by destroying a Crystron card on the field, and on summon it is a double foolish burial for the archetype, which is massive and helps set up all your plays (remember, most Crystron monsters do something in GY).
  • Crystron Smiger is the card you generally want to get into the GY to kickstart your plays (hence why you want to play Clockwork Knight as a Link 1 that you can use Smiger as material. It lets you banish itself from GY to search for a Crystron Spell/Trap, which will usually be Crystron Inclusion, the newly added continuous spell that is just incredible, letting you add any Crystron card on activation, reborn a Crystron by banishing itself from GY, as well as having a bonus battle protection effect. Inclusion is essential for the deck, and can function either as a starter, extender or as a combo piece.
  • Crystron Eleskeletus is the new Level 7 Synchro for the archetype. While it is a very solid card, it is not a boss monster itself, functioning more as an essential combo piece that can also help with the grind game. On summon, it adds back a Crystron card from GY or banishment (could be something you foolished with Sulfador, discard fodder for Sulfefnir, or simply a card for a follow-up play), and on destruction it revives a Crystron monster from GY or banishment. The attack reduction also comes up sometimes.
  • The remaining Crystron monsters are Crystron Thystvern, which has a very solid effect in GY to search for any Crystron monster; Crystron Prasiortle, which is not essential in the deck but it has a neat effect that lets you summon a Crystron from hand; and Crystron Ametrix, a budget Level 5 Synchro that is ok, but not essential since it rarely comes up.
  • The final piece that puts this deck together is Crystron Cluster, a continuous trap that lets you recycle resources to destroy face-up cards your opponent controls, every turn. It's a phenomenal endboard piece that's also easily accessible: you can get it with Smiger if you already have Cluster, send it to the GY with Sulfador to add back with Eleskeletus, or add it with Cluster if you don't need anything else from it.

The Speedroid package (Speedroid Terrortop + Speedroid Taketomborg) is included mainly to make Cherubini, Ebon Angel of the Burning Abyss, which can send Crystron Smiger to the GY, giving you access to the Crystron combos. Alternatively, if you already have combo, you could make an S:P Little Knight for a little extra disruption, especially when going 2nd.

The Millennium engine is also very good in this deck. Any of the 3 cards will let you go into The Zombie Vampire to get you GY setup or, alternatively, you can make Number 90: Galaxy-Eyes Photon Lord to play around handtraps such as Nibiru. In addition, during the Millennium combo you use Snake-Eyes Doomed Dragon, which has a useful effect that can help break boards going 2nd. The fact that Wedju Temple places a monster from hand in the S/T zone, and then you send them to GY for Doomed Dragon can also help getting a Smiger or Thystvern that's stuck in your hand into the GY, and it's also free if you use Sulfador or Sulfefnir since they both can be summoned from GY.

You could play around with ratios (some people play more or less copies of the Golem that Guards the Millennium Treasures), but one thing is certain: I prefer the Millennium engine over other engines such as Horus since it has no main deck bricks and doesn't care about Bystials at all.

As for the remaining cards in the Extra Deck:

  • F.A. Dawn Dragster is a Level 7 Machine Synchro that negates spells/traps by reducing its level (the level reduction actually matters in this deck, since it turning into a Level 5 lets you use it as material for Quariongandrax or a Cyber Dragon Nova in some cases). It should be part of your endboard or summoned during the opponent's turn. You should probably play 2 copies (replacing, for instance, the Ametrix); I only played 1 copy since I didn't want to craft more URs, but the 2nd one comes up somewhat often.
  • Cyber Dragon Infinity (which you make by overlaying Cyber Dragon Nova) is an omni-negate that should also be part of your regular endboard, since this deck easily puts up Level 5 Machine monsters (Sulfador and Sulfefnir).
  • Samurai Destroyer is a useful Level 7 Synchro that can help playing around your opponent's mass removal. For example, if your opponent activates Nibiru, you can chain your Tristaros and make Samurai Destroyer; then, when Samurai Destroyer goes to the GY, you can revive a Machine and keep going from there. The battle phase effect could come up sometimes as well.
  • Baronne de Fleur is not a Machine synchro, but it comes up more often than you'd think. You can make it with Tristaros or Citree + Sengenjin or Doomed Dragon.

The endboard you are usually aiming for includes Infinity (omni-negate) + Dawn Dragster (spell/trap negate) + Cluster (pop), potentially Quariongandrax setup as well (banish 3 monsters), plus any non-engine you might draw. It might not seem like much at first glance, but it's actually tough to play through, and the deck is very consistent at doing so. If you have access to the Millennium engine, you can sometimes add a Number 90, Baronne and/or S:P to the endboard as well.

Here's a basic combo, starting with Crystron Inclusion to end on Infinity + Cluster + Dawn Dragster:

  • Activate Crystron Inclusion, search Crystron Sulfador (if you started with Crystron Smiger in hand you could normal summon it and link into Clockwork Knight, then use its GY effect to get Inclusion). 
  • Activate Sulfador, pop Inclusion to summon itself. Send to GY Crystron Tristaros and Crystron Cluster.
  • Use Inclusion GY effect to revive Tristaros and Synchro Summon Crystron Eleskeletus. Eleskeletus adds back the Cluster from GY.
  • Use Tristaros effect in GY, banishing itself to destroy Eleskeletus and summon 2 Level 5 monsters from deck. Eleskeletus when destroyed allows you to summon back the Tristaros from banishment.
  • Use the 2 Level 5 monsters to go into Cyber Dragon Nova and then Cyber Dragon Infinity. 
  • Set Cluster and pass turn. During your opponent's turn, when they activate a card, you can use Tristaros to summon another Level 5 and Synchro Summon F.A. Dawn Dragster.

Of course there are variations on the combo depending on the cards you already have in your hand, or what your goals are (for example, instead of sending Cluster you could send Crystron Thystvern for a monster search), but it's enough to get the idea. This 1-card combo only misses out on the Quariongandrax setup, but with the remaining cards in your hand it is often not hard to be able to do it.

That's all I have to say about this deck for now. If you want to see it in action, I've included a video with some nice replays from my climb to Master I. I hope you enjoy it!

Creator: Sabeque Miah

There is the deck I brought to my national with some updates after somes testings in locals!

The deck works pretty well as a good mid-range deck option, with many non-engine and decent match-up overall. However, the deck could lack in Go 2nd and against some handtraps/freespots that kills the strategy (Fuwalos, Purulia, Banishment, ...).

Concept of the Deck

  • We're on a Fiendsmith/Handtrap control deck : the goal is really to manage the pace of the game with those tools. It's the reason why the decklist relies a lot on the Fiendsmith engine than the Eviltwin one (a lot stronger, recursive, allow use to play throught many threats).
  • Twins remain still insane for the ability to draw many freespots and to bring disruptions during the opponent's turn, in conjuction with the Fiendsmith.
  • Freespots : the choise here is more to rely on active Handtrap for the opponent turn even by drawing them during this one (main reason why I run Veiler instead of Impermance). Charmies are not that important in the Deck (Fuwa is the more generic but you draw so much with the engines that you don't need more : you prefer high-impact freespots).
  • Bodies : Kisi-kil is now our main starter overall even with bodies on board. Futhermore, we like having additional bodies to OTK, go on higher Links, ... (Nibiru & Bystial).
  • Extra Deck : The Extra deck is pretty standard : there is for me only one flexspot (the second Lil-la). The Duke of Demise is for me mandatory because of his utility to play throught Nibiru, to give us extra plays with the normal summon.

Some Options

  • Main Deck : Adapt the freespot to the format. You can cut the Sanct for another freespot (I like Fiendsmith's Sanct to keep Engraver alive and to have some line under Droll even if the deck isn't that sensitive to it).
  • Extra Deck : Fiendsmith's Rextremende (Recovery, Interesting boss monster in some cases), a second Fiendsmith's Requiem  (good to keep the Fiendsmith Engine alive, more reliant to the Bystial and crow, but I don't have a second one atm), Knightmare Phoenix  (Backrow removal), Chaos Angel (to manage some towers like Detonator).
  • Side Deck : Shared Ride (go 1st to draw more freespot), D.D. Crow or other impactful spots for the current meta. Solemn Strike/Solemn Judgment are not that bad ti reinforce the Go 1st, which is not that impressive.

Hope you will enjoy!

deck_excerpt: you know what killed the dinosaurs?
deck_description:
With the new Jurrac support, one of my favorite decks, Dinos, now has a 1-card combo to get some saucy polays going. However, another deck I love that cares about Dinos is Ryu-Ge, the forgotten deck from Crossover Breakers. After seeing a deck list that combined Ryu-Ge with the new Jurrac support, I knew I had to cook something, and I even tweaked the list to give it a bit of sauce.

The list has the typical Ryu-Ge ratios (any list running more than 1 Kaiva is wilin'), though the Jurrac/Dino ratios are a bit different than the norm. Even if Misc ever comes off the limited list, running two Ovi and one Petite will always be the most optimal ratio for the combo. Also, I'm personally running Petite over Baby is to summon Pankratops if I'm doing the combo through Droll. UCT is UCT and needs no explanation.

While UCT may need no explanation, a certain monster in the extra deck does, and it honestly makes playing Jurrac with Dinos more worthwhile. Grenosaurus Giga-Cannon is a retrain of the rank 3 Grenosaurus, both of which are cards that see no play. Though, with Jurrac Stego's Dinosaur monster lock, this may change for Giga-Cannon. Since the Evolzars are Dragons, they can't be made, but instead, you could use two level 4 monsters to make Giga-Cannon and have it as pop fodder for UCT. But, why does this matter?

Well, when Giga-Cannon is destroyed, you can pop a card and burn your opponent for 1000. Dinos having a way to pop any card on-field along with having a way to cheese a win in time now is really cool. Plus, the Stego combo becomes Nib-proof if you open one of the one card starters for Ryu-Ge.

This variant of Ryu-Ge is easily one of my favorites and one I would recommend for anyone wanting to play Ryu-Ge or the new Jurrac cards.

Prepare for a truly unique dueling experience where the lines between order and chaos blur, and victory is always within reach.

deck_excerpt: ft. The Lv9 Contrast HERO Chaos
deck_description:
HERO is a very difficult archetype to incorporate with other archetypal non-HERO cards. The reason for this is because there are just so many different HERO cards that either lock you into specifically only being able to Summon HERO monsters from the Extra Deck like in the case of Vision HERO Faris or those that are only able to use their effects if you’ve only Summoned HERO monsters during the current turn like Xtra HERO Cross Crusader and Xtra HERO Infernal Devicer. Because of that, it has been really hard for me to try to make a Prediction Princess Deck with any of HERO’s 7 Level 9 monsters because the cards that I would need to get to them either lock you into HERO monsters in some capacity, they only function when played with a multitude of other HERO monsters and cards en masse, or they are just too specifically designed for HERO that it would be a significant detriment to try to use them outside of a dedicated HERO Deck. Also, keep in mind that 4 out of the 7 Level 9 HERO monsters are Triple Contact Fusion Neos monsters, which I was able to actually make work in an extremely jank way through the same Decklist as my Dark Sage Prediction Princess Deck, but since Isolde got banned, that all but is impossible now. Elemental HERO Core is probably the easiest one to Summon since all it requires is 3 Elemental HERO monsters as Fusion Material, but because it is an EARTH monster in a Fusion Deck that cannot access Synchros for Ib the World Chalice Justiciar and has to hard-draw World Legacy Monstrosity, that is also pretty bad. Elemental HERO Neos Kluger is the next easiest one to Summon except that it also has the issue of having to hard-draw Monstrosity and the fact that it was not easy to get Elemental HERO Neos and Yubel into rotation, although it might be very feasible now with the Supreme Darkness Evil HERO support. But even harder than Core, Kluger, and the Triple Contact Fusion Neos Monsters is Contrast HERO Chaos. It is a Level 9 DARK Warrior Fusion Monster who requires 2 Masked HERO monsters as Fusion Material, it is always treated as an Elemental HERO monster (thank God), and it must be Fusion Summoned and cannot be Special Summoned by other ways. While face-up on the field, it is also LIGHT Attribute, and as a soft once per turn during either player’s turn, it can target a face-up card on the field and negate its effects until the end of the turn. This card is impossibly hard to Summon considering that it needs 2 Masked HERO monsters, which only used to consist of Fusion Monsters that could only be Special Summoned by the effect of Mask Change. HERO Decks could make this card by going through 2 Masked HERO monsters and then using Favorite Contact to Fusion Summon this card on your opponent’s turn if they for some reason did not want to make Elemental HERO Shining Neos Wingman. But the easiest possible way to make this card turn 1 was to Gale Dogra pay 6000 Life Points to send 2 Masked HEROs from the Extra Deck to GY and then Miracle Fusion them into Contrast HERO Chaos. Thankfully, we now have Main Deck Masked HERO monsters from the OCG’s Tactical Try Pack which includes support for Dark Magician, Masked HEROs, and Mikanko (Here’s to hoping for an easier way to make Arahime the Manifested Mikanko). That, alongside the SUDA Evil HERO Support (which is just Dead-End Prison) makes it very easy to Summon Contrast HERO Chaos. 

The combos for this Deck are not weird, but there are many possible ways to get to full combo based on what your starting hand looks like. There are many hands that get you to full combo with many also giving you literally nothing. The combo I will be describing uses A Hero Lives and any Prediction Princess card, but I will pivot to what some of the other combos look like when I finish or at certain points. Let’s say we have A Hero Lives and Prediction Princess Tarotrei. Activate A Hero Lives and pay half your Life Points to Special Summon Elemental HERO Stratos from your Deck. Stratos activates to search for Vision HERO Vyon from Deck. Normal Summon Vyon and activate its effect to send Evil HERO Sinister Necrom from your Deck to the GY. Activate Sinister Necrom’s effect in GY, banishing it to Special Summon Evil HERO Dead-End Prison from Deck. Activate Dead-End Prison’s effect to send Elemental HERO Shadow Mist from Deck to GY. Shadow Mist triggers to search for Masked HERO Dusk Crow from Deck. Activate Vyon’s second effect, banishing Shadow Mist from GY to search Polymerization from Deck. Link Vyon and Dead-End Prison into Xtra HERO Wonder Driver. Activate Dusk Crow’s effect in hand, banishing Dead-End Prison from GY to Special Summon itself to any of your Monster Zones except the one that Wonder Driver points to. Dusk Crow activates on Special Summon to search for Masked HERO Furnace. Activate Poly to Fusion Summon Contrast HERO Chaos to the Zone that Wonder Driver points to. Chain Link 1 Wonder Driver (since its mandatory) targeting Poly in GY, Chain Link 2 Furnace in GY. Furnace Special Summons itself back from GY and Wonder Driver sets Poly from GY. Now, if we had another Dusk Crow in hand, we could activate Poly to Fusion Summon another Contrast HERO Chaos using it and the Furnace on field. But since we don’t we can just banish Wonder Driver, Stratos, and Furnace from field in order to Special Summon Trishula, the Dragon of Icy Imprisonment from our Extra Deck. That gives us 2 Level 9s on field to Xyz Summon Mereologic Aggreagator which sends Herald of the Arc Light from Extra Deck to GY for a Ritual search, and then it can reattach the Herald. Then, Linking off the Aggregator (who is presumably in the EMZ) for a Gravity Controller, we get another Ritual search. Because we opened Tarotrei, those Ritual searches will be for Prediction Princess Tarotreith and Underworld Ritual of Prediction which gives us full Prediction Princess combo. But let’s say that we did not open A Hero Lives. Stratos is no longer a part of our field before we make Trishula. That’s still fine as we can just activate the Poly that Wonder Driver set in order to Fusion Summon Trishula using Furnace, Wonder Driver, and Tarotrei in hand. Tarotrei being sent to the GY does not matter as Underworld Ritual can Ritual Summon from GY. But in the advent that we did not has Stratos or the Prediction Princess card in hand, if we drew World Legacy Monstrosity, we can activate it targeting Chaos in order to Special Summon Deus-X Krawler and Prediction Princess Bibliomuse from Deck which still translates to full combo. Now let’s say that you opened Vyon and 4 other cards that get you nowhere to combo. Go through the previous combo I mentioned, but after you Summon Dusk Crow and search for Furnace, activate Furnace in hand to search for Mask Change and then discard a card. You are now locked into HERO monsters, but you will still be able to make a decent endboard without the Prediction Princess cards. Proceed through the rest of the combo until you get back to the part where Wonder Driver sets Poly from GY and Furnace Special Summons itself back from GY. Activate Mask Change on Furnace to Special Summon Masked HERO Atomic from Extra Deck which Special Summons Dusk Crow from GY on Special Summon. Now, you could Link Summon Wonder Driver and Dusk Crow into Xtra HERO Dread Decimator to boost your Chaos and Atomic or you can proceed to the End Phase in which Atomic sets Mask Change from GY. Now, during your opponent’s turn,  you can Mask Change Dusk Crow into Masked HERO Dark Law which gives you Dark Law and Chaos as ways you can mess with your opponent. It’s not great, but it still beats ending on nothing.

For the Main Deck Monsters: 3 Prediction Princess Tarotrei, 1 Prediction Princess Tarotreith, and 3 Prediction Princess Bibliomuse. Tarotrei can Quick Effect flip a monster on field face-up or face-down and she can Special Summon a Flip Monster from hand or GY face-down during your End Phase. Tarotreith must either be Ritual Summoned or Special Summoned via Tarotrei's effect in the End Phase. Her Flip Effect Special Summons a Flip Monster from your Deck face-down and she can also Quick Effect flip any number of your monsters face-up or face-down. Bibliomuse can Special Summon herself back face-down after being Tributed and sent there. Her Flip Effect adds a Prediction Princess monster other than herself and a Ritual Spell from Deck to hand and while she is face-up on the field, your Ritual Monsters gain targeting and destruction protection from your opponent’s card effects. 1 Deus-X Krawler which negates all activated monster effects on your opponent's side of the field after it has been flipped face-up and if it is destroyed on field, you can search for a Level 9 monster with a different Type and Attribute. 1 Pot of the Forbidden which has a Flip Effect that lets you choose between Drawing 2 cards, returning all Spell/Traps on the field to the hand, destroying all monsters your opponent controls, or looking at your opponent's hand and shuffling a card from it back into the Deck. For the Evil HEROs, 1 each of Evil HERO Sinister Necrom and Evil HERO Dead-End Prison. Sinister Necrom can banish itself from GY to Special Summon an Evil HERO from hand or Deck other than another Sinister Necrom. This card is a hard brick that you do not want to draw as you want to keep it in Deck to send off of Vyon. Dead-End Prison has 1 effect that we are specifically using it for. You can send a HERO from your Deck to your GY as cost, and if you do, if you Fusion Summon a HERO monster this turn, Dead-End Prison can be used as a substitute Fusion Material monster for a specific monster. While this card may look like another copy of Vyon, the fact that you can use Vyon to send Sinister Necrom who Summons Dead-End Prison from Deck gives you another body on field while also giving you the ability to dump a HERO from Deck. However, it is another brick, but it doesn’t hurt as much to draw compared to Sinister Necrom as it can still translate to Dark Law or Contrast HERO Chaos at the very least. For the Masked HEROs: 1 Masked HERO Furnace and 3 Masked HERO Dusk Crow. Furnace can reveal itself in hand to search for a Mask Change or a Polymerization and then discard a card, but this effect locks you into HERO monsters for the Extra Deck the turn you use it. Also, if you Special Summon a non-FIRE HERO Fusion Monster, you can Special Summon it from hand or GY but banish it when it leaves the field. Dusk Crow can banish a HERO from GY to Special Summon itself from hand, and if it is Normal or Special Summoned you can search your Deck for a Masked HERO except for another copy of Dusk Crow. Then we have 3 Vision HERO Vyon which can send a HERO monster from Deck to GY on Normal or Special Summon, and you can also banish a HERO from GY to search for a Polymerization. 2 Elemental HERO Stratos which searches for a HERO monster on Summon. 1 Elemental HERO Shadow Mist which adds a Change Quick-Play Spell from Deck on Special Summon and if it is sent to the GY, you can add a HERO monster from your Deck to your hand. But you can only use 1 effect per turn and only once that turn. Finally, 3 Mulcharmy Fuwalos and 3 Droll & Lock Bird. 

Spell/Traps: 1 Polymerization. 1 Mask Change which targets a HERO you control and sends it to the GY to Special Summon a Masked HERO from your Extra Deck with the same original Attribute as that monster. 3 A Hero Lives which can pay half your Life Points to Special Summon a Level 4 or lower Elemental HERO from your Deck if you control no face-up monsters. Notably, this card is not once per turn, so if the first one gets negated, you can activate another. 1 Reinforcement of the Army. 3 Underworld Ritual of Prediction which can Ritual Summon a Prediction Princess Ritual Monster from hand or GY face-up or face-down and you can banish it from GY during the Standby Phase to Special Summon a non-Ritual Prediction Princess monster from Deck face-down. 3 World Legacy Monstrosity which can either Special Summon a Level 9 monster from your hand or target a Level 9 monster you control to Special Summon 2 Level 9 monsters from your Deck with a different type and Attribute, but with different names. 1 Pot of Prosperity. And 3 Infinite Impermanence.

Extra Deck: 1 Trishula, the Dragon of Icy Imprisonment. 2 Contrast HERO Chaos. 1 Masked HERO Atomic which must be Special Summoned using Mask Change. The first time it would be destroyed each turn, it is not. On Special Summon you can target a non-FIRE Masked HERO monster in your GY or banishment and Special Summon it, and during your End Phase, it can target and set a Change Quick-Play Spell from your GY. 1 Masked HERO Dark Law which must be Special Summoned with Mask Change. While it is face-up on the field, any card sent to your opponent’s GY is banished instead, and once per turn, if your opponent adds a card(s) from their Deck to their hand except during the Draw Phase or the damage step, you can banish a random card from your opponent’s hand. 2 Herald of the Arc Light which adds a Ritual Monster or Ritual Spell from your Deck to your hand if it is sent to the GY. 2 Mereologic Aggregator, 1 Laevateinn, Generaider Boss of Shadows, and 1 Jormungandr, Generaider Boss of Eternity. 1 Xtra HERO Dread Decimator which requires 2+ HEROs as material and it and any HEROs it points to gains 100 ATK for each HERO monster with a different name in your GY, also, it can deal piercing damage. 1 Xtra HERO Wonder Driver which requires 2 HERO monsters as material. If a HERO is Normal or Special Summoned to your zone it points to, it must target a Polymerization Spell or a Fusion Spell or a Change Quick-Play Spell in your GY and set it. Also, if it is destroyed by battle or an opponent’s card effect and sent to the GY, you can Special Summon a HERO from your hand. 1 S:P Little Knight and 1 Gravity Controller. 

Side Deck: 3 Nibiru, the Primal Being, 2 Mulcharmy Purulia, 3 Ash Blossom & Joyous Spring, 2 Lightning Storm, 2 Dark Ruler No More, and 3 Evenly Matched.

deck_excerpt: Blasting the Ruins OTK ft. Tethys
deck_description:
Hello there! In this deck, we will have a blast with our beloved angel Tethys. What are you waiting for?

 

 

Gameplan

1) Bring forth Tethys by replacing Capricious/Aces/Corobane and draw your whole deck...

  • Whenever you draw a Fairy, reveal it to draw another card with Tethys. You can keep it going until you can't draw anymore.
  • If you hit non-Fairy, you stop movement. So, continue with Ixchel and alike to trigger Tethys again.
  • Know that card draw has to be caused by an effect, not as cost, in order to draw a card with Tethys. For example, using "Upstart Goblin", seen in Side Deck, won't do any help for Tethys but "Into the Void" will. Remember this rule well.

2) Special Summon Tarai + Mudora via their abilities and XYZ Summon Wolf with them as materials. Use Wolf to pop Chicken.

3) Set all Traps and end your turn. When it's your opponent's turn, activate them to blast your opponent.

deck_excerpt: Does the new PUNK support from BLMM makes the strategy competitively viable?
deck_description:
Incredibly powerful PUNK support finally comes out for the TCG with Battles of Legend - Monster Mayhem and I thought I would give my favourite cyberpunks a test run with the current meta! for the Rising Scale functions as an incredible extender summoning itself and another PUNK from deck, allowing these Cyberpunks to power through interruptions and handtraps. JAM FEVER! grants PUNK a unique monster negate as well, raising the power level of their endboards and insulating plays through handtraps like Nibiru. 
 
Lacrima the Crimson Tears along with Agnumday also released with Wrath of the Tyrants, meaning Fiendsmith is now completely available to any strategy that can run it! Fiendsmith allows PUNK to play through handtraps especially Droll, since Fiendsmith cards summon from deck or send to the GY rather than adding them to the hand.  If your PUNK deck was stopped by too much interruption, you can pivot to the Fiendsmith engine instead with any two bodies thanks to Moon of the Closed Heaven! 
 
Combining the excellent new PUNK support with nearly full power Fiendsmith the PUNK duelist can end on a multilayered board with 8+ interruptions in the field, hand, GY and backrow! 
 
Want to see the deck in action? Scroll to the very bottom for the Youtube video!
 
ARCHETYPES AND DECKBUILDING
 
In all my testing, I found that the PUNK strategy functions very well as a compact 40 card deck because of the prevalence of Mulcharmies and Droll. There are 13 copies of Ze Amin (3 Ze Amin, 1 Ogre, 3 Foxy Tune, 3 Rising Scale and 3 Emergency Teleport) giving the duelist a fair chance of drawing into it with their starting hand. 6
 
The two archetypes in this deck are of course PUNK (16 cards) and Fiendsmith (6 cards). PUNK forms the main strategy and Fiendsmith is essentially the backup crutch the deck falls on if you get droll'd. Fiendsmith also adds another layer of powerful interruption since it converts two of your extra bodies at the end of your PUNK combo into Caesar (double special summon negate) or Desirae (omni-negate). 
 
Due to the increased consistency given to PUNK thanks to Rising Scale giving three more starter/extenders, more staples can be jammed into the deck. 17 staple cards are used in this deck, with 16 of them are handtraps. 
 
COMBOS AND GAMEPLAN
 
Despite the introduction of Rising Scale and JAM FEVER, the strategy of PUNK remains the same - interrupt your opponent as much as possible while building as much resource advantage as you can with multiple draws and searches through your multiple engines. The turn after, if your opponent hasn't surrendered yet, both PUNK and Fiendsmith have massive follow-up to enable an easy OTK. If your Fiendsmith cards are still in the GY and Field, they can recur and resummon themselves to generate a lot of attack while simultaneously picking apart your opponent's board! The PUNK cards have follow-up to, since Jam Session and Amazing Dragon is on the field and Dragon Drive is in the GY. Both engines can OTK independently!
 
The combo for this strategy is the standard PUNK combo -> Fiendsmith combo via the two spare bodies on the field. This is possible using a singular Ze Amin!
 
PUNK Ze Amin = Draw 3 cards (several handtraps in hand) + JAM FEVER! (monster negate destroy) + Desirae (omninegate) or High Wave King Caesar/Paradise (double summon negate and targeted send)
  1. (The following is standard PUNK combo using new support) Summon Ze Amin. Ze Amin searches for Rising Scale.
  2. Link summon Almiraj using Ze Amin.
  3. Summon Rising Scale from hand using Ze Amin in the GY. 
  4. Activate Rising Scale's on-summon effect to summon Sharakusai from deck.
  5. Sharakusai fusion summons Rising Carp, using Sharakusai + Rising Scale. 
  6. Tribute Rising Carp to summon Deer Note and Wa Gon from deck. 
  7. Activate Wa Gon's effect to search for Jam Session from deck. 
  8. Activate Jam Session. 
  9. Synchro summon Dragon Drive using Wa Gon + Deer Note. 
  10. CL1 Dragon Drive to search for Ze Amin from deck, CL2 Deer Note to summon Rising Carp from GY. 
  11. Jam Session's trigger effect draws you 1 card. 
  12. XYZ summon JAM FEVER! using Dragon Drive + Rising Carp.
  13. Activate JAM FEVER!'s effect by detaching Dragon Drive to draw 1 card. 
  14. Jam Session's trigger effect draws you 1 card a second time. 
  15. Activate Jam Session's effect to summon Ze Amin from hand by banishing a PUNK monster from the GY. 
  16. (The following is the Fiendsmith combo) 
  17. Link summon Moon of the Closed Heaven using Rising Scale + Ze Amin.
  18. Moon of the Closed Heaven is FULL FIENDSMITH COMBO! You don't need me to detail you on this part, you've probably seen and done this plenty of times before. You can either end on High Wave King Caesar's double summon negate + Crimson Tear's mill of Paradise OR you can summon Desirae for an on-field omni-negate. 
From 1 Ze Amin, you get up to 5 interruptions and a draw 3 (potentially handtraps)! Of course, this is the simplest endboard. Endboards get better and stronger the more extenders you have. It's possible on the biggest boards to end on 10+ interruptions with 3 draws if you're allowed to combo uninterrupted. You'll generally have 5+ cards in hand if you're allowed to full combo since you draw 2-3 cards, so you'll have plenty of handtraps and follow-up.
 
If you're interrupted mid-combo by a turn-ending card, your plan B is to pivot into the Fiendsmith combo or sit on Psychic End Punisher.
 
Going second, hopefully your 16 handtraps simplify the gamestate enough to the point your in-engine combo, supplemental engines and extenders are enough to allow you to play the game through your opponent's interruption. 
 
Remember that 1 single uninterrupted Ze Amin + discard is an OTK!
 
1 Ze Amin + 1 discard can make Amazing Dragon synchro summoned with Rising Carp + Ze Amin clears 2-4 cards from the board while enabling it to attack twice with 3600ATK accompanied with Dragon Drive (2700ATK) totalling 9900 ATK! 
 
PUNK Ze Amin + 1 discard = 3600ATK Amazing Dragon that can attack twice, bounce 4 cards your opponent controls with Amazing Dragon, 2700 ATK Dragon Drive.
  1. (The following is standard PUNK combo) Summon Ze Amin. Ze Amin searches for Foxy Tune. 
  2. Foxy Tune effect to discard 1 card in hand to summon Sharakusai from deck. 
  3. Sharakusai fusion summons Rising Carp, using Sharakusai + Ze Amin. 
  4. Tribute Rising Carp to summon Deer Note and Wa Gon from deck. 
  5. Activate Wa Gon's effect to search for Jam Session from deck. 
  6. Activate Jam Session. 
  7. Synchro summon Dragon Drive using Wa Gon + Deer Note. 
  8. CL1 Dragon Drive to search for Ze Amin from deck, CL2 Deer Note to summon Rising Carp from GY. 
  9. Jam Session's trigger effect draws you 1 card. 
  10. Special summon Ze Amin from hand using Jam Session.
  11. Synchro Summon Amazing Dragon using Ze Amin + Rising Carp.
  12. CL1 Amazing Dragon to bounce up to 4 cards your opponent controls, CL2 Rising Carp targeting Amazing Dragon enabling it to attack twice, CL3 Ze Amin targeting Amazing Dragon boosting it's ATK by 600.
GENERAL TIPS
  • If you get hit by Droll & Lockbird, Dimension Shifter, or even Maxx "C," your typical plan B is to pivot into Fiendsmith combo or synchro summon Psychic End Punisher/Juraishin. 
  • If you suspect your opponent has handtraps like Ash or Veiler, bait out you opponent's by playing your Fiendsmith and Kashtira cards first. Afterwards you can full combo with PUNK! 
  • Other good supplemental engines that synergize with PUNK are Horus, Millenium, Bystial and Gold Pride! Feel free to replace Kashtira/Fiendsmith with these strategies. 
  • With Necroquip Princess' effect, you can draw an additional card when you activate Ogre Dance or Foxy Tune's search. In that scenario, you play your Fiendsmith cards first.
  • If you successfully resolve Psy-Frame handtrap during your turn, you can synchro it with Driver to summon Dragon Drive and search for your PUNK starters. 
Want to see the deck in action? Scroll to the very bottom for the Youtube video!
 
CONCLUDING REMARKS
 
I have been playing PUNK since it came out in Grand Creators back at 2023, and it's one of the most fun decks I've ever had the pleasure of piloting! It's 2025, and it's incredible these cyberpunk performers get amazingly powerful support! PUNK can now comfortably catch up to the big meta decks plaguing Masterduel ladder like White Forest, Yubel, Snake-Eyes and Blue-Eyes quite easily thanks to Rising Scale, JAM FEVER! and full power Fiendsmith. 
 
GLHF Duelists!

Play first and summon powerful Clear Wing synchro monsters using Speedroids combos, so you can interrupt your opponent's turn. 

Some combos:

- Cork Shooter Combo: If you have Terrortop in your hand, and no monster in your field, special summon it, add Taketomborg, special summon it, activate it, special summon Red-Eyed Dice, activate it, change Terrortop lvl to 2, summon Cork Shooter, activate and summon Terrortop and Red-Eyed Dice, now you can change Terrorop lvl again, by changing it to 4, summon Hagoita, then you can summon Crystal Wing Synchro Dragon or Kitedrake depending on wich you need. If you change Terrortop lvl to 6, you can summon Clear Wing Fast Dragon and then summon Crystal Clear Wing Synchro Dragon. You could also use Clear Wing Synchro Dragon instead if you can summon Glider to summon it from the GY and then summon Crystal Clear Wing Over Synchro Dragon, otherwise by using Clear Wing Fast Dragon you could pendulum summon it later. This combo can be started through other methods, for example, having Red-Eyed Dice in your hand and normal summoning Horse Stilts, or having it in the GY and normal summon Double YoYo. 

- Clackernel Combo: If you have a speedroid card in the GY, a lvl 3 monster in the field and Clackernel in your hand: You can activate Clackernel, activate its effects to put Wing Synchron in your other pendulum zone, then pendulum summon if you can and want to, after that activate Wing Synchron effect to summon a Clear Wing Synchro Dragon, activate Clackernel effect to summon another Clackernel, now you can summon Crystal Clear Wing Over Synchro Dragon.

- Marble Machine Combo: if you have Red-Eyed Dice or CarTurbo in your hand or GY, and Marble Machine in your hand: Normal summon it, add Taketomborg, special summon it, activate it, summon Den-Den Daiko Duke, summon Hagoita, activate Den-Den Daiko in your GY and summon the tuner you have, if is it Red-Eyed Dice, you can make the Cork Shooter Combo, or if is it CarTurbo, you can summon a lvl 8 synchro monster. 

- Band Shooter Combo: If you are not so lucky to make one of the previous combo, but at least can summon 2 monsters you can summon Band Shooter, activate it, banish Chanbara, and show Marble Machine and Terrortop, then you can use Band Shooter to normal summon the one you added to your hand. Ultra Hound can be used to do this combo, if you normal summon it you can send Dupligate to the GY, and activate its effects to summon it as a monster, then you can summon Band Shooter. If you have Red-Eyed Dice in your hand, you could use Ultra Hound to send Den-Den Daiko to GY and use it to summon Red-Eyed Dice and make the Cork Shooter Combo.

Unleash a captivating performance where Spellcasters, Beasts, and Aquatic horrors intertwine to dominate the duel! This isn't just a deck; it's a meticulously crafted fusion of Witchcrafter elegance, Artmegia's divine artistry, Tearlaments' abyssal power, and Lunalight's feral grace. Prepare to confound your opponent with the Witchcrafters, weaving a web of spell-based disruptions and resource recursion that will leave them guessing your every move. Just as they adapt, the Artmegia will reveal their divine might, locking down the field with continuous effects and summoning formidable deities. But the true spectacle begins when the Tearlaments plunge into action. Watch as your graveyard becomes a tempest of card effects, effortlessly Fusion Summoning powerful monsters like Kaleido-Heart at a moment's notice, disrupting your opponent's plays and fueling your own. And when the time is right, the Lunalights pounce, transforming into an unstoppable force of multi-attacking Fusion Beasts that will shatter your opponent's defenses! With a robust arsenal of hand traps to negate crucial plays and powerful Field Spells to establish your dominance, this deck offers unparalleled adaptability and control. Whether you're gracefully out-resourcing your opponent with Witchcrafters, strategically summoning with Artmegia, chaining devastating combos with Tearlaments, or delivering the final, ferocious blow with Lunalights, you'll always have the perfect answer. Master this intricate dance of destruction and creation, and become the maestro of the duel!

Welcome! Have you ever wondered how to win with Vennominaga? If you do, you found the right place!

 

 

Gameplan

1) At one point, activate Burning to skip your opponent's Main Phase 1. Then, play Black Garden.

2) With your summoning methods, plant at least three flowers to opposing side with Garden. Jigabyte and Dugares might help you achieve this goal.

3) When you have summoned Unicorn and it is the only monster at your side, use its ability to bounce it back to your Extra Deck. This lets you play "A Wild Monster Appears!" to cheat out Vennominaga.

4) Set Unleashed and end your turn. When it's your opponent's Draw Phase, activate Unleashed. Since you have skipped your opponent's Main Phase 1 and Unleashed forces your opponent's monsters to attack, your opponent will be locked into Battle Phase.

5) Let them tackle into Vennominaga with flowers you have planted and victory is yours!

Panik is a Dark and Fiend user duelist. Dark World archetype is pretty limited to Edison Format and a lot of cards can make you brick. I've tried a lot of different approaches to make this deck worth it and that's my final built. In the Youtube video you might see some different cards or ratios , I am sorry... One of the biggest weakness of Dark World monsters is that they don't have actual effects on field and can lose to other Boss monsters with higher ATK. Solidarity is a big plus and a reason to play only Fiend monsters. Necro Gardna and Plaguespreader Zombie can banish themselves from graveyard. Morphing Jar might be the only card we miss in this deck. For even more options you can look in your side deck.

The biggest problem with Dark World is the ruling or the "miss timing" rule. If you discard for cost , the effect can't be activated and cards like Raigeki Break or Lightning Vortex are not usable...

Stygian Security and Giant Germ can give you some time to set a play and special summon some cheap bodies on field without cost. Stygian Sergeants is a pretty cool card and valuable card that can turn the tides of the duel with some Solidarity cards on field. 

Dark World, GOLDD / SILLVA are basically the same card so chose which you like most art-wised. You really need patience and practise to play this deck. I've tried Caius, the Shadow Monarch + Battle Fader too. It was good, but it can brick. You can remove Allure of Darkness for +1 Hammer Shot maybe.

deck_description: Ancient might unites with arcane mastery for timeless duels

Make a strong board on your first turn with this recipe. 

Some combos:

- Fiendsmith Combo: Summon Fabled Lurrie, you can do it with One For One or using Fiendsmith's Tract and discarding it. Summon Requiem, activate its effect to summon Lacrima, activate it and send Engraver to GY, then activate its effects to special summon it. Summon Sequence, activate it and summon Desirae. Summon Agnumday, activate it and summon Desirae, then activate Sequence in your GY and equip it to Desirae.

- Snake-Eye Combo: Summon Ash, you can do it using One For One, or using Original Sinful Spoils, wich you can add it summoning Diabellstar The Black Witch. Activate Ash and add Poplar, activate it to summon it and add Dramatic Snake-Eye Chase, activate ash to summon Flamberge Dragon, use Poplar to put one of them in the Spell/Trap Zone, activate Drmatic Chase to add Snake-Eye Diabellstar, activate it and summon it, then use the 2 Snake-Eye monsters in your Spell/Trap Zone to summon Doomed Dragon. Now you can summon Number 38 using Snake-Eye Diabellstar and Doomed Dragon, or summon I:P Masquerena using Flamberge Dragon and other monster, use Flamberge Dragon effect to summon 2 lvl 1 Snake-Eye monsters, and use them to summon Apollousa with I:P Masquerena.

- Centur-Ion Combo: Summon Primera, activate it and add Stand Up Centur-Ion!, activate it and add Gargoyle II, activate it to special summon it, then summon Auxila and use its effect to add Centur-Ion Bonds, activate it and put Gargoyle II in your Spell/Trap Zone, then in the End Phase activate Auxila to put Primera in your Spell/Trap Zone. Now you can summon Primera and Gargoyle during your opponent's turn, and use Stand Up Centur-Ion! to summon Crimson Dragon, then activate it, target Auxila, so you can summon Cosmic Blazar Dragon or Red Supernova Dragon, wichever you prefer. You can start this combo using Trudea to add Primera, Trudea is searchable with Bonfire or Stand Up Centur-Ion. In the case you already have Stand Up Centur-Ion! before summon Primera, you could use Primera to add Gargoyle II and summon it sending Trudea to GY. If you already have Centur-Ion Bonds in your hand, you could summon Legatia instead of Auxila. If you did the Snake-Eye Combo before, and you still have Flamberge Dragon in the field, you could activate its effect to put one monster from your GY in your Spell/Trap Zone, then synchro summon using Primera and Flamberge Dragon, activate its effect to summon the 2 Snake-Eye monsters from your GY, and use then to summon Masquerena, then use Dramatic Chase in the GY to summon the monster you have in your Spell/Trap Zone, so you can use Masquerena to summon Little Knight in your opponent's turn.

This deck is meant to be a deck for Pegasus that doesn't use the toons or eyes restrict.

Please note that the Deck Master is Beautunaful Princess. The extra cards in the Side are cards I am considering through testing - I have not played this in paper yet.

I've been playing water pile for over 10 years now - let's make it in Domain! There are a handful of goal board pieces for the deck:

- For stun/floodgates, barrier statue (prima donna) and General Raiho (lancea) are key.

- For protection, toad, gaios, chengying, mermail king, mudragon(considering) and dragite(considering) are key.

- For card draw/value/consistency, Bubble Reef, Abysslacia and Crocodragon(considering) are key.

- For combo/recursion, abysstrite, poseidra abyss, coral anemone, halq, monoceros (considering), norden (considering) are key.

- For board breakers, poseidra abyss, zealantis(using coral anemone) are key.

 

For a game plan, you can generally make a small board combining a few pieces listed above to elicit interaction from the table. Use your big engine to recur board pieces and continue to make small boards until your opponents run out of resources, then make a floodgate/stun board with some protection behind it to simplify the board state. If needed, a board breaker line can seal the game from here. Using poseidra abyss will generally wipe 1 player's board, and coral anemone + zealantis can wipe the whole board before attempting a signature OTK line using the plethora of potent main deck options.

deck_excerpt: The most fun way to play pyros that has ever existed.
deck_description:
There really isn't a main character of this deck. You can win with the Ashened, Volcanic, or Diabell/Snake-Eye package and they all can play into each other. Only important thing to consider is to save your Ashened package for last because it will lock you out of the non pyro extra deck monsters.

You can look up any of the old Snake-Eye combo videos to understand the Snake-Eye package. You're basically just summoning a million things to link climb and end up with your pyro monsters on the field or in the graveyard. 

Volcanic is pretty cool in this deck because it basically puts volcanic bodies on the board or in the graveyard. When you end up with volcanics on the board you can use them to link climb or fusion summon via your ashened package or super poly package. When they're in the graveyard they're volcanic emperor targets. 

Ashened is the one that will throw your opponents for a loop since nobody knows how Ashened works or pays attention to it. Fusion Veidos wipes backrow, can't be destroyed by card effects or targeted by monster effects, quick effect destroys a face up card, and gains 500 attack for each material used to summon it when summoned by the Endlessness trap. Super Poly really messes people up with the Ashened package because the field spell causes all of their monsters to be targets for summoning the pyro fusion monsters. 

There are multiple recycling effects in each package that set you up for grind game if things get dicey.

deck_excerpt: Time Thief x Vanquish Soul! A fun deck for those who want dynamic and non-linear game play!
deck_description:
If you aren't comfortable with 42 cards here are some cards you can chop off to make it a nice 40: "Time thief hack", "Raigeki", and "Infernoble arms-durendal" but you can mix and match until you get the ratio's you want. Have you ever looked at a vanquish soul deck list and thought: " Why are they all similar and run degenerate cards like shifter?" or running high risk cards like pot of desires or extravagence where they banish random cards that could have been used to go into other combo's. 

Well here is something different and using the utility of Vanquish Souls recursion and engine to control the state of the board with cards like time thief, using Vanquish souls unique ability to have a 2nd win con through burning your oppenent, or even board wiping and OTKing your oppenent! Even if you go 2nd into a board you can likely come out on top.

IT SHOULD BE NOTED: Vanquish Soul by itself is already a very difficult deck for beginners and you MUST know the match ups and choke points of your opponents deck to succeed and this version is no different. Especially since this is a more control orriented deck (Which can be used very offensively if you so please but that requires a more specific board state) you will need to take note of when and what you want to be disrupting and also what you can do on the crack back. Wether you have the angle to kill with your monsters on field or if you can inflict damage to your opponent through cards like Borger or Snow devil.

Here is a combo guide created by this reddit user for vanquish souls in case you need an idea of what to do: https://www.reddit.com/r/masterduel/comments/18rwc4k/basic_vanquish_soul_combo_guides_for_beginners/#lightbox

Also, here are some packages/ other extra deck monsters that could be helpful if you wanna go off the beaten path a little bit:

Lancer package (Full armored dark knight lancer, Full armored crystalizedzero lancer (Optional), Xyz Armor fortress, Armored XYZ, and Full-armored xyz (Or any other Armored cards) 

Extra deck monsters (These haven't been tested but in theory they could be fun additions: Scareclaw Tri-heart (For more control orriented play with his forcing other monsters into defense position), Knightmare goblin (For more extension when co-linked with "Rock of the Vanquisher" due to his even trade of discard 1, draw 1 which can discard a time thief card that can activate in the GY and draw into engine or non-engine and also an additonal normal summon which can get your rank 4's online.), and finally Salamangreat almiraj (Can send "Time Thief Bezel Ship" or "Time Thief Temporwhal" if they are your only normal summons since they have GY effects. Also, allows for an S:P play if you are very desperate.)

deck_excerpt: Some Animals and a Weeb summon God
deck_description: This is a deck I made in tired vision, Need more playtesting though

Better build of my earlier version, can setup some nasty boards. Sadly board breakers will destroy us, but few people play them at the moment. Non-engine and side are based on what I have and tailored to my locals (Maliss, Memento and Ryzeal but also some rogue decks) so you can change them however you like, Bystial Magnamhut and Bystials can be very nice given that Materiactors are dragons.

The deck is built to have as many pushes as possible to play better around most 1 for 1 HTs. Of course Nibiru, the Primal Being, Mulcharmy Fuwalos and Mulcharmy Purulia are problematic for this deck as well as Droll & Lock Bird depending on the hand so it can be rough sometimes.

Still, even considering all of this, I believe it's a very fun deck: stacking the top to draw what you need or adding HTs as material to Materiactor Exagard so you can get them later is very cool.

There's no one set one card combo as it depends a lot on what's your starter and what you find with Meltdown, but the idea is get to Materiactor Exagard first, summon Materiactor Zeptwing and get Materiactor Meltdown, from there it all depends on how you got here and what other pieces of engine you have in hand.

deck_excerpt: We dance to the requiem, roaring with life and beauty
deck_description: Deck by me, Lunalights are one of my favorites

Make your Deskbot monster gain very high ATK power and beat your opponent in one Battle Phase.

Some advices:

- You can make these combos with Urgent Schedule:

1- By summoning 009 and 001, you can summon Deskbot Jet, use its effect to summon 002, and then you can add the deskbot card you need.

2- By summoning 002 and any other, you can use 002 to summon Clockwork Knight, if you have Clockwork Night in your hand before summon it, activate it, so when Clockwork Knight is summoned you can use its effect to send the activated Clockwork Night to GY and add other to your hand, then you can use the Clockwork Night in the GY to add one monster to your hand. You can use Clockwork Knight's effect to summon 002 from GY by tributing the other monster you have, then you can use 002 to add one Deskbot card to your hand.

3- By summoning any pair of monster, you can summon Ancient Gear Ballista, then use its effect to add Ancient Gear Box to your hand, and use Ancient Gear Box to add one deskbot monster to your hand. It would be great if you summoned 001, because you could summon it later.

- Use foolish burial goods to send Clockwork Night to GY, and use it to add one monster to you hand. 

- If have 003 in your hand, you could summon it, activate it to summon 002 and then add one Deskbot card to your hand, then you can make the Clockwork Knight combo with those two monsters so you can add another Deskbot card to your hand. You could make the Ancient Gear Ballista combo instead, but if you have Clockwork Night in your hand Clockwork Knight its better.

- The goal of these combos its let you add two pendulum monsters (preferable 005 and 006, because if something happens and they are destroyed you could summon/add a Deskbot monster from your GY) and 009 (008 or 007 depending on the situation, they are a good option if you have some Deskbot monsters in your GY, or cant use 009. 007 its the better option when your opponent's monsters are all in defense position, or the ones in attack position have too high ATK). Then pendulum summon as many monsters as you can (remember let one zone free if you have 001 in GY). After that use 009 effect and 003 effect targeting 009 to make it the strongest as possible.

- If you already have the neccesary monsters, you can add Deskbot Base to increase your monsters ATK.

A zombie build to help power up Slifer the Sky Dragon

In terms of building a Prediction Princess Deck, Magnifistorm is not the most friendly archetype to work with, specifically because you would rather see a hand that consists mainly of their cards rather than a hand that potentially has a bunch of Ritual and Flip Monsters mixed into it. While that is the case, it is still easy enough to work with. The biggest issue that I currently am having with this Magnifistorm Prediction Princess Deck is that I wish there was an in-archetype Extra Deck pay-off for Magnifistorm, one that would further help facilitate their plays. I was really lost on how to combine these 2 archetypes for a while until I settled on Tribute Summoning their Level 9’s as the most consistent way of getting them onto the field, at least in this Deck as opposed to an actual Magnifistorm Deck. I do really believe that this Deck will improve by a lot once we get some Magnifistorm support, not that it desperately needs it, but for the purposes of combining it with another archetype, one that does mind their WIND-lock on Magnifistorming Crothea, the archetype needs some other tools to access. 

Magnifistorm has 2 Level 9 monsters: Magnifistorm Great Pyre Phonix and Magnifistorm Vortex Beauty Valrune. Pyre Phonix is a Level 9 WIND Pyro monster that can Special Summon itself from your hand if a Quick-Play Spell Card is activated and if one is activated while it is on the field, it can target up to 2 cards your opponent controls and shuffle them into the Deck. While it is in the GY and a Mystical Space Typhoon is activated, it can Special Summon itself from the GY. Vortex Beauty is a Level 9 WIND Aqua monster that can also Special Summon itself from your hand if a Quick-Play Spell Card is activated and if a Mystical Space Typhoon is activated while it is in the GY, it can Special Summon itself from the GY. While it is on field, when your opponent activates a monster effect while MST is in your GY, you can Quick Effect negate that effect, and then if there are 2 or more copies of MST in your GY, you can destroy that monster. Both of these cards are pretty good, but in the context of this Deck, I would say that Pyre Phonix is the better one as it can act as both interruption and removal. While Valrune can theoretically negate an Ash Blossom that is activated in response to the activation of a World Legacy Monstrosity targeting Valrune, Valrune requires that MST is in your GY to use its effect which is something that is not the easiest or most optimal thing to set-up if you are going first. However, we still can, and are, playing both in this Deck. This Deck does function relatively well, but I am sure it will get better once more support comes out, so this is more or less a preliminary version of the Deck.

Magnifistorming Suen by itself is a 1-card combo that gets you to either of the Level 9 Magnifistorm monsters. All that is needed left is World Legacy Monstrosity, which we can either pray on hard-drawing or search through Ib the World Chalice Justiciar. Assault Synchron and either Suen or Magnifistorming Erdam gets us to Ib without using our Normal Summon, so Tribute Summoning the Level 9 is still the play. In that case, I will only be explaining the combo that doesn’t use Ib, and that requires Magnifistorming Suen and World Legacy Monstrosity. Special Summon Suen from hand and activate its effect to search for Magnifistorming Stanza Tribute. Activate Stanza Tribute to search for Mangifistorming Erdam. Special Summon Erdam from hand and activate its effect to search for let’s say Magnifistorm Great Pyre Phonix. Tribute Summon Pyre Phonix by tributing both Erdam and Suen. Activate Monstrosity targeting Pyre Phonix to Special Summon Prediction Princess Bibliomuse and Deus-X Krawler from Deck. After that, it is the same old Prediction Princess combo as I always go through. Xyz Deus-X and Pyre Phonix into Mereologic Aggregator (into the EMZ) who sends Herald of the Arc Light from Extra Deck to GY on Xyz Summon. Herald triggers to search for Prediction Princess Tarotrei. Aggregator activates again, targeting Herald in GY, and detaching 1 to reattach Herald from GY. Link Aggregator into Gravity Controller. Herald hits the GY again and triggers to search for Underworld Ritual of Prediction. Activate Underworld Ritual tributing Bibliomuse to Ritual Summon Tarotrei. Bibliomuse triggers in GY off of being tributed in order to Special Summon herself back face-down. Tarotrei activates to flip Bibliomuse face-up which triggers her Flip Effect to search for another Underworld Ritual and Prediction Princess Tarotreith. Activate the second Underworld Ritual tributing Bibliomuse to Ritual Summon Tarotreith face-down. End Phase: Tarotrei activates her effect to Special Summon Deus-X from GY face-down. During your opponent’s Standby Phase, banish Underworld Ritual from GY to Special Summon Bibliomuse from Deck face-down and activate Tarotrei’s Quick Effect to flip Tarotreith face-up. On a new chain, Tarotreith’s Flip Effect Special Summons Pot of the Forbidden from the Deck face-down. Then, Tarotreith can Quick Effect flip your face-down Deus-X, Bibliomuse, and Pot of the Forbidden face-up for their effects. 

For the Main Deck Monsters: 3 Prediction Princess Tarotrei, 1 Prediction Princess Tarotreith, and 3 Prediction Princess Bibliomuse. Tarotrei can Quick Effect flip a monster on field face-up or face-down and she can Special Summon a Flip Monster from hand or GY face-down during your End Phase. Tarotreith must either be Ritual Summoned or Special Summoned via Tarotrei's effect in the End Phase. Her Flip Effect Special Summons a Flip Monster from your Deck face-down and she can also Quick Effect flip any number of your monsters face-up or face-down. Bibliomuse can Special Summon herself back face-down after being Tributed and sent there. Her Flip Effect adds a Prediction Princess monster other than herself and a Ritual Spell from Deck to hand and while she is face-up on the field, your Ritual Monsters gain targeting and destruction protection from your opponent’s card effects. I did consider playing 3 Tarotreith and 1 Tarotrei in this Deck for the sole purpose of not using Tarotreith’s Flip Effect to Special Summon Pot of the Forbidden on the opponent’s turn in exchange for potentially being able to activate a Mystical Space Typhoon on the opponent’s turn to trigger either Magnifistorm Great Pyre Phonix or Magnifistorm Vortex Beauty Valurne in GY to bring themselves back for interruption. In that case, Underworld Ritual still Special Summons another Bibliomuse from Deck face-down, but Tarotreith will be used to flip both Bibliomuse and Deus-X face-up whereas Tarotrei’s Quick Effect to flip a monster on field face-up or face-down can be used as a Book of Moon-esque form of interruption. And you realistically can choose to do this instead by just changing the ratios. Normally, I would still be summoning Pot of the Forbidden and instead be using I:P Masquerena to go into like a LINK-4 or higher monster to clear up space on our field, but that requires you to draw a Quick-Play Spell in addition to the aforementioned Magnifistorming Suen and World Legacy Monstrosity or Assault Synchron. Then, you would need specifically MST to bring back either of the Level 9’s on the opponent’s turn. While this can be achieved and we are playing the Extra Deck monsters to facilitate this, I’d rather go with the more simpler option in most scenarios. 1 Deus-X Krawler which negates all activated monster effects on your opponent's side of the field after it has been flipped face-up and if it is destroyed on field, you can search for a Level 9 monster with a different Type and Attribute. 1 Pot of the Forbidden which has a Flip Effect that lets you choose between Drawing 2 cards, returning all Spell/Traps on the field to the hand, destroying all monsters your opponent controls, or looking at your opponent's hand and shuffling a card from it back into the Deck. 1 Magnifistorm Great Pyre Phonix and 1 Magnifistorm Vortex Beauty Valurne. Something to keep in mind about their effect to Special Summon themselves from hand if a Quick-Play Spell Card is activated is that if you have both in hand and you activate Phonix’s effect to Special Summon itself, you cannot chain Valrune’s effect to also Special Summon it, and vice versa. This has to do with the trigger effect conditions, so make sure you don’t actually make an illegal play once this comes out in paper. 3 Magnifistorming Suen and 3 Magnifistorming Erdam. Both are inherent Special Summons from the hand if your have MST in your GY or your opponent controls no Spell/Traps. On Normal or Special Summon, Suen searches a Magnifistorm Spell/Trap from Deck or an MST while Erdam searches for a Magnifistorm monster or an MST from Deck other than itself. Suen is the more important, monster, especially since it can be searched off of Fire Formation - Tenki, but it is also good to max out on Erdam. Opening with both Suen and Erdam means that both can Special Summon themselves from your hand for free while the Quick-Play Spell Suen searches can be used to trigger the effect of the Level 9 Magnifistorm monster Erdam searches to Special Summon it from hand. This then translates to more material on field for some Link plays. Finally, 3 Assault Synchron. So why Assault Synchron of all Level 2 Tuner monsters? Well, for one, we are depending on Tribute Summoning out Level 9 monster to get it out onto the field. So, not having a Level 2 Tuner we can Special Summon for free means that we don’t have our Normal Summon available to Tribute Summon. Assault Synchron can also be searched by Tuning, but that brings up the question of why didn’t I choose to play a Level 2 Psychic Tuner and Emergency Teleport? While E-Tele is a Quick-Play Spell that can trigger the hand effects of your Level 9 Magnifistom monsters, the same issue of drawing the Level 2 Psychic Tuner and having to Normal Summon it (if you didn’t draw E-Tele) comes up again. 

For Spell/Traps: 2 Mystical Space Typhoon which is Spell/Trap removal in general and it is needed for certain Magnifistorm cards’ effects. 3 Magnifistorming Stanza Tribute, 1 Magnifistorming Summoning Tribute, and 3 Magnifistorming Sight Trance. Each of these are Quick-Play Spells that allow you to choose between 2 effects, both of which can be each used once per turn. Aside from their unique effect, their second effect allows you to add an MST from your Deck or GY to your hand. And, if they are destroyed by the effect of MST, they can be set back to the field. Stanza Tribute searches a Level 4 or lower Magnifistorm monster from Deck, Summoning Technique sends a Magnifistorm monster from your Deck to the GY, and Sight Trance allows you to draw 2 cards and then discard a Magnifistorm card or a Quick-Play Spell otherwise your entire hand is discarded. 3 Fire Formation - Tenki to search for Suen. 3 Tuning to search for Assault Synchron. 3 World Legacy Monstrosity which can either Special Summon a Level 9 monster from your hand or target a Level 9 monster you control to Special Summon 2 Level 9 monsters from your Deck with a different type and Attribute, but with different names. Finally, 3 Underworld Ritual of Prediction which can Ritual Summon a Prediction Princess Ritual Monster from hand or GY face-up or face-down and you can banish it from GY during the Standby Phase to Special Summon a non-Ritual Prediction Princess monster from Deck face-down.

Extra Deck: 1 Garura, Wings of Resonant Life and 1 Elder Entity N’tss. 1 Ib the World Chalice Justiciar which searches for a World Legacy card on Synchro Summon. 2 Herald of the Arc Light which adds a Ritual Monster or Ritual Spell from your Deck to your hand if it is sent to the GY. 1 Divine Arsenal AA-ZEUS - Sky Thunder. 2 Mereologic Aggregator. 1 Laevateinn, Generaider Boss of Shadows and 1 Jormungandr, Generaider Boss of Eternity. 1 Tri-Brigade Arms Bucephalus II. 1 Underworld Goddess of the Closed World. 1 S:P Little Knight and 1 I:P Masquerena. 1 Gravity Controller. 

Side Deck: 3 Mulcharmy Fuwalos, 3 Droll & Lock Bird. 3 Ultimate Slayer. 2 Forbidden Droplet. 1 Called by the Grave. 3 Evenly Matched.

deck_excerpt: Origami Goddess FTK ft. Gaap + Barrel + Buzzking
deck_description:
Greetings! In this deck, may luck be with you. You are going to need it.

 

 

Gameplan

1) At one point, use Ravenous to discard two of these three monsters: Origami + Gaap + Barrel. Then, after you have Link Summoned Saryuja, place ME-PSY-YA on Pendulum Zone and Special Summon Chaos Emperor Dragon with its ability to unlock "Primal Seed" loop.

2) Use Saryuja to pull out one of these three monsters explained in #1 and revive the other two with "Monster Reborn". Activate Barrel to pop anything but combo pieces and "Primal Seed" loop. Setting cards on backrow helps and try hitting a lot of heads to boost your Origami.

3) Reset Barrel with Book, so that Gaap lets you go on with your setup. When you think it's enough, give Origami to the opponent with "Shien's Spy" and revive Accel with "Monster Reborn".

4) XYZ Summon Buzzking with Chaos + Accel as materials. Use Buzzking to pop Origami and your opponent.

 

If you wonder how to save up some SR and UR points, I can show you:

- "Monster Reborn" can be earned for free by completing the tutorial to save 30 UR!

- "Pot of Avarice" can be collected by purchasing "Re-Contract Universe" deck. 90 SR saved and you can try a new deck!

- "Wonder Wand" and "Spellbook of Knowledge" can be collected by purchasing "Spellbook of Prophecy" deck. 120 SR saved and you can try a new deck!

- "Summoner Monk" can be found within "True Awakening of the Oathbound Knights" Secret Pack to save 90 SR!

- "Upstart Goblin" can be found within "Bonkers Bikers' Wild Wheels" Secret Pack to save 90 UR!

- "Into The Void" + "Allure of Darkness" can be found within "The Infinite Void" Secret Pack to save 180 SR!

- "Moray of Avarice" can be found within "Treasures of the Cosmic Ocean" Secret Pack to save 30 UR!

- "T.G. Hyper Librarian" can be found within "Futuristic Creatures" Secret Pack to save 30 UR!

- "Number 60: Dugares the Timeless" can be found within "Number Recall" Secret Pack to save 30 SR!

- "Pot of Acquistiveness" + "Ravenous" + "Gaap the Divine Soldier" + "Number 1: Infection Buzzking" + "Origami Goddess" + "Primal Seed" can be found within "Legacy Pack" to save 90 SR and 120 UR!

- "Formula Synchron" + "Accel Synchro Stardust Dragon" can be found within "Evoked Dragon of Miracles" Secret Pack to save 60 SR and 30 UR!

 

So, in total, you can save up to 660 SR and 330 UR, if you are willing to spend some gems. Other SR and UR cards I didn't mention are essential.

 

That's all for this one. If you have any questions, feel free to ask. Have fun in Master Duel!
