deck_excerpt: Lock your opponent out of their extra deck in a very rogue way!
deck_description:
The only card you need in your hand to kick off the combo is Allure Dance. Start by activating this and adding Allure Palace. (If Allure Palace is already in your hand, add either Allure Queen Lv3 or Lv7 for future combo steps.) Activate your Allure Palace and use its effect to discard a card to take an Allure Queen monster and either add it to your hand, or summon it to your opponent's field. 1st activation of effect: send 1 card to the GY to add Allure Queen Lv7 from your deck to your hand. 2nd activation: send Allure Queen Lv7 to GY to special summon Allure Queen Lv3 from your deck to your opponent's field. 3rd activation: send 1 more card to GY to add Allure Queen Lv3 from your deck to your hand. (Some of these steps can be skipped depending on your hand. You basically want to reach a point where you have Allure Queen Lv7 in your GY, one Allure Queen Lv3 on your opponent's field, and another in your hand, with both Allure Dance and Allure Palace on your field.)

Next, normal summon your Allure Queen Lv3, and activate its effect to equip the Allure Queen Lv3 on your opponent's field to it. Then, Allure Palace gives your Allure Queen monsters the ability to send themselves to the GY if they are equipped with equip cards, to special summon an Allure Queen monster from your deck. Send Allure Queen Lv3 to the GY to special summon Chaos Allure Queen from your deck. Use Chaos Allure Queen's effect to equip Allure Queen Lv3 from your GY to it, then special summon Allure Queen Lv5 from your deck. Link summon Protector Whelp of the Destruction Swordsman, using Chaos Allure Queen and Allure Queen Lv5 as material, and use its effect to send Dragon Buster Destruction Sword from your deck to your GY.

Now, use the effect of Allure Dance, sending Allure Palace to the GY, to special summon as many Allure Queen monsters with different names from your GY. This will be Allure Queen Lv3, Allure Queen Lv5, Allure Queen Lv7, and Chaos Allure Queen. Make sure to keep at least one of Protectoir Whelp of the Destruction Swordsman's link zones free, as you'll now Link summon Golden Allure Queen, using Allure Queen Lv3, Allure Queen Lv5, and Allure Queen Lv7 as material. On summon, use Golden Allure Queen's effect to special summon any one of your Allure Queen monsters from your GY. It doesn't matter which, as you'll be using it and Protector Whelp of the Destruction Swordsman to Link summon Moon of the Closed Heaven.

From here, you'll use Moon of the Closed Heaven to Link summon Fiendsmith's Requiem, and so on, and so on into whatever Fiendsmith combo you like.

What the Allure Queen bits will do for you is that during your opponent's standby phase, Golden Allure Queen allows you to use any Allure Queen monster effect to equip a monster as a (Quick Effect), so you activate Chaos Allure Queen's effect to equip a monster from your GY, targeting Dragon Buster Destruction Sword, which stops your opponent from summoning from their Extra Deck. Because Dragon Buster Destruction Sword is a DARK monster, you'll benefit from the second part of Chaos Allure Queen's effect to special summon an Allure Queen monster from your GY, where you'll choose Allure Queen Lv3. Thanks to Golden Allure Queen, you will be able to use Lv3's effect as a (Quick Effect) too, so if your opponent brings out a level 3 monster that you don't want them to have, you can equip it to your Allure Queen Lv3.

The benefit to using the Fiendsmith engine with the Allure Queen engine,is that lots of Fiendsmith cards like to be in the GY, and Allure Palace needs to discard cards for its effect. so even if you open with Fiendsmith in Paradise (which is normally a brick), as long as you have Allure Dance or Allure Palace, you can still make use of its GY effect.

Enjoy!
Skye Zaizen
Theodore Hamilton

deck_excerpt: Stronger than before, powered up for more
deck_description:
This is my first attempt at a Domain format deck and I wanted to go with my all time favorite archetype, Super Quants. Super Quantal Fairy Alphan alone is a one card Super Quantal Mech King Great Magnus  if not stopped, but you could feasibly have him, Zetan, or Blue as the Deck Master and all 3 are valid options. Alphan's domain is probably the weakest compared to the others since you're locked into Light/Fairy. Alternatively, Super Quantal Fairy Zetan would give access the Danger! archetype for discard effects, and Super Quantum Blue Layer would give Water/Psychic so you could use the Kashtira cards to boost rank 7 plays and they're own Xyz monsters too. That being said, both Blue and Zetan will rely on Alphan's effect to reveal 3, so I decided having Alphan as the DM would be most beneficial since he most likely will get banished at some point in the combo and be easier to recycle from the DMZ compared to the other two.
 
If you speedrun to Magnus, your main gameplay loop/combo will generally look something like this:
1. Normal summon Super Quantal Fairy Alphan 
2. Tribute Alphan (keep him in the GY) > reveal Super Quantum Red Layer , Super Quantum White Layer , and Super Quantum Black Layer  (if one target is in hand, reveal Super Quantum Green Layer ) > Special random, send others to GY, activate effects effects as following
3a. (Red Layer selected) Special summon Super Quantum Red Layer > activate Red on field and Black in GY > return White to hand, add Layer 19: "Preventing the Invasion! The Pitch-Black Super Quantum!!" to hand
3b. (White Layer selected) Special summon Super Quantum White Layer > activate Red and Black in GY > special Black to field, add Layer 19 > Xyz Super Quantal Mech Beast Lusterrex with White and Black
3c. (Black Layer selected) Special summon Super Quantum Black Layer > activate Red in GY, Black on field > Xyz Super Quantal Mech Beast Magnaliger or Lusterrex with Black and Red from GY depending on field (Magnaliger if target to destroy, Lusterrex if not) > detach Black to GY > add Layer 19 to hand.
4a. (If Super Quantum Green Layer is still in deck) Activate Layer 19, special Super Quantum Blue Layer > add Super Quantal Fairy Zetan  from Blue's effect > special summon Zetan > tribute Zetan, sending Super Quantal Alphan Spike to GY > special summon Green from deck > special summon White from hand if added back
4b. (If Green is no longer in deck) Activate Layer 19, special Zetan > tribute Zetan, send Alphan Spike to GY > special Blue from deck > add something to discard (most likely Super Quantal Alphancall Appeal )
5. Banish Alphan and Alphan Spike from GY > activate Super Quantal Mech Ship Magnacarrier from deck > discard to Xyz summon / extend with cards in hand for more material > send Magnacarrier to GY > special Super Quantal Mech King Great Magnus 
 
General Notes:
1. Magnus being at full power and preventing cards being added to hand may lead to you being archenemy, it may be better to bring him out with fewer materials to not draw aggro
2. Keeping the above in mind, depending on extenders in your hand it may be more benefical to link one of your Quants off into Neo Super Quantal Mech King Blaster Magna for extra draw power, and being able to double up on that effect with Heritage of the Light is a nice bonus if its available
3. Speaking of card advantage: Ebon Sun may keep you from having to discard something that may be useful later on, and being able to trigger it and return Metalfoes Fusion to hand, only to discard it again and then shuffle it back to +1 feels fantastic
4. While Magnus is one heck of a boss monster, obviously it's not unbeatable. The most effective way of taking it out is with Kaiju type effects, so adding in Mask of Restrict is an option depending on your playgroup
5. Additionally, if Magnus does get removed you'll float into 3 of the Mech Beasts from the GY, meaning you can potentially link two of them off into Moon of the Closed Heaven, then with her hopefully pointing to an opponents monster you can link her with the last mech beast into Underworld Goddess of the Closed World to take out two of your opponents monsters as well and leaving you with a 3k Link 5
6. Hollow Giants and Made to Order Mermaid Outfit Outfitter are both cards I want to include but are meta dependant so for now they're in the side deck / maybes

Category: Tournament Meta Decks (TCG)

Tournament Meta Decks are current-level Meta Decks that are capable of going up against the best of the best. These are curated lists that cannot be uploaded by regular users.

Creator: Windy Wen

Tournament: Adelaide State Championship 2025 – June 15th 2025

Placement: Top 8

Crystron received some new cards in SUDA and they are pretty much all custom, so here I am playing one of my favourite decks (also probably the one I played the most, thanks Duel Links...).

This build performs very well only if you take the time to properly learn the combos and how to play under Droll/Mulcharmy(s), Nibiru is not that much of a problem, but if I'm going first and I have starters I prefer Photon Lord as 5th summon.

Engines

Crystron

very standard stuff. Play Prasiortle.
Keep in mind that you can summon Sulfador from Sulfefnir to trigger the foolish 2 without locking yourself (and then resummon it from GY whith his effect).
It's very easy with this deck to mentally lock yourself to just the standars combos, but it's very important to learn to adapt and change your ways of playing. For example, you play 2 Eleskeletus for a reason, you rarely need to reborn itself with it's effect when you destroy it for Tristaros.
Smiger, Prasiortle and Thystvern CAN FLOAT INTO TUNERS, both Tristaros and Citree are valid enboard pieces.
Also Cluster is hands down the best card in the deck.


Kashtira

You could think about playing only 2 Unicorn and 1 Fenrir but I prefer 3 Unicorn for 2 reasons:

  1. I don't have a Fenrir :)
  2. Unicorn is still crazy good to chip away resources from your opponent's extra (or completely mess up their combos) and I really like searching the spell, since it basically give me a free body

 

Millennium

YOU COPIED FROM YACINE!!!!

Well, yes. It make a lot of sense and it's much cheaper than the Horus package.

Your best starter is Sengenjin since it's a one-card full combo, but none of the Millennium cards are bricks.
Starting with Sengenjin makes Photon Lord / Zombie Vapire as 4th summon (if you can't start your crystron engine make Zombie Vampire and mill), also leaving a body (Golem).
If you start with Unicorn and Sengenjin you special summon Unicorn first and search for the spell, then you go into Millennium combo and you'll have your rank 8 zyx, Golem and Unicorn on field. Link 2 into S:P and then revive the Unicorn.
It's pretty solid, also considering that you do not go under Bystials and you still have your Crystrons!


Extra

Not much to say here, Mechaba could be considered as a side tech for Nova, since not 100% of the players fear (or read...) Nova.
Dawn Dragster is stupid easy to make and Chambara is for OTKs, but sometimes it doubles in utilities by just being a lv 5. Samurai Destroyer doesn't come up very often, but keep in mind that Eleskeletus give -500 ATK/DEF to monsters on the other side of the field, this small but crucial detail is forgotten by a lot of players.


Side

This is what I'm working with right now, I'm thinking about removing Ultimate Slayer and Mereologic for something like TTT and Mechaba, but I still believe in US (probably copium).
Side pattern is preatty easy, Droplet and Ash are often replaceable.

Possible changes

If you have the Charmy(s) play them instead of Ash or instead of the Kashtira package. You could also consider Nibiru instead of Ash or in side, but if you are playing very budget I think this is the best HT lineup: Droll is a must, Ash stops Charmy(s) and Imperma is generally strong.

I'll try 1 Crossout with 2 Droplets, just to have slightly more chance to survive a Droll.

I don't think I have to point out how this is a deck for locals, not for big events.
You could theoretically strip out every other engine and make it super-duper budget, but I think this is a good compromise.

 

Open to suggestions, thank you for reading this far!

deck_description:
Honestly the deck is better going second, than it is going first. Test this deck into the 3 main decks coming into JUHU and you see how insane the deck can be on a power spell-like approach. Striker MD monsters work as normals, and lightning storm clears and or forces out interactions. Either way, helps you clear the backrow so you can ss MST names.


If made to go first, just get into feather storm, and it can be used from hand with the harpie or crothea, but you can also make a board as well. Evenly matched is a meta call for these decks, because aside from yummy, VS K9 and DT have no reponse to it; vs k9 can run therion king but often do not. Yummy can be hit and killed with evenly if you get past the arc light. These decks dont have the greatest time trying to rebuild their board into the MST cards after dismantled, and you have an easier time just ending the game a lot sooner than you usually would with this deck.

deck_excerpt: Voiceless Voice Dark Magician Azamina Herald
deck_description:
*RELINQUISHED IS ACTUALLY MIRACLE RAVEN*

Voiceless Voice is getting some help from the new ritual Support! The Azamina engine helps improve your board, and Illusion of Chaos helps you make the most of the continuous spells. 

Diviner puts in the most work in this build. Using Deception to tribute her from hand or field is always amazing for grabbing a free Lo, but if you don't see the Azamina engine, no problem! Diviner can now dump Herald of the Arc light for Miracle Raven, who can also tribute her.

Illusion of Chaos is the premier search after sending off Miracle Raven. Souls is great for sending off your spent Voiceless spells for draws, and most importantly- Vingolf's blessing. This makes yet another way you can trigger the spell's graveyard effect.

Finally, don't forget to make use of Cross Sheep. He's a great choice to make using your spare Mu Rcielago to shuffle back later. The deck is uniquely positioned to trigger two of Cross Sheep's best effects to reborn a 4 or lower and filter 2 cards.

deck_excerpt: Some people deserve a second chance.
deck_description: Are you lucky enough to win? Toss a coin to find out!

• If you wonder about the 2-ofs: Either they are at 2, or I want to minimize bricking on double Nib or drawing Mulcharmies after turn 1, etc.

• Main combo is White Aura ending on Bubble Reef (draw 1, banish Psiics), Dragite, Virtue Stream (+ usually Virtue Dragon as fodder), Psiics and Keaf in rotation.

• But there are many two-card combos, for example Mermaid Shark and Abyss Shark using Leaffish and Harpooner.

• I like the field spell (I wish it would be a starter on activation, but having it post-turn 3 is sooo nice). But again, if I see 2 in my opening hand, I will cry. There are decent combos with White Sardine, Mermaid Shark, Leaffish. Mainly a grid/comeback card if your GY is loaded.

• With 2 Sarc and 2 field spell, you get the essential Ghotis (the 4 that are not Keaf) into rotation easily enough that you never need more than one Arianpos, even if it gets negated.

• Yeah, no Paces – Shif is just better, and you really don't want to brick on all the 1-ofs. Speaking of, I feel that all included fishes are needed for some common situations. I guess it would be optimal to learn all the spreadsheet-style combos with all the possible combinations of 1-of cards etc. But you can just freestyle.

• Impuls is super good against so many things, so it’s an easy 3-of for me. Just keep an eye out for sequencing, since you get locked out of Nib and Fuwa. Only from hand, though!

• Mermaid Shark is (unfortunately) still better IMO than Big Jaws. Like yeah, sometimes you can special the guy (but that rarely happens since we don’t run that many spells), but then you get XYZ locked, so you can’t set up your Ghoti plays. Also, if you want to use that card properly, you kinda need to play Fish Poplar – but that card is about as good as White Sunfish (only works in a very limited number of settings and is a vanilla otherwise).

• 2 Askaan is also important. He is an interruption going first but also cleans boards going second. At least he has some redundancy (but only until Toxic Boxfish comes to MD – then I will change one of them out for it).

deck_name: Mimighoul Ghostrick - This Chest is Locked
deck_excerpt: Your opponent tries to open the treasure chests you have given them. Alas, the chests are locked, and they do not have the key.
deck_description:
Mimighoul Ghostrick's goal is to give your oppenent as many Mimighouls as possible and keep them face down with the use of Ghostrick Night. With the support of Mimighoul Room and Book of Moon, you can clog up your oppnents field till they run out of space to play. Then swaping out Mimighoul Dungeon with Ghostrick Mansion, you can beat over them with Ghostrick Angel of Mischief and burn for game with Giant Mimighoul.

Starting End Board

Ideally, you want to end with Mimighoul Dungeon onboard, with a Mimighoul Master and Mimighoul Throne, as well as at least one Ghostrick monster, usually a Ghostrick Angel of Mischief and Ghostrick Festival, and a Ghostrick Night set, with at least one set card on your oppenents field. The set card will keep your oppenent from normal summoning so long as Mimighoul Dungeon is in play, and Ghostrick Night will keep your oppenent from flipping it up to break the lock. Anything they special summon also wont be able to attack this turn due to Dungeon. Ghostrick Angel of Mischief, which you will get to by overlaying Dullahan, will get you Ghostrick Shot, which will get you Dullahan for another Angel of Mischief for Ghostrick Night. Then the empty Angel of Mischief is linked into Festival, mostly for the follow up the following turn.

Once your oppnenets turn ends, you can use Ghostrick Shot to get Dullahan back for your 3rd Angel, search for Ghostrick Mansion, and attack directly with your two Angels, and other Mimighouls if you can get Giant Mimighoul out. This usually wont kill, but if your oppnent has 3-4 set monsters on field, Giant Mimighoul can burn for game. Just be sure to blow up Ghostrick Manison with its effect to get the full damage.

If you get interupted too much, you can try ending on a board of Mimighoul Dungeon, with a set Mimighoul Fairy on your oppenents field, and may a search of a Mimighoul Room with Giant Mimighoul. It's not the ideal endboard, but it can interupt the flow of your oppenents play enough for the clap back on the next turn.

Combo Starters

Mimighoul Dragon

Dragon will get you Dungeon or Maker, two of your other playmakers for this deck. Depending on your hand, you might want to search one or the other, but resolving this uninterupted will usually get you to your ideal end board so long as you pilot the deck right. 

Mimighoul Dungeon

Your field spell that floodgates your oppnenets normal summon, and protects you from battle with special summoned monsters the turn they come out. Also gives a boost to your Mimighoul monsters the following turn, which is nice to try and protect them from getting beat over, but if all goes right, you wont have to worry about that.

Mimighoul Maker

A bit of a random searcher, if it is the only card you are starting with, you will most likely be searching Dragon and Archfiend, as regardless of the result, you will be able to combo off of them. If you have Dragon in hand or if you are just feeling lucky, Archfiend and Slime will be your go to, with a 50-50 chance your oppenent gets Slime, giving you a bunch of gas when you special summon Archfiend. Even if you get Slim in hand, you still special summon and can combo from there.

Generic Searchers

One for One

You will most likely be using this to get a Dragon or an Archfiend if you give your oppenent a Mimighoul so you can combo. Very handy card.

Jack-In-The-Hand

This one is very unreliable, but can be used in a pinch. Usually I select Dragon/Archfiend/Slime and so long as I have another Mimighoul Ghostrick's goal is to give your opponent as many Mimighouls as possible and keep them face down with the use of Ghostrick Night. With the support of Mimighoul Room and Book of Moon, you can clog up your opponents field till they run out of space to play. Then swapping out Mimighoul Dungeon with Ghostrick Mansion, you can beat over them with Ghostrick Angel of Mischief and burn for game with Giant Mimighoul.

Starting End Board

Ideally, you want to end with Mimighoul Dungeon onboard, with a Mimighoul Master and Mimighoul Throne, as well as at least one Ghostrick monster, usually a Ghostrick Angel of Mischief and Ghostrick Festival, and a Ghostrick Night set, with at least one set card on your opponents field. The set card will keep your opponent from normal summoning so long as Mimighoul Dungeon is in play, and Ghostrick Night will keep your opponent from flipping it up to break the lock. Anything they special summon also wont be able to attack this turn due to Dungeon. Ghostrick Angel of Mischief, which you will get to by overlaying Dullahan, will get you Ghostrick Shot, which will get you Dullahan for another Angel of Mischief for Ghostrick Night. Then the empty Angel of Mischief is linked into Festival, mostly for the follow up the following turn.

Once your opponents turn ends, you can use Ghostrick Shot to get Dullahan back for your 3rd Angel, search for Ghostrick Mansion, and attack directly with your two Angels, and other Mimighouls if you can get Giant Mimighoul out. This usually wont kill, but if your opponent has 3-4 set monsters on field, Giant Mimighoul can burn for game. Just be sure to blow up Ghostrick Mansion with its effect to get the full damage.

If you get interrupted too much, you can try ending on a board of Mimighoul Dungeon, with a set Mimighoul Fairy on your opponents field, and may a search of a Mimighoul Room with Giant Mimighoul. It's not the ideal end board, but it can interrupt the flow of your opponents play enough for the clap back on the next turn.

Combo Starters

Mimighoul Dragon

Dragon will get you Dungeon or Maker, two of your other play-makers for this deck. Depending on your hand, you might want to search one or the other, but resolving this uninterrupted will usually get you to your ideal end board so long as you pilot the deck right. 

Mimighoul Dungeon

Your field spell that floodgates your opponents normal summon, and protects you from battle with special summoned monsters the turn they come out. Also gives a boost to your Mimighoul monsters the following turn, which is nice to try and protect them from getting beat over, but if all goes right, you wont have to worry about that.

Mimighoul Maker

A bit of a random searcher, if it is the only card you are starting with, you will most likely be searching Dragon and Archfiend, as regardless of the result, you will be able to combo off of them. If you have Dragon in hand or if you are just feeling lucky, Archfiend and Slime will be your go to, with a 50-50 chance your opponent gets Slime, giving you a bunch of gas when you special summon Archfiend. Even if you get Slim in hand, you still special summon and can combo from there.

Generic Searchers

One for One

You will most likely be using this to get a Dragon or an Archfiend if you give your opponent a Mimighoul so you can combo. Very handy card.

Jack-In-The-Hand

This one is very unreliable, but can be used in a pinch. Usually I select Dragon/Archfiend/Slime and so long as I have another Mimighoul in hand, it doesn’t matter what my opponent picks. It's a very bad card if you open with 0 Mimighouls in hand other than Master though, which can happen. Better hope your opponent thinks your playing a mind game and lets you have Dragon if that is the case.

Triple Tactics Thrust

A little harder to pull off just on its own, Thrust is great for fetching Maker, One for One, or Tactics. If you can get Archfiend down while your opponent has a Mimighoul on their board, when that Mimighoul activates, it counts are their effect, meaning Tactics is now live. Or if they hand trap you with a monster, give them a Mimighoul and now you can add any Spell to your hand since they control a monster. 

Extenders

Mimighoul Armor

Can special summon to your side of the field if your opponent has a monster, which they should if you give them a Mimighoul with Maker or just raw summoning to their side. Run at one because it can be a brick.

Mimighoul Fairy

Your main archetypal extender. So long as you have any Mimighoul on field, she can special summon herself to your side. If you normal summon Dragon for Dungeon, this will most likely be your primary search target so you can combo.

Mimighoul Slime

This card can special summon itself to your side of the field if your opponent controls more monsters than you, which usually isn’t going to be the case, but the true beauty of this card is when you pair it with Maker. If you already have this in hand and you have a way to find Archfiend, send him out first before playing Maker. Even if you don’t have Archfiend in hand, send out Slime and then play Maker, and you have a 50-50 chance of bringing out Archfiend to your side of the field to flip Slime over, letting you search possibly a Dragon or Master.

Where Arf Thou?

You need to control a level one for this, but getting one on board with Maker or just normal summoning a Mimighoul is great to get you going. Searching Mimighoul Fairy is usually a safe bet, but any Mimighoul can be fine. More than likely you will be taking the 2000 damage at the end of the turn but this shouldn’t be an issue for a control deck like this.

Optional: Mimighoul Fork

Usually a sub-par choice, as it gives your oppenent the choice on what happens, but drawing two means you can find a proper starter potentially, or if they flip the card face up, it can potentially start your combo. Run at your own risk.

Interruption

Book of Moon

Great for setting going first, ensuring your Dungeon's protection from attacks stays active. Great for going second and flipping a problematic monster face down.

Mimighoul Room

Your in archetype Book of Moon. It's a trap so its slower, but the fact it can get you a Master while flipping your opponent’s monster face down, or if you have a Master you can give your opponent a Dragon so you can use Master to nuke their monsters, is great. The bounce is hand on the following turn if you need to reset your Dragon so you can combo again, or for protection from your opponents nukes.

Tech

Ghostrick Fairy

The only main deck Ghostrick, and one that can be hard to use. If you have Mimighoul Master and Ghostrick Festival on board, and your opponent manages to attack, Ghostrick Fairy can be brought out from deck. Master can flip her up on Main Phase 2, and you then can possibly flip your opponents monster face down and recycle a Ghostrick card. Or if you have her in hand, instead of going into Festival, you can Ghostrick Shot her onto the board, and the same idea applies. Very situational, but another Book of Moon isn't going to hurt.

Relinquished Anima

Since you are already playing a bunch of level ones, Relinquished is a solid choice for a monster. You can even force your opponent to play into it by playing your Mimighouls into the edges and center of the board when you special summon them. It can be hard to get rid of once you have it on board, but you can drop a Festival for an S:P Little Knight if that concerns you.

Weaknesses

Back Row Hate

Harpies Feather Duster, Lightning Storm, and anything that breaks Dungeon and Night will be your bane.

Tribute Fodder

Your opponent using your monsters as tributes for their monsters is a concern. It is not as bad if you have Dungeon out, as they will need to set their tribute, but ultimately it is dangerous. The worst is Forbidden Droplet, as that card basically becomes free with Mimighouls on board.

Fusion Summoning

Cards flipped face down cannot be used for Links, Syncho, or XYZ plays, but Fusion summons are fair game. If you Book of Moon or Mimighoul Room your opponent, be careful they can't be used as Fusion material. Yubel, Thunder Dragons, and Branded will be tougher to deal with because of this.

Notes

  • Mimighoul Master is immune to destruction if you control a Mimighoul or your opponent has a face down card. If you try to burn for game with Giant Mimighoul, do not select Master

  • Ghostrick Mansion will half your effect damage, so make sure Giant Mimighoul blows it up if you are going to burn for game.

  • Cards like Dominus Impulse lock your opponent out from activating Earth Monster effects. Meaning if you try to Flip a monster after they have activated it, nothing will happen.

deck_excerpt: Domain Format: Budget Structure Deck Transcendences
deck_description:
Be the Arbiter. Control the Game.
This is a beginner-friendly Domain Format list built upon a $9.99 MSRP purchase of the Structure Deck: Shaddoll Showdown. It consists of a $10 upgrade of cards purchased from sites like TCGplayer.

Deckmaster: Shaddoll Hedgehog 
Domain Restrictions: DARK // SPELLCASTER // SHADDOLL
Made for Domain Format: Join the Community Discord!

To create this upgrade, please remove these 10 cards and any duplicate cards from the SD: Shaddoll Showdown (reference the sidedeck): 
Note: El Shaddoll Winda and El Shaddoll Construct will have Alternate Arts in the Structure Deck

  • ydke://W8DiA4S4OAD796EEvMbOAcL1CAQr3iED80e6ATQC0AWwjAoDRIF3AklR+gByYEsAwed3Aa9eOwKMcRUC/vuWA++CFgDFqdoE1CccACbrAAQ3Z6UCquxhAF1p3gIj1p0CudZKANTDIwRaM2kEFl/XBIXhbAH+o54E4qxiBA==!GbN1BA7qJQHCwzYBtufiAjbJCAPgTGkE9TypBXSTLgU=!/7pZBOyPAQAD7o4CkZVcBGO0rwWEpBECPoQoBLpEdQMxkbQEQgDgBA==!
  • View on YGOprodeck
  • Structure Deck Full Contents (YGOprodeck)

Next, you will want to buy and add these 37 cards to the deck: 

  • ydke://CQZ9BcWM2wSp8rMFx2T5A8a7wAPrvhQESCmYA5Y+UgTxQEMCBy8+AvxvaQQWpDIE82fmApO/HgJy6u4Fg+ykAp3vdAMseLQA0AoVAmpIHgCYGscAvgovAoEyLQGBB2QEwZahA2SaQAEVtoYFCjRnAF4eSgL7mjED!tUwrBC5OdwKI5joF32mGAUiIswDc+GgBmlUSAg==!!
  • View on YGOprodeck
  • View on TCGplayer Cart

Additional Resources can be found here:
https://docs.google.com/spreadsheets/d/1c8_W7TLHoExz9Iq2yNBKG4kniKN3fjamfMVRehPRitQ/edit?usp=sharing

Domain Format General Rules:

  • Singleton Format: Every card restricted to 1 copy per deck.
  • 60-card Format: Each Main Deck must contain exactly 60 cards.
  • 4-player Pods: Each player competes individually in an all-out battle against three opponents.
  • Deckmaster Restrictions: Each player chooses a "Deckmaster" which dictates the allowed types and attributes for their deck.
  • Deckmaster Contract: A Deckmaster can be summoned from a designated "Deckmaster Zone" using normal summoning rules. After switching zones, Deckmasters may return to the "Deckmaster Zone," where they start the game.

Refer here for additional rules and exceptions:

https://www.domainformat.com/rules 

Broad Categories

This simple strategy has cards that fall into three simple categories:

  • GY Resource Loops
  • Extra Deck -> GY
  • Free Fusions

Primary Packages: Dogmatika, Shaddoll

Reccommend Shaddoll Guide (from tcgsam):

  • https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=2YxZjJcrk7U
  • https://youtu.be/xy2nQBnlWrE

What do we want our Deckmaster to do? Shaddoll Hedgehog 
- Shaddoll Domain
- Searches Shaddoll Spells or Traps on Flip
- Searches a Shaddoll monster if sent to GY by card effect

Shaddoll Hedgehog is not an optimal normal summon. However, its Dark Spellcaster Shaddoll domain allows us to access the varied attributed Shaddoll monster and its most important support archtypes. In a pinch, you can set Shaddoll Hedgehog in hope of flipping it face up to obtain access to powerful Shaddoll spell/traps on a following turn for engine access. You will likely want to add Reeshaddoll Wendi when using Shaddoll Hedgehog's GY effect, in order to gain more access into the Shaddoll Engine.   

El Shaddoll Construct is often the first Shaddoll you want to be summoning due to its ability to send a Shaddoll card to GY on summon and ability to fetch back a Shaddoll Spell or Trap when sent to GY. This allows you to find either utility or your Shaddoll Fusion.  El Shaddoll Construct does not have a once per turn on its effects, so reiving it with Naelshaddoll Ariel can be reuse its effects. In order to obtain a Light Monster for fusion material, you can link any Spellcaster (including the Deckmaster) into Artemis, the Magistus Moon Maiden. 

For boardbreaking, the best monster to summon is El Shaddoll Apkallone, which permentaly negates a card on summon. El Shaddoll Winda is the best shaddoll monster to pass the turn with due to its floodgate effect. 

The easiest way to send the Shaddoll Fusion monsters from Field to GY is by summoning them into the Extra Monster Zone and linking them into Gravity Controller. Or XYZ into Super Starslayer TY-PHON - Sky Crisis 

The easiest way to gain access to our Shaddoll Extra Deck is by fusing. While the Deckmaster Shaddoll Hedgehog can get access to the Shaddoll Fusion spells once flipped, doing so is quite slow. Instead, the deck plays a large variety of Fusion effects, the most notable and searchable of which is Blazing Cartesia, the Virtuous. Plese also note that Mathematician and Armageddon Knight can send Tearlaments Havnis into GY to activate it as a Fusion effect.

This deck will leverage powerful effects active when going second/third/fourth, notably Dogmatikamatrix and Shaddoll Fusion . Additional, this deck has powerful boardbreaking tools in Shaddoll Schism and Shaddoll Fusion  (for El Shaddoll Apkallone using Nehshaddoll Genius and  Naelshaddoll Ariel)

GY Resource Loop 
- Offers Interaction ( Nehshaddoll Genius )
- Triggers if Sent for Ritual or Fusion Summon ( Reeshaddoll Wendi ) or Trap Effect ( Subterror Succession )
- Deincentivize Removal ( Shaddoll Falco )

Shaddoll monsters have 2 effects each, one on Flip and one if sent to GY. If an opponent attacks into a facedown Shaddoll, it'll trigger the effect. If an opponent trys to destroy the Shaddoll, it'll trigger the effect too! Your opponent is put into a situation where they must let you get value out of your Shaddolls. Now what are these effects? 

Main Deck Shaddoll Monsters: 

  • Shaddoll Dragon
  • Nehshaddoll Genius  
  • Helshaddoll Hollow 
  • Naelshaddoll Ariel 
  • Shaddoll Hedgehog 
  • Shaddoll Squamata 
  • Shaddoll Falco 
  • Shaddoll Beast 
  • Shaddoll Hound 
  • Reeshaddoll Wendi 

Extra Deck Shaddoll Monsters: 

  • El Shaddoll Apkallone 
  • Other Shaddolls 

The deck's primary way to recur GY resources will be Shaddoll Falco and Naelshaddoll Ariel in addition to your Extra Deck Shaddoll GY effects. The Shaddoll monsters sent to GY effects can also be triggered through use of our Fusion and RItual Spells, using the Shaddoll as material. The most desirable monster to trigger the GY effects of is Reeshaddoll Wendi , which gets access into the other Shaddoll monsters from our deck. However, the other GY effects of Shaddolls offer amazing utililty and interaction. 

Each extra deck Shaddoll monster gets you access to a Shaddoll Spell or Trap if sent to the GY. Here are the targets: 

Shaddoll Spells/Traps:

  • Resh Shaddoll Incarnation 
  • El Shaddoll Fusion 
  • Shaddoll Fusion 
  • Nephe Shaddoll Fusion 
  • Shaddoll Schism 
  • Shaddoll Core 
  • Purushaddoll Aeon 

The most powerful Shaddoll Spell/Traps are Shaddoll Fusion and Shaddoll Schism , which are the cards you most want to obtain with El Shaddoll Apkallone. The primary card for resource looping is Resh Shaddoll Incarnation , which can revive a Shaddoll monster from our GY. The most efficient monster to revive will be El Shaddoll Construct , which can both send another Shaddoll to GY and also fetch the Resh Shaddoll Incarnation back to hand once it is sent to GY.

Another GY resource loop involves the Labrynth  monsters and thier favorable interaction with Subterror Succession .
Labrynth by themselves is a small package that can search Normal Traps through Lady Labrynth of the Silver Castle . By searching Subterror Succession and using its effect, we can both trigger our Shaddoll Monsters GY effects and find our other monsters from deck while also triggering the revival abilities of  Labrynth Stovie Torbie and Labrynth Chandraglier in the GY (because a monster was sent to GY by Trap effect). This becomes a continous stream of resources when Subterror Succession resets itself after use.

Extra Deck -> GY
- Trigger GY effects ( Branded in High Spirits )
- Access Engine ( El Shaddoll Apkallone )
- Interupt Combo Lines ( White Relic of Dogmatika )

When Shaddolls were made, the intention was for them to be Fusion Summoned, and have effects if they were sent to GY from field. However, in modern Yugioh we now have cards like Nadir Servant , Branded in High Spirits and Dogmatika Maximus which not only send them directly from the Extra Deck, they also give additional benefits! By sending the Shaddolls directly from our Extra Deck to GY, we shortcut the process and resources needed to use the GY effects of the Extra Deck Shaddoll Monsters. The most important of these effects is El Shaddoll Apkallone , which accesses our Shaddoll Spells and Trap from Deck. Recall that the most important Shaddoll Spells and Traps are Shaddoll Schism and Shaddoll Fusion. 

However, we also built this deck to utilize Dogmatika Maximus and White Relic of Dogmatika to disrupt our Opponents extra Deck. While we benefit from our Extra Deck being sent to GY, our opponents may not, especially if they have tight extra decks that they need for their combo plays. Meanwhile, we will use the GY effects of Shaddolls in conjunction with the GY effects of Titaniklad the Ash Dragon , Albion the Branded Dragon , and Alba-Lenatus the Abyss Dragon for advantage generation! 

To access the powerful Dogmatika monsters, we have a combination of Dogmatikamatrix and Dogmatika Ecclesia, the Virtuous. Another powerful Dogmatika of Note is Guiding Quem, the Virtuous , which can access our Blazing Cartesia, the Virtuous to access our Shaddoll Fusions. Each of these can be accessed through the GY effect of Titaniklad the Ash Dragon. 

Between El Shaddoll Winda and ripping cards out of the Extra Deck with Dogmatika Maximus and White Relic of Dogmatika, we will force our opponent to play a more lower-powered game.  

Free Fusions
- Cheat Resource Costs ( Mutiny in the Sky )
- Extend Past Interruption ( Shaddoll Fusion )

Fusion Spells are crimminal. Many of modern Fusion Spells no longer require monsters on Field or GY, which simply mean you can get Free Fusion Monsters and in some case also Free Monsters into GY to trigger their effects. Here are some examples that we play in this deck:

Fraudulent Fusion Spells:

  • Shaddoll Fusion 
  • Shaddoll Schism 
  • Branded Fusion 
  • Branded Banishment 
  • Mutiny in the Sky 
  • Magicalized Fusion 
  • Necro Fusion 
  • Super Polymerization 

With each of these Fusion Spells being able to direct access our Shaddoll Extra Deck (notably either El Shaddoll Construct or El Shaddoll Apkallone), we can ensure that even just a single card allows our deck to access our Engine. This allows the deck to extend and recover well against interruptions. Especially of note is how our Shaddoll monsters have GY effects, so if the Fusion summon goes through even if they remove and negate the Fusion Monster they will need to contend with the GY effects of Materials and the Fusion Monster. 

In the cases of Branded Fusion and Shaddoll Fusion that use material from deck, the materials itself can gain us advantage. For example, if boardbreaking, Naelshaddoll Ariel and Nehshaddoll Genius contribute GY vanishing and monster negation. Shaddolls work fabulously if allowed to be sent from Deck to GY.

The easiest Fusion Spells to search are the Shaddoll Fusion , Shaddoll Schism , and Branded Fusion.  

Gameplans

Endboard Pieces: El Shaddoll Winda , White Relic of Dogmatika 

Extend/Recover: Branded Fusion , Magicalized Fusion , Mutiny in the Sky , Shaddoll Fusion 
Backup Plan: Set Shaddoll Hedgehog , Labrynth 
Searchable Utility: Shaddoll Dragon , Nehshaddoll Genius , Naelshaddoll Ariel 
Grindgame: Resh Shaddoll Incarnation , Shaddoll Fusion GY effects 

Other Considerations: 

Extra Deck Monsters: Borreload Savage Dragon , Mirrorjade the Iceblade Dragon , Predaplant Dragostapelia , Sprind the Irondash Dragon , Guardian Chimera , Magistus Chorozo 
Monsters: Edge Imp Chain , Tearlaments Havnis , Danger!? Tsuchinoko? , The Iris Swordsoul , Incredible Ecclesia, the Virtuous , Springans Kitt 

Spells: Ultimate Slayer , Foolish Burial Goods 
Traps: Dogmatika Punishment , Gigantic Thundercross , Titanocider 

Removed From Deck:
Monsters: Aleister the Invoker , Invoked Caliga , Rilliona, the Magistus of Verre , Predaplant Ambulomelides , Predaplant Bufolicula , Predaplant Dragostapelia 
Spells: Extra-Foolish Burial , Magistus Invocation , Verre Magic - Lacrima of Light 

Recap: 

Important Cards: El Shaddoll Construct , Shaddoll Fusion , Shaddoll Schism 
Strategy Elevator Pitch: Outwit with recursion, overwhelm with fusion.

Recommened Upgrades: Granguignol the Dusk Dragon , Despian Luluwalilith , Deception of the Sinful Spoils 

Flip the script, fuse the shadows, and outplay with grave-born power.

deck_excerpt: Time Seal Lock ft. Junk Speeder
deck_description:
Welcome! It has been a while since I released a "Junk Speeder" deck. In that case, why not try locking down the opponent with recently unbanned card called "Time Seal"? Let's rev it up!

 

 

Gameplan

1) Place ME-PSY-YA on Pendulum Zone and Special Summon Chaos Emperor Dragon with its ability to unlock "Primal Seed" loop.

2) Use "Monster Reborn" to fill up your 3 x Main Monster Zones with Librarian + Junk Synchron + Jester/Boost. If you don't have enough, use Offerings to clean up.

3) Synchro Summon Trishula with monsters explained in #2 as materials. Use Trishula to banish whatever your opponent has and repeat it with De-Synchro until they have nothing to use.

4) Play Temple >>> Time Seal combo to not let your opponent draw anything. Meanwhile, use either Cardian or Offerings to not deck-out by accident and end your turn but not before setting "Primal Seed" to keep your loop.

5) Since your opponent has nothing to do, you can revive monsters with "Monster Reborn" and finish your opponent when it's your time. In case it's not enough, don't forget to use Offerings and Time Seal.

 

If you wonder how to save up some SR and UR points, I can show you:

- "Reinforcement of the Army" + "Monster Reborn" can be found by completing the tutorial to save 60 UR!

- "Flower Cardian Moonflowerviewing" can be found within "Hand of Fate" Secret Pack to save 30 SR!

- "Centur-Ion Legatia" can be found within "True Awakening of the Oathbound Knights" Secret Pack to save 30 UR!

- "Time Seal" can be found within "Battle of Destiny" Timed Pack to save 30 UR!

- "Temple of the Kings" can be either found within "The Ones Who Serve Ra" or "Guardian of Kings" Secret Packs to save 30 SR!

- "Junk Synchron" + "Ravenous" + "Primal Seed" can be found within "Legacy Pack" to save 120 SR and 60 UR!

deck_description: A (horribly done) attempt at a Folgo Domain deck.
Fun Hat pure Constellar deck, for play with friends

This is the most consistent synchron deck I've managed to come with in 16 years of building the same deck over and over.

It can often still brick, but you only need an adventurer card and jet synchron (searchable in many ways) to get the full combo started.

The point of this is to protect junk speeder's effect at all costs. You can negate an effect mid-combo with gryphon rider, play dark ruler no more or called by the grave.

Full combo:

Adventurer combo (summoning gryphon rider), jet synchron + token => Junk Speeder

Necro synchron effect: you increase junk speeder level by two. Jet synchron + Junk speeder => Crystal Wing

Crystal Wing + Stardust synchron => Crimson Dragon. You draw synchro world and activate it

Jet synchron effect, Jet synchron + Gryphon rider => Accel synchro sturdust, effect: Summon Jet synchron

Revolution + Accel => Psychic End Punisher   ;    Crimson dragon effect: Summon Shooting majestic star dragon   ;   Jet synchron + Psychic End Punisher => Crimson dragon (again)

Revolution effect: you summon it,  Stardust synchron effect: you tribute revolution to summon it (Stardust Trail follows, you increase it's level by one with Stardust illumination)

Necro synchron + Stardust Trail => Power Tool Dragon   ;   Power tool effect: you draw Living Fossil  ;  Activate Living fossil: you summon Revolution Synchron

Revolution + Power tool => Chengying  ;  (at this point you will have 12 counters on synchro world)  Synchro world effect: you summon Crystal Wing

(If you have activated at your mark you can use two counters on the field to draw 2)

In the opponent's standby phase you summon Majestic Star Dragon with Crimson Dragon effect

 

Final board: effect negate + destroy all opponent cards', effect negate, monster negate, Chengying

deck_excerpt: Fiendsmith voiceless voice but with purge
deck_description:
Always something I wanted to truly theory craft and make completely. But in the past, things were different. Now? I decided to give it a revisit. My take on fiendsmith voiceless voice.

The deck has its consistancies issues with dealing with certain handtraps, but you play around those with the other engine in the deck. The thought of using the bystials to get an extra body on board to continue combos and have the additional end phase add from Bystial Magnahamut was very tempting. But I then remembered that since Fiendsmith and Voiceless Voice archtypes are both lights, with the occansional D/D/D Wave High King ceaser (Being water). I figured that instead of using the bystial package, just discard it completely and use 3 copies of dominus purge. The chances of you needing to summon Wave High King are usually high against decks that summon alot of crap in a turn, but in a scenario where you only have purge in hand, alongside a copy of imperm? Its actually optimal. 

You make them unable to play the 1 of Triple Tactics talent and force them to play around the effectively Ash blossom and Effect Veiler without them being regarded as monster effects.

My final thoughts? I believe the deck has very good consistancy with both engines smashed in there together. The odd eyes package was optional, but its there because Pendulumgraph is a free body that provides a spell negate, alongside a free double add from GY.

 

If you have any thoughts regarding my opinion of my take of this deck? Do feel free to comment. I will read them.

Playing style

For the playing style, etymology, and other information, see Despia.

"Branded" is an archetype of primarily Spell and Trap Cards that support various cards related to "Fallen of Albaz" and Fusion Summoning. It also directly supports the "Despia" and "Bystial" archetypes:

  • Despia: "Branded Despia", also known as just "Branded", is a Fusion-based decktype that uses the "Branded" cards as playmakers, with the "Albaz" Fusion Monsters forming the Deck's primary resource loop. Cards in either archetype can search each other out.
  • Bystial: The "Bystials" are generally supported by the "Branded" Continuous Spells and Continuous Traps. "The Bystial Lubellion" and "Branded Beast" can place such cards directly from the Deck or GY respectively.

The primary ways of searching "Branded" Spell and Traps are "Aluber the Jester of Despia", "Springans Kitt" and "Albion the Branded Dragon". They can also be 'searched' by sending them to the GY via cards like "Albion the Shrouded Dragon" and "Bystial Saronir", then recovering them with "Branded Retribution" or "Despian Tragedy".

Each of the "Branded" Spells & Traps that debuted in Lightning Overdrive share an effect to Set themselves to the field at the End Phase if it is sent to the GY to activate the effect of "Fallen of Albaz". Similarly, other "Branded" Spells and Traps can recur themselves back to the hand when a Fusion Monster is sent to the GY (eg. "Branded in High Spirits" and "Brightest, Blazing, Branded King").

Finally, "Branded in Central Dogmatika" supports the Ritual-centric portion of "Dogmatika".

 

Playing style

"Fur Hire" is primarily a Swarm Deck that aims to quickly fill the field with monsters from the hand by using the shared effects of the low-Level monsters "Fur Hire" to Special Summon more monsters "Fur Hire", who can keep the Summoning going. As they do this, the low-Level monsters "Fur Hire" also trigger their unique Trigger Effects to maintain momentum. Since the monsters can only activate their effects once per turn, per name, it is necessary to play a large number and variety of low-Level monsters "Fur Hire". The last Special Summon will usually be a high-Level monster "Fur Hire", activating its Trigger Effect in addition to the protective effects it gives.

To address consistency, the most important monster "Fur Hire" is "Beat, Bladesman Fur Hire", whose Trigger Effect searches a monster "Fur Hire" to ensure the Summons can continue, followed by "Filo, Messenger Fur Hire", whose Trigger Effect revives a monster "Fur Hire" from the GY, granting resource recovery as an extender. Because there needs to be a monster "Fur Hire" on the field in order to start the Summons, the Deck can struggle if their first monster is removed from the field before it can activate its effect; Spell Cards that Special Summon can alleviate the pressure on their Normal Summon, such as "One for One" (for "Filo") or "Reasoning".

The Deck's boss monster is the Link-3 "Folgo, Justice Fur Hire", whose Link Material requirement of 3 monsters with different Types is relatively easy to meet within the archetype "Fur Hire" due to its diverse array of monster Types. Upon its Summon, it Special Summons a monster "Fur Hire" from the Deck with a different Type from the Link Materials used, replenishing some of the advantage used to Summon it, and its other effect draws cards if an opponent's card is destroyed, depending on how many monsters "Fur Hire" the player controls. This works especially well with a "Donpa, Marksman Fur Hire" or "Recon, Scout Fur Hire" on the field who have not yet used their Trigger Effects, since they can activate in response to the Link Summon of "Folgo".

The effects of all low-Level monsters "Fur Hire" can also be activated again during the opponent's turn, making cards that can Special Summon monsters "Fur Hire" during the opponent's turn to trigger them very valuable. These can include the in-archetype "Mayhem Fur Hire" and "Rookie Fur Hire", or out-of-archetype cards such as "Tri-Brigade Airborne Assault". This is especially important with "Donpa" or "Recon" on the field, to interrupt the opponent's plays and draw more cards with "Folgo". Also, as the archetype's swarming capability naturally lends it to Link Summoning, the Deck works well with non-archetypal staples such as the "Knightmare" monsters, "Borrel" monsters, "Accesscode Talker", and "Saryuja Skull Dread".

Because there are several Beast, Beast-Warrior and Winged Beast monsters "Fur Hire", with "Donpa" and "Recon" in particular being Level 2 Beast monsters, the archetype works well with cards and themes that support those Types, such as "Tri-Brigade" and "Melffy". Also, a small Sacred Beast engine can consistently Summon "Folgo" off a 1-card starter.

Due to already running a large number number of monsters, it is also possible to play a pure monster variant Deck. This type of Deck "Fur Hire", can be supplemented with staple monsters such as "Dinowrestler Pankratops", hand traps like the Yo-kai Girls, and a few Spells like "Sekka's Light" or "The Big Cattle Drive".

Need: 

- 3x Ecclesia, the Virtuous

- 2x Emergency

- 3x Imperm

- Triple Tactics

This is a Snake-Eyes deck that can go first OR second and still perform just as well.

This is very much imperfect and in progress. I've taken this to diamond, so it's vaguely playable? I essentially tried shoving as many engines as possible to facilitate the summon of the man himself, Big Gabonga. Materiactor is very much the best of these, Exagard being made first should always allow another rank 3, sometimes grabbing the counter trap in the process. Also, Exareptor (and Foxy Tune) are good for putting the annoying cards to draw into the grave while extending. Essentially the game plan is to push through whatever your opponent has through sheer amount of gas. Ideally by using Terrortop and Emergency Teleport, you can get through your opponent's interruptions before you use your normal summon.

I used to run Bamboozling Gossip Shadow to insulate against nib, but most hands are not so fortunate to be able to do that so I cut it. Ideally, you just play through the nib. Droll hurts the deck really bad and ofc maxx C will just end your turn if it goes through. The Materiactor counter trap IS the only spell/trap negate you have, so it's usually worth it to go for that over the Exaraptor bounce- this also means making Exapgard without any Materiactor material is fine. I've added the utopic future cards more recently, and to be honest, I'm still learning how to incoporate them fully.

deck_excerpt: Silent shadows strike, Face-down foes in trembling fear, Victory unseen.
deck_description:
Ninja's are a fun archetype and this is a Pure Ninja Control deck focused on flip disruption, board manipulation, and tempo advantage. Using a mix of old and new Ninja support, this build capitalizes on the strength of Meizen Hayabusa (I know he's not a Hayabusa) to grant your monsters direct attacks and disrupt enemy strategies by flipping threats face-down mid-turn. 

The deck thrives on setting the pace early with Hanzo or Tobari, transitioning into Saizo setups that tutor key Ninjitsu Art cards like Dancing Leaves or Notebook of Mystery. Hand traps like Ash Blossom and Veiler help keep opposing combo decks in check, while your trap lineup provides ongoing field control.

Meizen, backed by cards like Geo and Baku a, provides both offensive pressure and defensive options. The Extra Deck offers tech tools like Bagooska, Abyss Dweller, and Apollousa to match various threats, while the Side Deck is tuned for going second and handling backrow-heavy or graveyard-reliant matchups. I used to run Apollousa and Abyss Dweller but they are currently on the list.

High consistency with small world + tachyon [swap out post side into droll].  Deck bridge with small world + 18 hand traps.  If you get drolled you can end on bagooska with 1-3 handtraps to force your opponent into a half board.

Starting hand if you have no names you usually search Ice for most flexibility.  After resolving tachyon or small world - if your opponent drolls you, you can access star + cross, if they chain fuwaloss to your normal summon of Ice, you can summon sword add ext and make bagooska. 

The deck is a mid-range tool box deck.  Well situated list with strong matchup into Mitsu Ryzeal, Orcust, and rogue.  Maliss matchup is fair.

deck_excerpt: Testing deck for potential Nats Deck - Locals gameplay to be posted on Friday
deck_description: Testing deck for potential Nats Deck - Locals gameplay to be posted on Friday

Big thank you to Krawch for giving me the idea for making this Deck.

If I haven’t said this about Prediction Princess already, the Deck knows what it wants to end on, but it has almost no way of actually getting there. That is why I have been experimenting with incorporating all sorts of different archetypes, especially ones that include a Level 9 monster or can facilitate one in order to see if I can frankenstein a good Prediction Princess Deck. If anything, the archetype literally just needs a Spell that says ‘Add 1 “Prediction Princess” monster or 1 “Prediction” Ritual Spell from your Deck to your hand’ and it will be much more capable of accessing its plays a whole lot more often. While this hypothetical card is still just a figment of my imagination, Miracle Raven is a very good card for facilitating the closest thing to a “pure” Prediction Princess Deck. Miracle Raven is a Level 1 Ritual Pendulum Monster whose Pendulum Effect allows you to Ritual Summon it (from your Pendulum Zone) by Tributing monsters from hand/field whose total Levels equal or exceed 1. Its monster effect allows it to fulfill an entire Ritual requirement for a Ritual Summon that uses monsters while you control it. Also, if it is Tributed for a Ritual Summon, you can add a Ritual Monster from your Deck to your hand. Sure, Prediction Princess can’t make insane use of this card like archetypes like Megalith (with their new support) and Voiceless Voice (since Diviner sending Herald, Herald search Raven, Scale Raven, Ritual Summon Raven Tributing Herald, Herald summoning Lo is bonkers crazy), but Ritual Raven can essentially replace the need for using Prediction Princess Bibliomuse when Ritual Summoning Prediction Princess monsters. 

Let’s imagine a combo: You have Prediction Princess Tarotrei and Underworld Ritual of Prediction in hand and you control a Ritual Summoned Miracle Raven. Activate Underworld Ritual, Tributing Miracle Raven as the whole Tribute, to Ritual Summon Tarotrei. Miracle Raven, upon being Tributed for a Ritual Summon, searches for Prediction Princess Tarotreith. During your End Phase, Tarotrei activates to Special Summon Tarotreith from your hand face-down. During your opponent’s Standby Phase, you can banish Underworld Ritual from GY to Special Summon Prediction Princess Bibliomuse from Deck and chain Tarotrei’s effect to flip Tarotreith face-up. On a new chain, Tarotreith’s Flip Effect triggers to Special Summon Deus-X Krawler from Deck. Tarotreith can then Quick Effect flip both Bibliomuse and Deus-X face-up. Deus-X negates all activated monster effects on your opponent’s side of the field while Bibliomuse’s Flip Effect triggers to search a Tarotrei and another Underworld Ritual for follow-up while also providing your Ritual Monsters targeting and destruction protection. So in situations where you do not have Bibliomuse access, but you do have Miracle Raven access, you can still pretty much achieve full Prediction Princess combo. Is this Deck good? For a pure Prediction Princess Deck, this is much much much better than what pure Prediction Princess looked post DABL when its support came out. The cards that I have chosen to play do their absolute best to produce hands that end on some semblance of the Prediction Princess endboard. Is this beating say Runick Prediction Princess or Blue-Eyes Prediction Princess? Definitely NOT, but this is still as good as pure is going to get at this point in time. 

For the Main Deck Monsters: 3 Prediction Princess Tarotrei, 1 Prediction Princess Tarotreith, and 3 Prediction Princess Bibliomuse. Tarotrei can Quick Effect flip a monster on field face-up or face-down and she can Special Summon a Flip Monster from hand or GY face-down during your End Phase. Tarotreith must either be Ritual Summoned or Special Summoned via Tarotrei's effect in the End Phase. Her Flip Effect Special Summons a Flip Monster from your Deck face-down and she can also Quick Effect flip any number of your monsters face-up or face-down. Bibliomuse can Special Summon herself back face-down after being Tributed and sent there. Her Flip Effect adds a Prediction Princess monster other than herself and a Ritual Spell from Deck to hand and while she is face-up on the field, your Ritual Monsters gain targeting and destruction protection from your opponent’s card effects. 1 Deus-X Krawler which negates all activated monster effects on your opponent's side of the field after it has been flipped face-up and if it is destroyed on field, you can search for a Level 9 monster with a different Type and Attribute. 1 Whirlwind Weasel whose Flip Effect makes it so that your opponent cannot activate any Spell or Trap Cards for the rest of the turn. You can also play Guard Dog alongside Whirlwind Weasel or you can play it over Weasel. But where is Pot of the Forbidden you ask? You can still play Pot, but in the event that you open Deus-X and are not playing a second copy in Deck (which you could if you wanted to), if you want to make full use of both Underworld Ritual’s GY effect and the Tarotreith in hand rather than just using Tarotrei’s effect to Special Summon Deus-X from hand, you can choose to play either Guard Dog or Whirlwind Weasel to Special Summon off of Tarotreith’s Flip Effect. Guard Dog and Whirlwind Weasel’s Flip Effects have the potential to just end your opponent’s turn. And because you have Tarotreith on field, it can also flip Bibliomuse face-up to give protection and search follow-up. Now imagine if you wanted both protection and follow-up with Bibliomuse off of Underworld Ritual, but you played Pot instead of Guard Dog, Whirlwind Weasel, or a second Deus-X. What is 1 hand-rip going to do by itself if your opponent opens multiple starters? What is Quick Effect Raigeki or Giant Trunade that activates on a following chain going to do without a Deus-X to support it? It’s really your choice if you want to play Pot or one of the alternatives I listed. 1 Cyber Angel Benten. It searches a LIGHT Fairy if Tributed and it is basically another search target for the Preparation of Rites that we are playing and it can search Tarotrei. 1 Miracle Raven. You pretty much only need the 1 copy. Also, just keep in mind that you can Tribute your Prediction Princess Ritual Monsters to Ritual Summon Miracle Raven if you have access to Underworld Ritual since it can also Ritual Summon from GY. 3 Diviner of the Herald. On Normal or Special Summon, it can send a Fairy from Deck or Extra Deck to GY and increase its own Level by the Level of the sent monster. If it is Tributed, you can Special Summon a Level 2 or lower Fairy from your hand or Deck except for Diviner. Diviner is just good in general for most Ritual Decks since it can send Herald of the Arc Light to search a Ritual Spell or Ritual Monster. It is a shame that we aren’t playing any targets for its second effect, but this effect doesn’t really benefit us much in this Deck. Finally, 3 Ash Blossom & Joyous Spring and 3 Droll & Lock Bird. 

For Spell/Traps: 2 Pre-Preparation of Rites which searches a Ritual Spell from Deck and a Ritual Monster that is mentioned on that Ritual Spell from your Deck or GY. 2 Prediction Ritual which specially only can be used to Ritual Summon Prediction Princess Tarotrei and you can banish it from GY except the turn it was sent there to search a Prediction Princess monster. 3 Underworld Ritual of Prediction which can Ritual Summon a Prediction Princess Ritual Monster from hand or GY face-up or face-down and you can banish it from GY during the Standby Phase to Special Summon a non-Ritual Prediction Princess monster from Deck face-down. The combo I described with Miracle Raven is best done with Underworld Ritual as it can Special Summon Prediction Princess Bibliomuse from your Deck during your opponent’s Standby Phase whose Flip Effect can search follow-up while also providing protection while face-up on field. Ritual Summoning Tarotrei using Prediction Ritual and Tributing Miracle Raven does not give you Bibliomuse access for searching follow-up or protection. So why are we playing Prediction Ritual and Pre-Prep? Pre-Prep gives us both Tarotrei and a Ritual Spell to Ritual Summon it which, alongside Miracle Raven (given you did not draw Bibliomuse) still gives you basically almost the entire Prediction Princess endboard, specifically the most important part of it: Deus-X Krawler. It’s still better than ending with nothing. 3 Readying of Rites which adds a Fiend Ritual Monster from Deck to hand and if you added a Pendulum Monster, you can Special Summon a Sacrificial Offering Token which is basically a Level 1 Token intended to be used as Tribute to Ritual Summon Miracle Raven. However, while you control that Token, you cannot Special Summon from the Extra Deck which is not an issue. And when your Ritual Monster inflicts battle damage to your opponent, you can banish Readying of Rites from GY to draw a card. This card just facilitates Miracle Raven which is really good and all that it needs to do. 3 Preparation of Rites. This searches a Level 7 or lower Ritual Monster from Deck and then can add a Ritual Spell from GY to hand. This searches for either Miracle Raven or Benten in this Deck, and more importantly, it is not once per turn. So, in the case where you draw multiple copies, you can access both Miracle Raven and Benten to get more Prediction Princess Ritual Monsters into your hand. 1 Called by the Grave. 3 Pot of Extravagance and 1 Pot of Prosperity. Gotta have additional consistency from somewhere. And finally, 3 Infinite Impermanence. 

Extra Deck: 1 Elder Entity N’tss which, if sent to GY, can target and destroy a card on field. In the instance where you have an additional Diviner in hand for a following turn, you can use its effect to send N’tss for a pop. 3 Herald of the Arc Light which adds a Ritual Spell or Ritual Monster from Deck to hand if sent to GY. We are playing 3 copies because I really do not want to banish this card off of Extravagance because I really need to send it off of Diviner if I am able to do so. 1 Divine Arsenal AA-ZEUS - Sky Thunder and 1 Super Starslayer TY-PHON - Sky Crisis. 2 Infinitrack Earth Slicer and 1 Laevateinn, Generaider Boss of Shadows and 1 Jormungandr, Generaider Boss of Eternity. For Extravagance purposes, I am choosing to play 2 Earth Slicer because it is good for removal on a following turn and it doesn’t require another card like Laevateinn does. If I choose to play multiples of Laevateinn and Jormungandr, that is a waste of Extra Deck space first of all, but there is still the chance of banishing all of my Laevateinns or all of my Jormungandrs which effectively makes them useless. 2 S:P Little Knight. 1 Dyna Mondo. And 1 Salamangreat Almiraj if I need to Link off Diviner. 

Side Deck: 3 Nibiru, the Primal Being, 3 Mulcharmy Fuwalos, 3 Mulcharmy Purulia, 2 Lightning Storm, 1 Harpie’s Feather Duster, and 3 Solemn Judgment.
Just some old cards put together for fun with friends

deck_description: There is a lot going on here. I took some inspiration from Brakrom Lord's decklist (mainly for one combo). I have very little time, so it shall be mentioned in depth later.

Essentially, you're adding Machine of the Closed Heaven (Booster) so you can make Machinesmith's Desirae (Booster pointing at an arm w/ Funk Dock) as either an additional endboard piece, or as a backup plan if you get handtrapped too much. Best case, you can end on Infinity + Tristaros + Cluster + Dragster + Booster/Dock/Arm, but that's a ~3 card combo. It's also not awful to open RB, fire a Rocket as a boardbreaker/interaction bait, and then still get full Crystron after (eg: Special Limb > Normal Smiger > Link Booster add Dock > Dock add Rocket > Rocket inherent summon > Rocket effect > Dock summon > Banish Smiger to add Inclusion > Play normally).

The basic endboard combo to add RB requires summoning Prasiortle somehow, and having any Crystron monster in hand (added by Eleskeletus, Thystvern):

Summon Prasiortle > link Clockwork Knight > Prasiortle summon from hand > Link 2 Booster w/ Clockwork + Crystron > add Dock > Dock, add Driller/Cutter > Booster effect, summon from hand.

----

Unfortunately, they haven't printed Machinesmith's Requiem yet, so none of the RB parts are starters on their own, but Driller and Rocket are viable for 2-card combos into full Crystron, whereas Cutter can only 2-card into Booster/Brute unless you run Hi-Speedroid Kendama or something (Powered Inzektron doesn't work, Tristaros can't pop it).

R.B. Stage Landing is 0-1 in this deck because the lock makes it a brick in most hands, but it's still worth considering as a 1-of because on its own it's a 1-card RB combo, and also turns Dock into a 1-card combo. I've also tried fitting 1 more copy of Rocket (it's a better 2-card than Driller) but haven't managed to justify it yet.
GRANDPA’S UNSTOPPABLE EXODIA Deck

deck_excerpt: It's Albaz's turn to get anime lore episodes! Time to test out the strategy vs. TCG meta!
deck_description:
Sky Striker lore episodes are done, and it's Albaz's turn to get anime lore episodes! It is time for fusion enthusiasts everywhere to celebrate by continuing to play Branded! As it turns out in my testing (and personal experience at Locals), Branded is still very viable vs. the current TCG meta! Mainstream meta decks like Mitsurugi, Ryzeal and Maliss interrupt with destruction or banishes, something that Albaz and friends easily shrug off! That means that Branded can out-resource in an extended grindgame, power through established boards and make a ton of interruptions going first! Common meta staples like Droll are ignored by the strategy, and opening hands often have enough gas to keep on playing. 

This build of Branded uses 60 cards since it is incredibly consistent and has multiple 1-card and 2+ card combos. Relevant Mulcharmies are maindecked since they offer more draw power and stop the opponent from playing too much, but if they're dead in the hand they can be discarded as part of your combos. Making a deck around Grass is incredible. If you resolve the card, you basically win the game!

Shoutout to MetaGamesGX for his excellent guide on Branded and for being the main inspiration behind this particular build! Feel free to watch his video guide on Branded by clicking here! 

Also, if you want to read my article and combo guide on Branded, click here!

GLHF Duelists!

Want to see the deck in action? Scroll to the very bottom for the Youtube video!

deck_name: Master Duel - Ninja Flip Destroying Deck Yugioh 2025 Tutorial
deck_description:
This video showcases the Ninja Deck Combo with Flip Monsters in Yu-Gi-Oh! Master Duel, using the April 2025 Banlist format. There are two main strategies demonstrated in the gameplay:

1. Stalling & Defense Strategy

Focusing on slowing down the opponent's game and gradually depleting their deck. This is done by shutting down the opponent's monsters and maintaining a defensive position.

2. Direct Attack Strategy

Using effects from the Ninja Archetype to attack directly while filling the opponent's field with face-down monsters that cannot be destroyed or flipped, creating constant pressure.

This deck is flexible and can be adjusted according to the duel situation. If you're interested, you can check out the video directly on Youtube: Ninja Flip Destroying Deck Yugioh 2025

deck_excerpt: Don't rely on what you can do here
deck_description:
What you do here doesn't matter, only what God has done in you and what He can do in others. Let His Spirit give you the Victory!

These Christian tips should help explain the rules:

Basic Yu-Gi-Oh strategy is revealing what your chosen characters are doing as they interact with the space around them. For instance, the strategy of Zefras is encouraging others to trust in the salvation of God's Word due to the angels God sends through the power of His Word and His Spirit. So you would add cards that would support that notion of trust like Grand Horn of Heaven, or Recall, or Solemn Warning. You could also add cards that are trusting in the angels of the Lord to do what they do; like Symphonic Warrior Rockks, or Seraphnite, or Proxy F Magician, or Zefra Metaltron.

On the other hand, Gravekeepers' strategy is about including others in the participation of anticipating the promise of our eternal lives in Heaven. So you would add cards that would support that notion of including others. Cards like, Book of Eclipse, the Selection, Cup of Ace, Present Card. You could also include cards that support trusting in God's promise of eternal life through Heaven like Desert Sunlight, Blessings of the Nile, Imperial Tombs of Necrovalley, Necrovalley, Stelle, Grand Horn of Heaven, Kahyo-rai-getsu, Flash Fusion, Kuribohrn, and Master Peace, or Metaltron 12.

On the contrary, the strategy of something like Archfiends would be trying to get others to believe in their gained abilities by trusting in what they earned for themselves by relying on satan. So cards that focus on selfishness or what satan can give would probably be ideal. Cards like Solemn Strike, Ash Blossom and Joyous Spring, or Sakuretsu Armor.

A card's Attack or Defense is the willingness of the card to share what God has given to it. Either its' willingness to give to others (attack) or its' willingness to accept what others share (defense). Sometimes these stats can be increased or decreased as they trust in other things instead of what is just given to them personally. Either by trusting in what God is doing in others or believing in other things that God has done. Or by trusting in what satan does or what it can do to others.

Cost is simply acknowledging that players cannot abuse their cards thus accepting how the cards are interacting with each other since the cards wouldn't take back believing in what a card does or trusting in what a fellow teammate could accomplish.

Star/Star Level is how the card is connected to the Word (Christ). This allows other cards to trust in how others are connected to the Word. For instance, with Synchro summoning cards who are connected to the Word differently (having different levels) can trust in the abilities of someone else who is connected to the Word in a different way than them. When Xyz summoning, cards can trust in the abilities of someone who is connected to the Word in the same way as them. When fusion summoning, cards trust in the abilities of someone else based on how they are connected to that other individual. This is independent of their level or how they're connected to the Word or Christ. Because Link monsters are supposed to be trusting in the connection to the Word via their Spirit, they don't have levels. When Pendulum Summoning, cards can also trust in other cards' connection to Christ by having faith in God. Tribute summoning is simply when the cards have faith in what another card can do and isn't really dependant on their connection the Word.
